<1ST_LINE>r a AM-School-FoodPoisoning     03-30 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School-Food Poisoning,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 75 Elementary Schoolchildren Sent To Hospital For Food
Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELLIJAY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food poisoning, possibly from fresh turkey
fixed for lunch Wednesday, sent at least 75 Ellijay Elementary
School pupils to an overflowing hospital Wednesday night.
   North Georgia Medical Center Administrator John Downs said 24
pupils, mostly kindergartners through second graders, and one
teacher were admitted for treatment of stomach cramps and
dehydration brought on by vomiting. Other pupils were being treated
and sent home.
   ``It's not a serious thing. It just requires monitoring,'' he
said. ``Most are on intravenous feeding to replace the fluids they
lost. We're listing it as gastritis due to food poisoning.''
   Downs said the 50-bed hospital already had about 40 patients
when the schoolchildren started coming in Wednesday afternoon.
   ``We've got them in the chapel and various treatment rooms,'' he
said. ``We haven't had to use the halls yet, but we have beds
available for that if we need it.''
   If more pupils come in and are admitted, he added, ``we'll
probably have to send some to other hospitals.''
   Gilmer County School Superintendent J. Homer Hefner said the
food poisoning apparently hit two classes the hardest and also
struck some children from a few other classes at the 619-pupil
school.
   Lunch Wednesday was fresh turkey and dressing, green beans and
potatoes.
   Downs said doctors suspected the turkey caused the illness. The
turkey that remained after the meal was finished would be tested at
a medical laboratory Thursday, he said.
   ``I talked to the luncheon person and reviewed how they thawed
and prepared the turkey and I saw nothing wrong with how they did
it,'' Hefner said, adding that he has asked the state Department of
Education's food services division to help with his investigation
into the problem.
</TEXT>
