<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APArts:Oscar-Origins     03-30 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Oscar-Origins,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: A Statuette Is Born</HEAD>
<HEAD>Real Star of Glittering Awards Has Down-to-Earth Beginnings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The origins of the Oscar, a golden symbol of
artistic triumph, are more down to earth than many of the glitzy
stars who take home the greatly cherished statuette.
   Far from the studios, sun and sea of the California West Coast,
is a cluster of brick buildings in a residential-industrial
neighborhood of Chicago. Under a cloak of security, this is where
the trophy manufacturer R.S. Owens & Co. creates the Academy Award
prize.
   Winning the Oscar contract may not compare with winning the
Oscar itself. However, it was a coup for Owens seven years ago and
remains a source of company pride. The statuettes used to be made
by Dodge, Inc., at a small manufacturing plant in Crystal Lake,
Ill., some 25 miles northwest of Chicago.
   With 300 employees, Owens makes about 95 percent of the most
prestigious awards in the country, including the television
industry's Emmys, advertising's Clios, the Super Bowl trophy and
the Miss America awards. But Oscar tops them all.
   Most people don't know the names of awards in other fields, much
less what they look like, said Bernice Estka, who handles the Oscar
account for Owens.
   ``Oscar, you know,'' she said.
   Each model of the muscular knight, who holds a sword and stands
impassively on a reel of film, is hand cast from a single steel
mold.
   Oscar was designed by Cedric Gibbons, then head of the MGM
studio's art department. He sketched the prototype on a table cloth
in 1927. Sculptor George Stanley transformed the sketch into the
coveted statuette.
   The trophy was named Oscar by longtime Academy employee Margaret
Herrick, who took one look at the statuette and declared that it
reminded her of her Uncle Oscar, Estka said.
   The design has remained unchanged since 1927, and the mold,
which was turned over to Owens with the contract, is kept in a
vault.
   Neither Owens nor the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts &
Sciences, whose members' votes decide the winners, would reveal the
price tag on Oscar.
   ``I like to say that they are worth a million dollars to the
people who receive them,'' said Owen R. Siegel, founder and chief
executive officer of the trophy company. ``Once you have got an
Oscar _ you've made it.''
   ``If we say it only costs a certain amount to make, what does
that do to the image?'' said Patrick Stockstill, the Academy
historian who will hand the Oscars to presenters at the 60th annual
awards presentation on April 11.
   ``It is the most famous award and the most prestigious. It
thrusts a person into the limelight and brings additional cash into
their pockets.''
   The Oscar's value as a symbol far exceeds the cost of the pewter
form and electroplating of copper, nickel, silver and gold, Estka
said. However, from 1943-47, because of war rationing, the
statuettes were made of plaster. They were later replaced.
   Early each year, nine or 10 Owens employees set aside the work
of the moment such as Little League trophies or bowling prizes to
make the Oscars. Each 13{-inch, 8{-pound statuette takes about five
man hours to craft, Estka said.
   The awards are handcrafted in the 100,000 square-foot facility
with cinderblock walls whose concrete floors often are shrewn with
metal shavings.
   The academy usually needs about 100 Oscars, but this year's
order was for 150 because of the Academy is celebrating its 60th
anniversary, Estka said.
   The Oscars are locked in a separate room each night. As each
statuette is finished, it is packed in plastic foam. When all are
ready, they're put in a sealed truck for the trip to Los Angeles.
   ``We don't have an elaborate secret route, but only a few people
actually know when they leave or how they go to Los Angeles,'' said
Scott Siegel, president of the company.
   Once in a secret Los Angeles warehouse, the Oscars wait in
muffled silence for the night they make dreams come true.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
