<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AppleSuit     03-30 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Apple Suit,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit: Student Paralyzed By Apple Injury During Food Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a teen-ager has filed a $5 million
lawsuit charging that her son was paralyzed by injuries suffered
when he was hit by an apple during a cafeteria food fight, an
attorney said.
   Francisco Beltran, 14, of the Bronx was ``minding his own
business'' as he ate lunch Oct. 23 at Junior High School 143 while
a food fight went on around him for 15 or 20 minutes, attorney
Kevin Concagh said Tuesday.
   ``One fellow threw an apple at somebody and missed who he was
throwing it at and hit Francisco in the back of the head,'' Concagh
said. ``It hit him very hard and then the apple shattered into
pieces.''
   Shortly after he was struck, Beltran collapsed when a blood
vessel broke in his head, said Concagh, who was hired by the boy's
mother, Aida Garcia.
   In a lawsuit filed March 18 in U.S. District Court against the
Board of Education, Concagh said Beltran has required two brain
operations, is paralyzed on his left side and suffered severe brain
damage.
   Concagh said the lawsuit asks for $5 million in damages,
contending that school employees failed to stop the food fight even
though it had gone on for some time and had occurred on other days.
   Concagh said there were more than 250 students in the cafeteria
at the time with no security guards or monitors.
   Board of Education spokesman Frank Sobrino said school officials
could not comment because the suit had not been studied.
</TEXT>
