<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0845,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Pelt Arkansas, Texas, Louisiana; Boy Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with storm fatality in
Louisiana, other detail, picking up 5th graf pvs, `Rain
showers...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front pushing across the south-central states produced
strong thunderstorms in Arkansas, Louisiana and Texas on Tuesday,
while wintry weather gripped the Northwest and spring dazzled the
East.
   A 2-year-old boy died after high winds whipped up by a
thunderstorm knocked a tree into his trailer home in Bastrop, La.,
police said. His 3-year-old sister was injured.
   City crews with chainsaws and hydraulic equipment worked with
police and firemen to free the children, who were pinned by the
tree to the chair they had been sitting in, authorities said.
Another small child and their baby sitter were unhurt.
   Near Bunkie in central Louisiana, about 100 miles south of
Bastrop, a tornado destroyed two brick homes and one woman received
minor injuries, authorities said.
   The tornado knocked down poles holding power lines, cutting off
service to an undetermined number of Central Louisiana Electric Co.
customers. Traffic was rerouted around U.S. 71 until the live wires
could be secured, deputies said.
   Earlier in the day, thunderstorms in eastern Texas pelted
Buchanan Lake Village with three-quarter-inch hail Tuesday morning
and produced high winds that overturned an airplane at Mineola
Airport north of Tyler.
   Thunderstorms in western Arkansas downed trees northeast of
Magazine on Tuesday and spawned a tornado that uprooted trees and
damaged a barn and service station at Harriet.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from western Arkansas and
northern and central Louisiana into south-central Texas on Tuesday
afternoon. Other showers and thunderstorms extended from southern
Illinois across eastern Arkansas.
   Rain showers were reported in Oklahoma, eastern Kansas and much
of the middle-Mississippi Valley, with snow and sleet reported
along the northern and western fringes of that area. Clouds and
light rain and drizzle were reported in the upper Great Lakes
region.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m.
EST included 2{ inches at Harrison, Ark., an inch and a third at
West Plains, Mo., and Fayetteville, Ark., and an inch at
Springfield, Mo., and Waco, Texas.
   Skies were cloudy in the Northwest, and scattered rain and snow
showers fell.
   Snow advisories were posted Tuesday for Washington's Cascade
Range and Olympic Mountains, Oregon's northeast mountain areas and
for southwest Montana.
   Gale warnings were in effect along the coast of Washington and
Northern California.
   Skies were sunny over much of New England, the middle Missouri
Valley and the Southwest. Afternoon temperatures were in the 70s
from the Gulf Coast and the southern Atlantic Coast as far north as
Lake Erie.
   While strong northerly winds ushered much colder air into the
Great Plains and the Mississippi Valley, strong southerly winds
brought warm weather ahead of the cold front, from the western Gulf
Coast to the Great Lakes.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 20
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 87 degrees at McAllen, Texas,
and Fort Myers, Fla. The nation's low Tuesday morning was 1 degree
below zero at Yellowstone Park.
   Wednesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
the central and western Gulf Coast across the Ohio Valley to the
lower Great Lakes and western New England. Scattered rain showers
and snow showers in higher elevations were expected from the
northern Pacific Coast through the upper Rockies to the Dakotas and
across the upper Great Lakes. Snow was predicted in western and
central Montana and northern Wyoming.
   Temperatures in the 30s and 40s were forecast from the northern
and central Plateau region through the Dakotas to the upper Great
Lakes, and across northern Maine; in the 70s and 80s from Southern
California through southern New Mexico and the Rio Grande valley of
Texas to the south Atlantic Coast; and in 50s and 60s across most
of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
