<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WaterProjects     03-30 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Projects,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Wants to Add $1.59 Billion in Additional Water Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee wants to add $1.59 billion
worth of water projects to an already huge, backlogged construction
agenda that is being squeezed by budget deficits.
   The Environment and Public Works Committee voted unanimously
Tuesday to authorize the building of 16 new Army Corps of Engineers
projects from Florida to California, with Illinois receiving the
two costliest.
   The panel's bill is the first water projects authorization
measure to begin moving on Capitol Hill since 1986, when Congress
and the Reagan administration agreed on a massive package of
proposed construction.
   The 1986 legislation authorized more than 200 projects around
the country at a cost of between $10 billion and $15 billion,
depending upon the final scope of the flood control, navigation and
environmental restoration work.
   The 1986 law also forced localities to begin paying a portion of
a project's cost, a proposal that had deadlocked the water-projects
pipeline and had resulted in no new authorizations in the previous
16 years.
   Committee Chairman Quentin Burdick, D-N.D., said the new
proposal contains no rollbacks in the cost-sharing requirements,
and he insisted that the plan is ``non-controversial.''
   He and Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., said they hoped the
committee's action would be the start of a regular two-year cycle
of new authorizations for the corps.
   Once a project is authorized, its backers have to go to the
administration and the House and Senate Appropriations committees
in an effort to obtain construction money. If the money is not
forthcoming within five years, a project automatically loses its
authorization.
   Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine, said obtaining construction money
for a project is becoming difficult because of the huge number of
already authorized projects competing for limited money in times of
big budget deficits.
   The 1988 bill's costliest project, at an estimated $775 million,
would be a new lock and dam on the lower Ohio River near Olmsted.
Half the cost would be paid by all taxpayers and half would come
from fees and taxes paid by inland waterway users.
   The second most costly project would be a new phase of the
Chicagoland Underflow Plan, the flood control program for the
Chicago metropolitan area. Estimated total cost would be $419
million.
   Other projects that would be authorized by the Senate bill and
their estimated total costs are:
   _Fort Pierce Harbor, Florida, navigation improvement, $6,742,000.
   _Nassau County (Amelia Island), Florida, beach erosion control,
$5,753,000.
   _Port Sutton Channel, Florida, navigation improvement,
$2,670,000.
   _Hazard, Ky., flood control along a 14-mile stretch of the North
Fork Kentucky River, $7,450,000.
   _Mississippi River, southeast Louisiana and southern
Mississippi, enhancement of fish and wildlife resources,
$59,300,000, with the federal government paying the entire cost
because it is an environmental restoration proect.
   _Wolf and Jordan rivers and Bayou Portage, Mississippi,
navigation improvement, $2,229,000.
   _Truckee Meadows, Nevada, flood control, $78,400,000.
   _Scioto River, West Columbus, Ohio, flood control, $31,562,000.
   _Delaware River, Pennsylvania and Delaware, navigation
improvement, $17,200,000.
   _Lower Mission Creek, Santa Barbara, Calif., flood control,
$10,420,000.
   _Cypress Creek, Texas, flood control, $114,200,000.
   _Guadalupe River, Texas, navigation improvement, $23,900,000.
   _Falfurrias, Texas, flood control, $31,800,000.
   _McGrath Creek, Wichita Falls, Texas, flood control, $9,100,000.
   The exact federal and local shares of most of the projects will
not be known until the corps and local interests negotiate under
the terms of the 1986 law.
</TEXT>
