<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WeldProfile     03-30 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weld Profile,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Criminal Division Head Came from Distinguished GOP Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Justice Resignations Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William S. Weld, head of the Justice
Department's criminal division until his resignation Tuesday, is a
well-known figure in Massachusetts where he served as a successful
federal prosecutor.
   Weld, 42, a member of a distinguished Republican family in his
home state, spent five years as the U.S. attorney in Massachusetts
before he came to the nation's capital in 1986.
   During his tenure in Massachusetts, he led investigations that
resulted in the indictments of associates of Lyndon H. LaRouche
Jr., the political extremist. He also prosecuted money-laundering
cases against several New England banks.
   Before he moved into the criminal arena, Weld was a civil
litigator for a decade at Hill and Barlow, a Boston firm. He once
said he had a hard time getting started as a prosecutor.
   ``It took me six months to learn where the bathroom was,'' he
said.
   Weld has stellar academic and political connections. A summa cum
laude graduate of Harvard College, Weld also studied at Oxford
University in England. He received his law degree from Harvard in
1970.
   During 1974, he worked as a minority counsel for the House's
impeachment hearings during the Watergate episode.
   In 1978, he ran unsuccessfully as the GOP nominee for the
attorney general in Massachusetts.
   Weld is married to the former Susan Roosevelt, and they have
five children.
</TEXT>
