<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlanePit-Stop Bjt   03-30 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Pit-Stop, Bjt,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Caters To Fast-Paced Flyers, From Business People To
Celebrities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fresh flowers, catered refreshments, a
smiling flight attendant, a fill-up and a clean windshield _ it's
all part of the service offered by a network of ``pit stops'' for
the nation's corporate jets.
   The network, operated by Pueblo, Colo.-based Flower Aviation,
also features a mini-skirted service attendant named Tana Zipsie,
who directs the jets as they line up at Mount Vernon-Outland
Airport here.
   ``It's always fun when we get a jet in,'' said Ms. Zipsie, 20.
``It makes a person probably have a better day if they're greeted
with a smile.''
   To these corporate passengers, time is money. In 10 minutes,
Flower's ground crews can refuel a jet, restock on-board supplies,
dump the trash, vacuum the carpet and wipe the windshield, said
Stan Jones, the company's local general manager.
   Flower specializes in obscure airports, like Mount Vernon, where
amenities are scarce. The company also has flight pit stops in
Salina, Kan., and Fort Smith, Ark., and has plans for three more
Midwest bases.
   Most of the Flower flight stops are open 24 hours daily,
year-round. Mount Vernon is open from 6 a.m. to midnight.
   ``I haven't seen anybody unhappy when they left here at all,''
Jones said recently. ``That's the idea, anything they want. Treat
them like royalty.''
   When they arrive at Mount Vernon in the summer, passengers are
presented with flowers, usually fresh daisies. They're led indoors
to a plush lounge for refreshments and homemade chocolate chip
cookies.
   And if they're hungry, Flower also offers catered foods _ from
rolled slices of turkey, ham and roast beef to chilled shrimp and
crab legs.
   If pilots radio in ahead of time and mention the password,
``spin,'' they take home a bottle of champagne and a frozen steak,
said Jones, who declined to discuss his company's rates.
   ``This is a vacation for me. All the pressure is down,'' said
Gary Garrison, a corporate pilot from nearby Olney. ``It's just a
time for me to relax when the airplane is down like this.
   ``And they're very accommodating to you,'' Garrison added. ``You
can take their car and go uptown and eat if you like.''
   Some passengers, said Jones, take time to golf, fish or shop.
``We have guys that get out of the airplane and jog around the ramp
out there, in all kinds of weather.''
   Though most of their business comes from business people, Jones
said they also get celebrities, like singer Mickey Gilley and race
car driver Mario Andretti, military officers, politicians and
wealthy private parties.
   Jones said he could provide no figures on the number of daily
flights that used Flower's services at Mount Vernon, but he noted
that business picks up in the summer, with up to a dozen jets lined
up on the tarmac.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
