<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IowaBust     03-30 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iowa Bust,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Man Charged In Iowa's Largets Cocaine Haul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID TOMLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities charged a California
man Tuesday with intent to distribute after seizing 189 pounds of
cocaine worth more than $40 million when the car he was in was
stopped for speeding.
   Orlando Rene Monie, 33, of Los Angeles appeared in handcuffs
before a U.S. magistrate, and a bond hearing was set for Friday.
   Officials called the seizure by far the largest cocaine haul on
record in Iowa. Agents said the largest prior seizure they could
recall was a 12-pound haul in Davenport last year.
   Public Safety Commissioner Gene Shepard said two suitcases of
cocaine were found in the trunk of a car stopped for speeding
Monday afternoon near the Atlantic exit on Interstate 80.
   The trooper who pulled the car over had become suspicious and
asked to look inside the trunk, Shepard said.
   ``He saw several suitcases, one of which appeared to be leaking
a white powdered substance,'' Shepard said. The trooper called for
help, and a dog trained to detect narcotics was brought to the
scene.
   ``The dog indicated there were controlled substances in the
containers,'' Shepard said.
   Field tests concluded that the suitcases held cocaine, and Monie
was arrested along with a woman who had been driving the car and a
second woman. A 2-year-old child in the car was turned over
temporarily to county human services workers.
   The two women said they knew nothing about the suitcases in the
trunk and were later released.
   State agents said the largest prior cocaine seizure in Iowa they
could recall was a 12-pound haul in Davenport last year.
</TEXT>
