<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Philippines-Rebels 1stLd-Writethru a0461 03-30 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Philippines-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Captured Rebels Include New People's Army Chief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Aquino statement, background on
Kintanar, names of other communist rebels arrested. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the communist
insurgency's army was among seven rebels captured this week, the
military disclosed Wednesday.
   Romulo Kintanar, the elusive leader of the New People's Army,
was presented at a news conference held Wednesday by Maj. Gen.
Ramon Montano, chief of the Philippine Constabulary, at a heavily
guarded suburban Manila military camp.
   The seven rebels, who were arrested in a series of raids
Tuesday, also include Communist Party Secretary-General Rafael
Baylosis; Central Committee member Benjamin de Vera; and the chief
of staff and logistics officer of the New People's Army, Napoleon
Manuel.
   Of the seven rebels captured, only Baylosis did not appear at
the news conference Wednesday. Montano said Baylosis had refused to
be photographed.
   The arrest of the rebels was seen as a significant breakthrough
in the government's 19-year battle against the communist insurgency.
   President Corazon Aquino immediately hailed the arrests and
commended the armed forces chief of staff, Gen. Renato de Villa,
and other officers.
   ``The arrest of top communist leaders Rafael Baylosis, Benjamin
de Vera and several others is happy news for our country,'' Mrs.
Aquino said in a statement read by Press Secretary Teodoro Benigno.
   ``It clearly demonstrates that we have turned the tide and are
winning the war against the communist insurgency. The fact that
they were arrested on the NPA's 19th anniversary (Tuesday) attests
to the admirable performance of our armed forces of the
Philippines. I am elated and so is our citizenry.''
   The statement apparently was prepared before officials realized
that Kintanar was among those arrested in raids Tuesday in the
Manila suburb of San Juan. Officials said Kintanar initially gave
authorities a false name.
   Kintanar had long been wanted by the military.
   Besides being the alleged head of the 24,000-strong New People's
Army, he is widely believed to be the organizer of communist urban
assassination squads called Sparrow Units because of the swiftness
of their attacks.
   Kintanar organized the Sparrows, which began operations in the
southern Davao City in the early 1980s before moving out to the
Manila area and other urban centers.
   Military authorities did not mention Kintanar when they
announced the arrests Tuesday. He apparently used the alias of
Mario Asuncion because no person with such a name was among the
rebels presented to the press Wednesday.
   The others arrested were Kintanar's wife Gloria; Manuel's wife
Inez; and Marco Palo, a member of the Communist Party's liaison
committee jailed under deposed President Ferdinand Marcos. Palo was
among 500 political prisoners Mrs. Aquino released soon after
assuming power on Feb. 25, 1986.
</TEXT>
