<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-30 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Rally in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down after opening more than one
yen higher in Tokyo on Wednesday, while stocks extended their rally
to three days.
   The dollar began trading at 125.75 yen, up 1.38 yen from
Tuesday's close of 124.37 yen. After holding steady during the
morning, it began declining and ended trading at 125.43, up 1.06
yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues rose 366.89 points, or 1.41 percent, closing the
day at 26,319.98.
   It was the first time the index had ended trading above the
26,000-level since last October's market crash. On Tuesday, the
Nikkei gained 330.38 points.
   Traders said stock prices were boosted by the stronger dollar
and by gains on the New York and London markets on Tuesday.
   Dealers said trading on the foreign exchange market was quiet,
with many corporate customers staying on the sidelines because of
the end the Japanese fiscal year on Thursday.
   Many participants, traders said, were continuing to cover
dollar-short positions as they did on Tuesday, when the dollar
capped a 2.78-yen decline over four trading days and temporarily
touched 123.87 yen, its lowest level since the first week of
January.
   A Bank of Japan source said the dollar's recent fall ``was
triggered by speculative movements bolstered by almost groundless
factors.''
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, described
recent market intervention in support of the dollar by Japanese and
U.S. central banks as having been ``firm.''
   But many market analysts have said bullish sentiments toward the
yen remain because of healthly Japanese economic fundamentals.
</TEXT>
