<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     03-30 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Committee OKs April Fuel-Tax Exemption For Farmers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee has agreed to
grant a fuel-tax exemption for farmers and other off-the-road
diesel users on April 1 and to make corporations foot the bill.
   However, the future of the proposed relief remained in doubt
Tuesday because the House Ways and Means Committee, which must
originate tax bills, has scheduled no action on the diesel
proposal. Backers of the legislation are holding out hope that the
House panel will approve a bill this week before adjourning for
Easter week.
   Farmers, fishermen and others who use diesel for off-the-road
business purposes traditionally have been exempt from the tax,
which finances highway construction. But under a 1987 law aimed at
preventing cheating, they must begin paying the tax on April 1 and
then apply for a refund when they file their income-tax returns
next year.
   The Finance Committee voted last week to grant these users
relief from paying the tax at all but, because of budget
restrictions, it acted to provide the exemption on Oct. 1. At the
direction of the committee, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, the
chairman, introduced an amendment Tuesday that steps up the relief
to April 1.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Georgetown University Settles Case With Homosexual Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgetown University has agreed to provide
homosexual groups with the same privileges given other campus
groups, ending an eight-year legal battle over gay rights at the
Jesuit school.
   The consent order signed Tuesday by Judge Sylvia Bacon of the
District of Columbia Superior Court, university officials and
members of gay student groups, means that Georgetown must now
provide equal treatment to gay groups.
   However the consent order includes a ruling by the District of
Columbia Court of Appeals that said Georgetown does not have to
officially recognize the organizations. For that reason, the school
said it will not appeal the order to the Supreme Court.
   Officials at the nation's oldest Catholic university had argued
that recognizing the groups would violate basic tenets of the
Catholic church, and imply endorsement of homosexual practices.
   ``This result has been a long time in coming, and it is
gratifying to have Georgetown admit that it was wrong all these
years,'' said Lorri Jean, who first brought the case as a member of
a lesbian group at Georgetown Law School in 1980. ``There's great
satisfaction that a battle begun as a first-year law student has
finally been won.''
   Bacon also put into effect an appeals court ruling that
Georgetown must also pay attorney's fees for the students, which
are ``substantially in excess of half a million dollars,''
according to attorney Richard Gross, who represented one student
group.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Rejects Bill Giving States Title to Historic Shipwrecks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States hoping to get title to abandoned
shipwrecks of historic significance lying within their waters won't
get those submerged treasures following a rejection of a House
proposal strongly opposed by sport divers and some commercial
salvage operators.
   The House defeated the measure on Tuesday, 263-139, which was
five votes short of the two-thirds majority required for passage.
The bill passed the Senate by voice vote on Dec. 19.
   Rep. Norman D. Shumway, R-Calif., complained that under the
bill, ``there is no legal, binding or enforceable way ... to ensure
that the sport divers' right to dive on these wrecks, even for
purely recreational purposes, will be protected by states.''
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., countered that ``its passage will
go a long way toward preserving these archaeological treasures,''
although he agreed with Shumway that the bill may discourage
private exploration for undiscovered shipwrecks.
   Without the bill, said Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn., dynamiting and
other abuses by some reckless treasure hunters ``would absolutely
guarantee for future generations that these shipwrecks, these
valuable pieces of history, (would) be lost for all time.''
   Opponents complained that the bill had been brought to the floor
under parliamentary ground rules usually adopted for abbreviated
debate on non-controversial bills, with no amendments allowed.
   The bill's supporters, led by Rep. Charles E. Bennett, D-Fla.,
were expected to try to return the measure to the House floor under
different rules which would allow opponents to introduce amendments
and would require only a simple majority for passage.
</TEXT>
