<HEAD>Douglas Ginsburg to Join George Mason Law Faculty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas H. Ginsburg, whose nomination to
the U.S. Supreme Court was withdrawn because he once used
marijuana, will join the faculty of the George Mason University
School of Law as a visiting professor.
   Ginsburg, who will remain a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the District of Columbia, was one of four new law school
professors appointed Tuesday.
   Law school Dean Henry G. Manne said of Ginsburg's drug use: ``I
think it had nothing to do with his qualifications to sit on the
Supreme Court'' or his qualifications to be a professor.
   The law school, which opened in 1979, has about 700 students.
   Ginsburg, who will join the faculty in September, will teach
courses in antitrust law and business regulations.
