<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SimulatedShuttle     03-30 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Simulated Shuttle,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simulated Shuttle Flight In Progress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-man crew and Johnson Space
Center flight controllers are in the middle of a 32-hour simulated
mission to rehearse the real flight scheduled for August 4.
   NASA's first post-Challenger shuttle crew ``launched'' Tuesday
on the mission that ends today at 5 p.m., and almost immediately
began to confront potential problems it might face during an actual
flight.
   The most severe problem occurred nearly six minutes after the
9:09 a.m. liftoff, when one of three main engines shut down
prematurely, forcing the crew to simulate an emergency
abort-to-orbit procedure, which it did successfully.
   Later, the crew, commanded by Frederick Hauck, missed its first
opportunity about 3 p.m. to deploy their primary payload.
   Eventually, the rehearsed deployment was delayed a day when
difficulties developed with the satellite's stabilizing gyroscopes
and a booster.
   Efforts to troubleshoot on-board problems were hampered even
more when an orbiting TDRS satellite malfunctioned, forcing the
crew to communicate with mission controllers through a network of
ground stations rather than the satellite network.
   The crew is made up of Hauck, pilot Richard Covey and mission
specialists David Hilmers, George ``Pinky'' Nelson and Mike Lounge.
</TEXT>
