<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 0556EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LehderTrial     03-30 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lehder Trial,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Additional Noriega Testimony Banned by Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge threatened attorneys
in the cocaine-smuggling trial of Carlos Lehder Rivas with contempt
if they again mention the name of Panamanian Gen. Manuel Noriega.
   Noriega's name came up during the testimony of British pilot
Andrew Barnes, 32. Barnes told of having his twin-engine plane
sabotaged last year after G-2, the Panamanian secret police,
questioned him about the death of Noriega's personal pilot.
   ``We are trying one case here. Mr. Noriega will have his chance
if and when he comes to trial,'' U.S. District Judge Howell W.
Melton admonished Attorney Robert W. Merkle and defense attorney
Jose Quinon.
   Lehder, 38, is on trial on charges that he conspired with a
group of Jacksonville smugglers to import some 3.3 tons of cocaine
into the United States from Colombia via Norman's Cay in the
Bahamas from 1978 to 1980.
   Noriega's name came up after Barnes mentioned the Panamanian
strongman in a letter he wrote last month to Lehder. ``This whole
thing has to do with Noriega's indictment in the middle district of
Florida,'' he said.
   Noriega is under indictment on drug smuggling charges in both
Miami and Tampa.
   After the slaying last year in Colombia, Barnes said he was
detained and questioned for two days in Panama by G-2 about the
killing allegedly carried out by the Medellin cartel. The
government alleges Lehder is one of the cartel's leaders.
   ``The suggestion was that the people I worked for had murdered
the pilot. ... It was not true,'' Barnes said.
   Merkle said he did not contend Lehder was involved in the
killing. Merkle said Noriega's pilot was killed because he had
stolen cocaine while flying drugs for both the Panamanian leader
and the Medellin cartel.
   Following his detention, Barnes was ordered out of the country
and left aboard his private twin-engine plane. About an hour over
the ocean, one of his engines went out, and then the other started
failing.
   With the jury out of the room, Merkle said, ``G-2 removed the
backs of the magnetos in his engines and tried to kill him, plain
and simple.''
   Barnes has pleaded guilty to one charge of conspiracy to import
cocaine and faces a maximum seven-year sentence.
   Although Barnes testified that he flew some 3,000 kilograms for
Lehder in 1978 and 1980, he admitted under cross-examination that
he was not aware of any of the drug flights listed in the
indictment under which Lehder is being prosecuted.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise.
   Co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged only with taking part in a smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
