<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 0609EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugFight     03-30 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Fight,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pushers Pushing Family From Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who helped organize a citizens'
revolt against drug dealing in his neighborhood says he and his
family are being chased out of town by drug traffickers because he
dared to speak out.
   Rick Hargraves said Tuesday he decided to speed up his previous
plans to move after he was threatened with a pistol outside his
home this week.
   ``They really don't scare me. ... I'm worried about my wife and
kids,'' said Hargraves, an unemployed mechanic who has owned a
house on Yakima's once-quiet South Naches Avenue for six years.
   The family's plight illustrates the rising frustrations of
residents on the city's East Side, who are faced with discarded
hypodermic syringes on lawns, open drug dealing on sidewalks, and
violence in the alleys.
   Central Washington is a drug hotbed, with cocaine and heroin
carried north from Mexico by people posing as migrant farmworkers,
officials say. The influence of drugs has sent the Yakima County
crime rate, particularly murder and burglary, skyrocketing.
   ``Drugs are a very serious problem over here. It far exceeds
what I thought I would get into when I got here'' a year ago, said
Robert Dreisbach, head of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration
office in Yakima.
   The local DEA task force, in place just over a year, has made 99
arrests, many of them upper echelon dealers and suppliers, he said.
   ``This used to be a beautiful neighborhood,'' said Teresa
Ocampo, Hargraves' neighbor and like him a member of the
two-week-old South Naches Cleanup Committee. ``Now kids go outside
to play and find syringes and put them in their mouth.''
   While many committee members have preferred anonymity,
Hargraves, an unemployed mechanic, was outspoken.
   He talked with reporters about the committee's effort to record
license plates of suspicious vehicles, and the anger of homeowners
at seeing their values decreasing.
   On Monday, while Hargraves and his wife, Jill, were standing
outside their house talking with a television reporter, a vehicle
pulled up to the curb and the passenger rolled down the window,
Hargraves said.
   The driver leaned over, pointed a gun at them, made three sounds
like shots being fired, and then drove away, he said. Police
arrested two men a short time later, but Hargraves said things have
gone too far.
   The family purchased a house outside of town about two months
ago, intending to leave the neighborhood as soon as they sold their
present home. Mrs. Hargraves said they hadn't wanted to leave
before then for fear drug dealers would take over the empty house.
   After Monday's incident, however, they decided to move out right
away and found a friend who was willing to live there.
   ``If she minds her own business they're not going to bother
her,'' Mrs. Hargraves said. ``We were fine until we started
fighting back.''
   Police Chief Pleas Green said Hargraves made the mistake of
becoming a focal point in the anti-drug efforts, especially through
media interviews and photographs.
   The average citizen is not equipped to fight drug dealers,
Dreisbach said.
   ``In this area most of the drug traffickers are armed with
loaded automatic and semi-automatic weapons,'' he said. ``The
number of drug-related homicides and assaults shows they do use
them periodically.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
