<2ND_LINE>PM-Mspi Runoff,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nominations Decided in 2 Mspi Districts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two southern Mississippi congressional
districts have selected nominees for seats that congressmen Trent
Lott and Wayne Dowdy are giving up to run for the U.S. Senate.
   In the 4th District runoff Tuesday, Brookhaven funeral home
director Mike Parker, a 38-year-old political newcomer, defeated
Brad Pigott, a 33-year-old Jackson attorney, in the Democratic
runoff. Thomas Collins III defeated Andy Taggart on the Republican
side. Collins is executive director of the Mississippi Veterans
Home Purchase Board. Taggart is a Jackson attorney.
   In the 5th District, state Sen. Gene Taylor of Bay St. Louis
defeated Glenn White of Hattiesburg, while 43-year-old Sheriff
Larkin Smith of Gulfport outdistanced Hattiesburg businessman
George Robert Hall, 57, in the Republican runoff.
   In a runoff race for the Democratic nomination for a vacant seat
on the state Supreme Court, former Attorney General Ed Pittman
defeated Laurel attorney Jon Swartzfager by a 3-to-2 margin.
   The races were left over from contests on Super Tuesday.
