<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BridgeCrash     03-30 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridge Crash,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buses Carrying Teen-agers in Bridge Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAYWARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two buses loaded with teen-agers
returning from a visit to the nation's capital collided on a bridge
that crosses San Francisco Bay, injuring at least 20 people and
closing the span for more than two hours.
   The accident Tuesday night began when a car with a flat tire
stopped in the fast lane of the 9{-mile-long San Mateo Bridge, said
California Highway Patrol investigator Nick Chouprov.
   The buses carried 72 youngsters from Modesto junior high
schools. The first stopped and was struck from behind by the
second, according to Chouprov.
   The youngsters suffered only minor injuries, according to Thomas
McGarry, a spokesman for Eden Hospital in Castro Valley.
   The most seriously injured was bus driver Charles Ford, 60, of
Oakland who was in serious condition with stomach injuries, he
said. ``It took 20 minutes to get him out of the bus,'' McGarry
said.
   The driver of the car that stopped for the flat, Xiaoyun Zhou,
38, of Hayward, was in serious condition with head injuries.
   The teen-agers from La Loma and Roosevelt junior high schools
were en route home from San Francisco International Airport, where
they had returned from a field trip to Washington D.C.
   ``When we crashed into the other bus everybody started screaming
and crying. The driver swerved but he still hit the bus,'' said
Kristi New, 13, of Roosevelt.
   Callie Stewart, 13, also of Roosevelt, said she flipped over a
seat during the accident.
   ``I was sitting up and talking to my friend when I did a total
flip,'' she said. ``Everybody was screaming. After the bus stopped,
people started hugging each other and asking if they were OK.''
   Some of the youngsters said police officers and paramedics got
them out through the windows of the vehicles.
   Three students who suffered minor injuries were treated and
released at Eden, said McGarry. The most seriously injured was Todd
Johnson, 12, who had a fractured arm.
   St. Rose Hospital treated seven youngsters, including two
students with minor nose injuries, said spokeswoman Debbie
Bartling. Ten other students were treated at hospitals for minor
injuries, McGarry said.
   The bridge that links San Mateo and Hayward is about 20 miles
south of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
