<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 0635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OralRoberts     03-30 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oral Roberts,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roberts Launches New Money Drive with No Warning He'll Be Called
`Home'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TV evangelist Oral Roberts said he will ask
followers to donate another $8 million for his troubled medical
school, but he did not repeat last year's warning that God would
call him ``home'' if the drive failed.
   Roberts, in a taped appearence Tuesday on his son's program,
``Richard Roberts Live,'' said he would reinstate the medical
missionary program that the university canceled two months ago for
lack of funds.
   ``Now, by faith ... we will undertake a second year of
scholarship. You heard me say it the way I said it, by faith, we
will go for a second year,'' Roberts said on the program, which was
to be broadcast today.
   The evangelist agreed with his wife when she said their ``faith
wavered a little'' when they announced cancellation of the
scholarship program.
   The scholarships are provided to the students, who in return
work in Third World countries after graduation for several years as
part of the Roberts ministry.
   In 1986, Roberts announced the drive to raise by March 1987 the
$8 million needed to fund the scholarships and the medical school,
saying he wanted his students to concentrate on their education
without worrying about tuition.
   In announcing that fund-raiser, Roberts said God told him, ``I
want you to get this going in one year or I will call you home.''
   On Tuesday, Roberts and his wife Evelyn spoke via satellite from
Anaheim, Calif., to a gathering of students, faculty members and
university trustees in Tulsa. The exchange was recorded for use on
his son's program.
   The taped segment included statements from the chief financial
officer of the university, and from auditor firms who said the $8
million raised last year was used to underwrite the total costs of
the medical school for one year.
   Medical students appeared confused when Roberts made the
announcement to reinstate the program. Mark Claussen, president of
the junior class at the Oral Roberts University medical school,
spoke out.
   ``I just want this to be clear, President Roberts. Two months
ago, all of the students here were directly told that all money
would be discontinued in May,'' Claussen said.
   ``You fine young men and women ... have come face to face with
the heart of Christianity, living by faith,'' Roberts responded.
``I've got no guarantees of what will happen in the future, as we
try to serve our Heavenly Father.''
   Mrs. Roberts interrupted her husband and said, ``Two or three
months ago, our faith wavered a little and that's what the
confusion is.''
</TEXT>
