<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brawley-Classmate     03-30 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley-Classmate,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schoolmate of Tawana Brawley Had Filed Similar Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A girl in Tawana Brawley's school claimed 18
months ago that she had been abducted and sexually abused in a
manner markedly similar to the details of Miss Brawley's story,
according to a report published today.
   The teen-ager, who knew Miss Brawley, reported that she was
grabbed by men in a green car and driven to a wooded area where she
was sexually assaulted, according to a report in today's Daily
News, citing unidentified law enforcement sources.
   Police in Poughkeepsie investigating that case found that the
charges were unfounded and that the girl had made up the story
apparently to cover sexual abuse committed by a male relative.
   Details of the 1986 incident have been turned over to the task
force working on the Brawley case under the direction of Attorney
General Robert Abrams.
   Poughkeepsie police turned over the files after the earlier case
was brought up by an anonymous caller on a local talk radio
program, the report said.
   Investigators are trying to determine whether the other student
discussed the case with Miss Brawley as late as Nov. 23, the day
before Miss Brawley, who was then 15, claims she was abducted.
   Miss Brawley has said she was abducted Nov. 24 in a green or
blue car, taken to a wooded area and then sexually assaulted by at
least six white men, including one who flashed a police-type badge.
   She was found after four days near her Dutchess County home,
covered with animal feces and with racial epithets scrawled on her
body.
   Abrams spokesman Timothy Gilles refused to comment on the News
report.
</TEXT>
