<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-30 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites ,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Lite Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you've ever dreamed of making it on to the
cover of a Wheaties box, dream no more.
   General Mills Inc., the maker of the ``Breakfast of Champions,''
is inviting everyone to appear on a Wheaties box. But unlike recent
box subjects like Walter Payton and the Minnesota Twins, the public
will have to pay.
   The promotion, beginning next week, offers individualized
Wheaties boxes for $18.95 and proof of purchase. Eight weeks after
sending in the money and a black-and-white picture, people will
receive a single, acrylic-sealed box with their picture on the
cover, the company says.
   ``Customers have been writing letters to us for many, many years
wondering how they could get their picture on the Wheaties box,''
General Mills spokeswoman Kathryn Newton said.
   The boxes also are offered for $13.95 and five proof-of-purchase
coupons.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to make the cranberry muffin the
official state muffin wasn't a half-baked idea and didn't deserve
to get jokingly panned by the Legislature last weekend, Elaine
Tabor says.
   It was Ms. Tabor's class at Washington Elementary School in
Merrill that initiated the drive last year to give the cranberry
muffin official status.
   The proposal was still pending when Assembly Speaker Thomas
Loftus decided to adjourn the Democratic-controlled Assembly late
Friday night before the Senate could finish work o the 1988-89
state budget.
   Loftus said his action was in part because the Senate was
spending its time discussing whether the cranberry muffin should be
the state's official muffin.
   ``They (the Senate) sent us the cranberry muffin bill at 11:30
p.m. and I think we snapped,'' Loftus said.
   The senators had added a mocking amendment that would have
established the Egg McMuffin as the official state breakfast and
the ragamuffin as the state's official child muffin.
   Senators passed that version on a voice vote and shipped it back
to the Assembly. The bill died.
   But Ms. Tabor said the situation wasn't funny for the children
in her second-grade class last year.
   ``We were studying Wisconsin and had visited a cranberry marsh
about eight miles from here,'' Ms. Tabor said Monday. ``We read
about some students in Massachussetts who had done the same thing
for the corn muffin. I know it's a frivolous thing, but it's not
frivolous to the children.''
</TEXT>
