<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Latin-Panama     03-30 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Latin-Panama,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latin American Group Condemns U.S. Sanctions On Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Latin American organization
condemned U.S. economic pressure on Panama as outside interference,
but also called on Panama to adopt democratic reforms and hold
elections.
   The 26-nation Latin American Economic System, based in Caracas
and created 12 years ago as a forum for Latin American countries,
ended an extraordinary two-day meeting on Tuesday which had been
requested by Panama.
   It said the U.S. economic measures violated international law
and the charters of the United Nations and the Organization of
American States.
   The Reagan administration has imposed economic sanctions on
Panama and made it clear that it wants Panama's strongman, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, ousted as leader of that nation's military,
known as the Defense Forces.
   Noriega has been indicted in the United States on charges of
drug smuggling and money-laundering, charges that he denies.
   Washington still recognizes Eric Arturo Delvalle as president of
Panama, though Delvalle was stripped of his office by the
Noriega-dominated legislature after trying to fire Noriega.
   Foreign Minister Allan Wagner of Peru told the assemblage
Tuesday, ``We have not come to defend a regime, or even less a
person who has been insubordinate to civil and constitutional
authority.
   ``Our solidarity is with the people of Panama.''
   Wagner called for an end to Panama's political crisis ``through
free elections and the removal of any obstacles that prevent this
clear expression of the will of the people of Panama.''
   The Latin American Economic System noted that Foreign Minister
Jorge Abadia Arias of Panama promised the conference Panama would
``deepen its democratic system.'' The Economic System said a
request for economic aid by Panama will be considered ``with a
spirit of solidarity'' by the organization's members.
   The nations said they opposed foreign intervention in Panama and
asked the United States to honor a treaty which turns full control
of the Panama Canal over to Panama in 1999.
   ``We urge the U.S. government to revoke immediately the coercive
measures it has adopted against Panama,'' they said in their final
communique Tuesday.
   ``We reaffirm the sovereign right of all nations to decide their
own economic, social and political destiny in peace and liberty,
free from foreign pressure, aggression and threats.''
</TEXT>
