<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 0755EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     03-30 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Black Communities Claim Victories Over Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two black communities are
claiming victories after lengthy battles against the government,
which had sought to relocate one group and change the political
status of the other.
   In one case, an appeals court ruled Tuesday that the government
did not have the authority to incorporate the 120,000-member black
community of Moutse into a homeland dominated by a different tribe.
   Also, the government said late Monday it will not attempt to
relocate the remaining 8,000 residents of Oukasie, a township 30
miles west of Pretoria.
   In the Moutse case, the four-judge panel ruled that President
P.W. Botha exceeded his powers by incorporating the community into
the KwaNdebele homeland on Jan. 1, 1986. The court said the action
was taken for ``administrative convenience'' rather than in the
interest of Moutse residents.
   Most Moutse residents belong to the North Sotho tribe, and they
argued that their language and culture differed sharply from the
Ndebeles, who make up most of KwaNdebele's 400,000 residents.
   Moutse, located northwest of Pretoria, previously was part of
the Lebowa homeland. But the white-led government excised Moutse
from Lebowa when it incorporated the community into KwaNdebele.
   Dozens of people were killed in the unrest that followed. Moutse
residents staged frequent protests, and battled both local police
and vigilantes from the KwaNdebele government.
   Moutse, at least for the time being, does not belong to any
homeland. It is a 171-square-mile region that adjoins KwaNdebele,
an impoverished, undeveloped homeland where many of the workers
ride buses for up to eight hours a day, commuting to and from jobs
in Pretoria.
   Meanwhile, Minister of Constitutional Developlment Chris Heunis
told Parliament on Monday that the government would no longer try
to relocate Oukasie residents to Lethlabile, 12 miles away.
   Heunis abolished Oukasie by decree in October 1986, but only
about 5,000 of the 13,000 residents moved to Lethlabile, a newly
established township with some upgraded facilities. Most Oukasie
residents preferred their old home, where they could walk to their
jobs in the white town of Brits.
   About 8,000 residents have stayed even though the government at
various times cut off the water supply, stopped garbage collection,
tore down the school and halted bus service in an effort to make
residents leave.
   The government also sent in bulldozers to destroy houses of
people that moved from Oukasie. The town has been run largely by
community organizations for the past 18 months.
   The government's apartheid policy establishes a racially
segregated society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have
no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the
economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health
services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
