<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-MiddleEast     03-30 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Middle East,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Meets on Occupied Territories
^With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
expressed concern over ``the deteriorating situation'' in Israel's
occupied territories and the Security Council scheduled an urgent
meeting on the crisis.
   The 15-member council agreed to hold the meeting today at the
request of Arab nations who said it was necessitated by increasing
repression of Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Today is Palestinian Land Day, a traditional day of nationalist
protest, and Israel on Tuesday sealed off its occupied lands
territories for at least three days to gird against unrest.
   Arab foreign ministers and the Palestine Liberation Organization
also asked Perez de Cuellar on Tuesday to send a new fact-finding
mission to the occupied lands and disseminate U.N. information
gathered there while journalists are barred.
   The U.N. chief later issued a statement expressing ``acute
concern about the deteriorating situation in the occupied
territories and especially the continued killing and wounding of
unarmed civilians.''
   He said he was ``particularly disturbed by recent press reports
of statements in Israel to the effect that the problem in the
occupied territories will be resolved by force.''
   He said such a policy ``can only lead to further violence.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir was quoted as saying Monday, ``If
the Arabs of Israel won't come to their senses, reality will be
harder and laden with impending disaster.''
   Perez de Cuellar said a political solution could be found only
through an international peace conference with the participation of
the parties directly concerned and the five permanent members of
the Security Council _ the United States, the Soviet Union, China,
Britain and France.
   The Security Council has repeatedly condemned Israel's harsh
measures to put down the protests that began Dec. 8 in the
territories taken from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
