<1ST_LINE>u i PM-ANCKilling 1stLd-Writethru   03-30 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ANC Killing, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0504,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Offices Attacked In Paris and Marseille</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, `They were...' to CORRECT age. Pick up 6th
pvs, `Police sources...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded early today near the South African
Embassy in Paris after demonstrations protesting the killing of an
African National Congress spokeswoman. No injuries were reported.
   In the southern port city of Marseille, at least six gunshots
were fired Tuesday night at the windows of a building in front of
the South African Consulate. The gunmen fled in a car and no
arrests were made.
   The bomb, which caused only minor damage, exploded about 3 a.m.
in Paris at an office building a few blocks from the South African
Embassy. No one immediately claimed responsiblity for the bombing.
   The explosion occurred a few hours after police arrested more
than 80 demonstrators who broke into the South African Tourism
Office and protested outside the residence of the South African
ambassador in Paris.
   They were protesting the slaying of Dulcie September, 53, the
ANC representative to France, Switzerland and Luxembourg who was
found dead Tuesday outside the door of her Paris office from a
gunshot to the face.
   Police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at the
time that the killing looked like ``the work of a professional.''
   The ANC, the main guerrilla group fighting white domination in
South Africa, blamed Pretoria for the killing. The South African
government denied responsiblity and said the attack was related to
strife within the ANC, which was banned by South Africa in 1960 for
its anti-apartheid activities.
   A French Foreign Ministry spokesman said on Tuesday that no
claim of responsiblity had been received.
   In Marseille, the gunshots were fired at 11:15 p.m. Tuesday at
the windows of a building in front of the South African Consulate.
The building was painted with the slogan, ``Botha, assassin, SS.''
The slogan was apparently referring to South African President P.W.
Botha.
   In Paris, 41 protestors were arrested by police Tuesday night
after breaking into the South African Tourism Office after it had
closed and smashing the interior. Two officers and a French
journalist were slightly injured in the scuffle to eject the
protesters from the office.
   Forty-six demonstrators were arrested Tuesday night outside the
residence of the South African ambassador in Paris for painting
anti-apartheid slogans on the wall of the building. Police
identified the protesters only as young leftists who supported the
ANC and all but four were released overnight.
   Earlier, at least 1,000 people marched peacefully in separate
protests of the killing in Paris.
   President Francois Mitterrand said he would ask South Africa
about the attack and reaffirmed his ``categoric condemnation of the
regime of racial segregation.''
   A colleague of Ms. September's claimed that the victim had
requested protection from the Interior Ministry after receiving
threats. She also said she had been followed for several days.
   The Interior Ministry denied she had requested protection.
   ``We were never called on for the least demand for protection,''
a spokeswoman said. ``If she had asked, we would have given it to
her.''
   At ANC headquarters in Lusaka, Zambia, spokesman Tom Sebina
called the killing ``part of a deliberate South African campaign to
assassinate ANC members and ANC leaders.'' He said Ms. September
went to Paris in 1983 and was among the ANC's ``most vigorous
activists.''
   The ANC maintains a worldwide network of about 20 ``information
offices,'' including several in Europe, to lobby for support and
receive aid.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
