<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Rebels 1stLd-Writethru a0510thattime 03-30
0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0510,0787</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raids Net Top Communist Fighter, Aquino Says Tide Turned Against
Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Baylosis identified as No.
2 man in party. PICKS up 5th graf, `Kintanar had ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military today said it captured
the country's top rebel fighter and the No. 2 man in the Communist
Party. President Corazon Aquino said the arrests marked the turning
point in the battle against communism.
   Maj. Gen. Ramon Montano told reporters that Romulo Kintanar,
commander of the communist New People's Army, was among seven rebel
leaders captured in Tuesday's raids. He said authorities did not
immediately realize who Kintanar was because he gave a false name.
   The government-run Philippine News Agency quoted another
military official as saying the chairman of the Communist Party of
the Philippines, Benito Tiamzon, had escaped by the time raiders
arrived at his hideout in suburban Quezon City.
   But his No. 2 man, party Secretary General Rafael Baylosis, was
among those arrested.
   The agency said Tiamzon must have been tipped off by radio
broadcasts on the arrest of his comrades in two raids at the Manila
suburb of San Juan earlier Tuesday.
   Military officials said they believe the rebel leaders had just
held or were about to convene a central committee plenum. They said
search operations were continuing and they expected more arrests in
the coming days.
   Kintanar had long been wanted by the military. Besides being the
alleged head of the 24,000-strong New People's Army, he is widely
believed to be the organizer of communist urban assassination
squads, called Sparrow Units because of the swiftness of their
attacks.
   The Sparrows first began operations in southern Davao City in
the early 1980s before moving out to the Manila area and other
urban centers.
   Among those arrested with Kintanar were Baylosis and Benjamin de
Vera, the Central Committee member in charge of operations on
Mindanao island. The others were New People's Army logistics
officer Napoleon Manuel; his wife Inez; Kintanar's wife Gloria; and
Marco Palo, a member of the party's liaison committee.
   Mrs. Aquino immediately hailed the arrests as ``happy news for
our country'' and commended the armed forces chief of staff, Gen.
Renato de Villa, and other officers and enlisted men.
   ``It clearly demonstrates that we have turned the tide and are
winning the war against the communist insurgency,'' she said in a
statement read by Press Secretary Teodoro Benigno. ``The fact that
they were arrested on the NPA's 19th anniversary (on Tuesday)
attests to the admirable performance of our Armed Forces of the
Philippines. I am elated and so is our citizenry.''
   Montano announced the capture of Kintanar when he presented the
guerrilla leader and other captives to journalists at a suburban
military camp where they were being held under heavy guard. The
only captive not present was Baylosis, who Montano said refused to
be photographed.
   Montano would not let reporters ask the captives any questions.
   Military officials did not mention the name of Kintanar when
they announced the arrests Tuesday, identifying one of those
arrested as Mario Asuncion _ apparently the alias Kintanar used.
   Montano told reporters that Kintanar admitted his real identity
when the officer confronted the rebel later. Officials said the
captured rebels refused to talk to interrogators and would only
give their names.
   Kintanar, Baylosis and de Vera were the fourth, fifth and sixth
Central Committee members to be captured since Mrs. Aquino came to
power in February 1986 in a civilian-military uprising that ousted
President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Former New People's Army chief Rodolfo Salas, whom Kintanar
replaced, was arrested in 1986 while leaving a Manila hospital
following a checkup. Last year, Juanito Rivera was captured in a
raid on his mother's house in Pampanga province north of the
capital. And in February, Tomas Dominado was among 20 suspected
rebels nabbed in a series of raids in the capital.
   Tuesday's arrests came as the military was on a heightened state
of alert in Manila and several other regions in anticipation of
attacks marking Tuesday's 19th anniversary of the New People's Army.
   No major rebel attacks were reported Tuesday, but a Japanese
businessman was shot and killed in a Manila suburb by an
unidentified lone gunman who escaped, police said. The victim was
identified as Akihiro Sato, 49, of Tsuchiura City in Japan's
Ibaraki Prefecture.
   In Luzon's Bulacan province, two suspected communist assassins
shot dead a policeman Tuesday, while government troops captured a
guerrilla in Bataan province, military reports said.
   Reports of attacks in the countryside often take days to reach
Manila.
</TEXT>
