<1ST_LINE>r p PM-TipperGore     03-30 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tipper Gore,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tipper Gore Stumps For Husband While Others Protest Music-Labeling
Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tipper Gore said she still supports
efforts to establish a voluntary rating system for rock music
lyrics as about 150 protesters, some sporting spiked haircuts and
punk-rock clothing, demonstrated against the idea.
   Mrs. Gore, wife of Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore, a Democratic
presidential contender, spoke Tuesday night to nearly 400 people at
the 14th annual National Issues Forum, sponsored by Pitzer College.
   The protesters, including musician Jello Biafra, were
demonstrating against her efforts to initiate a rating system for
rock music similar to that used by the movie industry.
   Mrs. Gore said she does not support censorship, but also said
she is now more interested in helping the homeless and getting her
husband elected president.
   At times chanting ``All we are saying is give rock a chance''
and ``No more censorship,'' the protesters lined two side entrances
to the Beverly Wilshire Hotel, where Mrs. Gore spoke.
   Some waved signs proclaiming ``Ozzy not Albert,'' references to
heavy-metal rock musician Ozzy Osbourne and to Mrs. Gore's husband.
   ``I just don't think any music should be censored by someone
else,'' said Kris Wood, 20, of Burbank.
   Inside the Beverly Wilshire's grand ballroom, Mrs. Gore briefly
acknowledged the demonstration.
   ``I understand that some people are outside protesting my
efforts to call attention to violent and explicit song lyrics that
are being peddled to children. That's certainly their privilege,
but I think they've been misinformed about what my position is _ or
possibly they don't care,'' she said.
   The author of ``Raising PG kids in an X-Rated Society'' said she
favors voluntary ``truth in packaging'' by the music industry and
not censorship.
   Most of her speech focused on the plight of America's homeless,
however, a problem she said her husband would dedicate himself to
solving if elected president.
   She showed a 12-minute video titled ``Homeless in America: A
Photographic Project,'' featuring poems and statements by homeless
people. The tape was produced by several photographers working with
the National Mental Health Association and Families For The
Homeless.
   ``We need a president who understands that homelessness isn't
just a problem of those who are forced to live on the streets. It's
our problem, yours and mine,'' she said.
   The annual National Issues Forum dinner sponsored by Pitzer, one
of the Claremont colleges, has in past years featured such keynote
speakers as former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and
communications tycoon Ted Turner.
</TEXT>
