<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PalmBeachTennis     03-30 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palm Beach Tennis,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What To Do About Those Noisy Tennis Ball Machines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The thunk of tennis ball machines is
disturbing the serenity of some residents at this posh resort, and
town officials ended up with the ball in their court.
   Members of the Ordinances, Rules and Standards Committee
pondered the issue Tuesday: Should use of the machines, popular
with partnerless players on the peninsula's private estates and
members-only clubs, be limited?
   ``I think the people who now have them should be grandfathered
in,'' Mayor Yvelyne ``Deedy'' Marix said. ``But I'm not sure that
any more should be allowed.''
   Town Council Chairman Nancy Douthit lobbed back: ``It seems to
me that when you begin regulating your neighbor's tennis game, it
gets a bit heavy. Supposing I had a noisy hair dryer _ should we
then outlaw hair dryers in Palm Beach?''
   Three years ago, Douthit was adamantly opposed to the
high-pitched, whining noise made by leaf-blowers and had the town's
noise ordinance amended to limit their use.
   The ordinance already prohibits the use during the winter
season, when most part-time residents are in town, of pile drivers,
jackhammers, sandblasters, dredges ``or any engines operated in
such a manner as to emit odors or noises offensive or disagreeable
to the inhabitants of the town.''
   The committee agreed to recommend that the Town Council vote
amend the noise ordinance to limit the use of tennis ball machines
to between 9 a.m. and 5:30 p.m. during the winter and 8 a.m. to 6
p.m. the rest of the year.
   On Sundays, they would be prohibited year-round.
</TEXT>
