<HEAD>North Korea Accuses South Korea Of Violating Territorial Waters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea today claimed a South Korean warship
violated territorial waters off its coast, the North's official
Radio Pyongyang said.
   Radio Pyongyang, monitored in Tokyo, said coast guard boats were
mobilized in response to an unidentified South Korean warship which
was spotted Tuesday in the North's ``western territorial waters off
Changsan-kot.''
   The report said the battleship fled toward the south.
   ``The act of a military provocation like this by the South is
another planned scheme to intensify the situation on the Korean
Peninsula,'' the radio said. North Korea designates all areas
within 50 miles of its coasts as being within its territorial
waters.
   On Tuesday, North Korea charged that U.S. SR-71 high-speed,
high-altitude reconnaissance planes had intruded its air space 12
times since joint U.S.-South Korean military exercises began last
month.
