<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0455 03-30 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,550</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 5 grafs new with Dukakis' comments today; picks up 5th
graf pvs, He cited.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis today thanked Connecticut
voters for the primary victory that gives him momentum heading into
Wisconsin and the next round of presidential contests.
   ``It was a good win for us. We won with a big, big margin,''
Dukakis said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show. ``But it's not the first
of my victories. I've won in the South. I've won in the Midwest.
I've won up here in the Northeast ... I'm just very pleased that
people who know me best were so supportive.''
   The Massachusetts governor defeated Jesse Jackson by a 2-to-1
margin in neighboring Connecticut, and regained the lead in
delegates to the Democratic Convention.
   The latest Associated Press count put Dukakis at 647.55; Jackson
at 634.55 and uncommitted at 500.6. Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
had 364.8 and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon 169.5.
   ``The message ... is getting stronger and stronger every week
this campaign goes on,'' Dukakis told his backers Tuesday night.
   He cited his commitment to job growth, education, housing,
health care, the environment and ``a strong America that reflects
our values and our principles.''
   Hands on his hips, Dukakis also responded to those who have
minimized his New England victories because of his regional
advantage.
   ``It's as absurd to say this should be discounted as it is to
say Jesse's should be because (Michigan) is next to Illinois,'' he
said upon returning to Boston late Tuesday after an evening in New
York.
   He stuck closely to his chosen themes, avoiding any open
criticism of Jackson and refusing to speculate about the vice
presidency.
   ``This sends us back to Wisconsin and Colorado with a very good
boost,'' Dukakis said, adding that each contest is different and
that no candidate will win all of the remaining states.
   Colorado's Democratic caucus is Monday and Wisconsin's primary
follows one day later.
   ``I look forward to going back out to Wisconsin and Colorado,''
both of which pick delegates next week, ``with that same strong
message of economic opportunity and good jobs as someone who not
only talks about those things but who's done them,'' Dukakis said,
underscoring the government experience that he has and Jackson
lacks.
   In a written victory statement, the Dukakis campaign sought to
draw attention to Dukakis' vote among blue-collar white voters, who
had helped Jackson win in Michigan.
   ``Tonight, Connecticut voters across all ideological lines _ and
an overwhelming margin of blue-collar voters _ gave a resounding
endorsement of the Dukakis bid for the presidency,'' the campaign
statement said.
   Fielding questions from reporters, Dukakis predicted that
neither he nor Jackson could hope to collect an outright majority
of nominating delegates by the time the primary season ends in
California on June 7.
   ``This is 15 rounds, and it's going to be a decision _ not a
knockout,'' he said. ``I felt from the beginning that the field
would narrow to two or three'' and that one candidate would have a
``substantial lead.''
   Asked how he felt after rebounding in Connecticut from his
surprising loss to Jackson in the Michigan voting four days
earlier, Dukakis said each race is different and ``it is the
cumulative result that counts.''
</TEXT>
