<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     03-30 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli-Back Militiamen Storm Shiite Moslem Stronghold</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli-backed militiamen stormed a
pro-Iranian guerrilla stronghold in south Lebanon today after
repulsing two attacks on their outposts, police reported.
   Militiamen from the South Lebanon Army backed by Israeli
artillery fire inflicted heavy casualties on the guerrillas, police
and United Nations observers said.
   Moslem radio stations in Beirut said Israeli soldiers also
fought in the battle but police could not confirm that. The Israeli
army denied the reports.
   Police said the attack occurred after the guerrillas, Shiite
Moslems linked to the Iranian-backed Hezbollah movement, launched
pre-dawn raids on militia posts near Kfar Roumman and the town of
Hasbaya.
   No accurate casualty figures were immediately available.
   Police said a South Lebanon Army force, spearheaded by 12
Soviet-designed T-54 tanks, drove the Moslem guerrillas out Kfar
Roumman after heavy fighting.
   The town, a base for the guerrillas of the Islamic Resistance
Movement, is about half a mile west of a South Lebanon Army base
and two miles north of the Shiite market town of Nabatiyeh.
   Most of Kfar Roumman's estimated 12,000 residents fled earlier
as the battle raged. The town had come under repeated machine gun
fire from hilltop army positions.
   ``Islamic Resistance fighters were seen withdrawing from Kfar
Roumman. The town has been devastated by shelling,'' a police
spokesman said.
   Tanks from the South Lebanon Army advanced behind a fierce
barrage of Israeli artillery fire from U.S.-made 155-mm howitzers
in the Israelis' self-designated ``security zone'' north of the
Lebanese border, police said.
   The attacks, the latest in a chain of assaults by the Islamic
fighters, came as Lebanon's Moslems marked the 12th anniversary of
Land Day, when the Israelis killed six Palestinians in 1976 in
protests against land confiscation in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank.
   A strike was also called in Moslem sectors of the country to
express support for the Palestinians in the occupied lands. Banks,
schools, shops, restaurants, cinemas, government offices and other
businesses shut down.
   Palestinians in the occupied territories have been mounting
violent protests against Israeli rule since Dec. 8. More than 110
Palestinians and one Israeli soldier have been killed.
   According to figures released Tuesday by Maj. Gen. Yossi Peled,
chief of the army's northern command, 236 Lebanese guerrillas,
mostly of the Hezbollah movement, died over the past year in
attacks on Israelis and Israeli-supported forces in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
