<HEAD>Last of L'Esperance Quints Back Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of spokeswoman's name thruout, Jonson sted
Johnson</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last of the nation's first test-tube
quintuplets went home again after a week of observation for a
breathing problem, a hospital spokeswoman says.
   Veronica L'Esperance left the hospital late Monday after being
observed for apnea, a condition in which she stopped breathing
while eating, hospital spokeswoman Carol Jonson said Tuesday.
   Veronica, her brother and three sisters were born Jan. 11 after
their mother, Michele L'Esperance, was impregnated through in-vitro
fertilization. The boy and two of the girls left the hospital March
7, Jonson said.
   Veronica and one of her sisters left the hospital 11 days later,
but Veronica went back into the hospital on March 21. She and the
rest of the quints are doing fine, Jonson said.
</TEXT>
