<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NuclearPrank     03-30 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Prank,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Possible Prank Puts Green Water In Nuclear Fuel Pool</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0544 to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WINTERSBURG, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials say they can't be sure it
was a prankster who planted green dye in a pool where highly
radioactive nuclear fuel is stored, even though it happened on the
eve of St. Patrick's Day.
   The 1,270-megawatt Unit 2 reactor at Palo Verde Nuclear
Generating Station was not operating on March 16 when the 241,000
gallons of water turned green. The plant had been shut down Feb. 20
for a three-month refueling outage.
   Chemical analysis revealed the cause of the color change _ green
dye _ but officials said it was still speculative to label the
incident as the work of a prankster.
   ``We don't see any connection between the color change and the
holiday,'' said Don Andrews, a spokesman for the Arizona Nuclear
Power Project. ``We're investigating several possibilities. It may
have been intentionally done. Then again, it may not be.''
   Andrews said Monday that plant security officials were
investigating. He said the incident occurred in a 44-foot-deep
stainless steel-lined pool that holds water in which highly
radioactive fuel rods taken from the Unit 2 nuclear reactor are
stored after use.
   The rods are submerged in water that absorbs radioactive
neutrons and gamma rays. Andrews said the rods are being stored
on-site until federal officials build an underground repository for
permanent disposal.
   U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission officials said they have
determined that ``nothing harmful was added to the pool.
   Greg Cook, a spokesman for the NRC's Region 5 office in Walnut
Creek, Calif., said the commission would deal harshly with anyone
responsible for the prank at the $9.3 billion, triple-reactor plant.
   ``If it turns out that someone was playing a prank, that
individual may need to have his sense of humor recalibrated,'' Cook
said. ``A nuclear power plant is the wrong place to horse around.''
   Since 1984, there have been at least 16 unusual incidents at
Palo Verde, many involving unresolved mischief or suspected
sabotage. But NRC and Palo Verde officials said they saw no
connection between those incidents and the green water.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
