<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0530 03-30 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0530,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Attacks Tanker In Gulf; Iranian Rebels Battle Khomeini's
Forces</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to raise references to fire aboard tanker
and two Kuwaitis wounded. PICKS up 10th graf, `In the ...' SUBS
last graf, `Iran, which ...,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with details
of attack on Kuwait.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi warplanes attacked and set fire to
a Cypriot tanker off Iran's coast today. Iranian rebels said their
forces killed 2,000 of Ayatollah Khomeini's Revolutionary Guards in
a two-day battle in southwestern Iran.
   The Kuwaiti Defense Ministry said Kuwaiti forces clashed today
with three Iranian gunboats that had opened fire on Kuwait's
Bubiyan Island in the northern end of the Persian Gulf. Two Kuwaiti
soldiers were wounded.
   And Iran said its warplanes dropped 10 tons of bombs on an
northern Iraqi provincial capital. And Iraq said it fired three
long-range missiles into the central Iranian city of Isfahan,
ancient capital of the Persian empire.
   The Iraqi-backed National Liberation Army of Iran said in a
communique telexed from its headquarters in Baghdad that an assault
force of 15 brigades has returned to Iraq after a two-day offensive
into Iran's oil-rich southwestern Khuzestan province.
   The rebel force, fighting to topple Khomeini's Islamic regime,
claimed its forces also wounded 1,500 Iranian troops and captured
508. Rebel losses were listed as 30 killed and 92 wounded. The
rebel force included two battalions of women fighters and tanks.
   The rebels claimed they captured or destroyed Iranian equipment
including 17 Korean War-era U.S.-built M-47 tanks, armored vehicles
and rocket launchers worth an estimated $100 million.
   The Baghdad communique said the rebels decimated nine battalions
of Iran's 77th Khorassan Division in the fighting south of the
garrison city of Dezful.
   Iraqi jets fired a missile into the Cypriot supertanker Anax,
setting its engine room on fire but causing no casualties, shipping
executives reported.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit said the
259,447-ton vessel was hit in an Iraqi air raid, although Baghdad
had not reported any ship attack today.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said Iraqi
planes hit two tankers off Iran Tuesday night. There was no
confirmation of those attacks.
   The Anax, which was also hit by Iraqi warplanes Dec. 2, was
attacked south of Iran's big Kharg island oil terminal in the
northern Gulf with a full load of oil. It was on charter to the
National Iranian Tanker Co.
   Both sides have resumed the ``tanker war'' in the last two
weeks, hitting about a dozen vessels. Two Iranian tankers were set
ablaze in an Iraqi air raid on Kharg March 19, killing at least 50
seamen.
   Nearly 500 ships have been attacked by both sides since 1981 and
nearly 300 seamen killed.
   In other action today, Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia,
reported that a squadron of Iranian fighter-bombers attacked three
``important military garrisons'' in Sulaimaniyeh city, an Iraqi
provincial capital in the northeastern mountains.
   The communique said dozens of people were killed in the attacks,
in which the regional state-run radio and television headquarters
was also hit. It was one of the heaviest bombing raids by Iran's
badly depleted air force reported in a year.
   Iran said it was launched in retaliation for Iraqi chemical bomb
attacks on three Kurdish towns in the northeast March 16-17 in
which Tehran claims 5,000 civilians were killed and 5,000 injured.
   The towns had been captured by Iranian Revolutionary Guards, who
have pushed 15 miles into Kurdistan, where ethnic Kurds have been
in rebellion against Baghdad.
   The Iranians claim to have seized 540 square miles of Iraqi
territory in the two-week old offensive. Iraq has admitted losing
ground, but given no details.
   The Kuwait News Agency reported two Kuwait soldiers were wounded
today in a skirmish initiated by Iranian gunboats at Bubiyan
Island, 15 miles south of Iraq's coast. It did not say if the
Iranian vessels were struck.
   Shipping executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the Iranians boats escaped Kuwaiti shellfire.
   Iran, which last year fired several missiles into Kuwait waters,
accuses the gulf Arab state of aiding Iraq in the 7{-year-old
Persian Gulf war.
   A Kuwaiti communique declared that Kuwait, which is the closest
state to the Iran-Iraq war zone, ``reserves the right to respond to
any assault on its territory or infringement on its sovereignty.''
   The attack came only a few days after the Kuwaitis had
approached Tehran, seeking to improve relations that deteriorated
sharply seven months ago.
</TEXT>
