<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Arrests     03-30 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Arrests,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Members Arrested During Lunchtime Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 160 men and
women protesting a pending labor bill that would restrict union
rights, a top union official said today.
   Frank Meintjies, spokesman for the Congress of South African
Trade Unions, the nation's largest labor federation, said members
of three unions were arrested Tuesday as they responded to a call
for lunchtime rallies.
   Police had said in their daily unrest report they had arrested
124 men and women in industrial areas for gathering illegally and
refusing to disperse. Police gave no further details, except to say
that they had used batons and dogs to disperse one group.
   Meintjies said those arrested were members of the Food and
Allied Workers Union, the Paper and Allied Workers Union and the
National Metal Workers Union. They were protesting the government's
Labor Relations Amendment Bill, pending before Parliament, which
would make unauthorized strikes more difficult and require unions
to pay employers' damages for illegal strikes.
   Most of the Congress of South African Trade Union's 750,000
members are blacks, who have no representation in Parliament.
   The congress issued a statement Tuesday listing incidents of
what it termed ``state repression'' against union affiliates during
the past mongth, including detentions, police raids on offices and
removal of union property and records. It has been making similar
complaints for the past year, accusing the government of harassment.
   Police replied in a statement today, saying they do not comment
on ``routine police duties, such as the visiting of premises,
confiscation of property.''
   It also said, ``The police do not act against people because
they belong to certain organizations.''
   However, in the few cases of emergency detainees which have
reached the courts in the past 21 months, the government has often
listed membership or participation in an organization as its reason
for keeping people in detention without charge.
   One such case is that of Zwelakhe Sisulu, editor of the New
Nation newspaper, closed last week. Answering his appeal to be
freed or charged with a crime, the government said he was being
held because of his participation in the National Education Crisis
Committee, a lawful organization, and because of his journalistic
activities. Sisulu denied he was a member of the committee.
</TEXT>
