<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 0952EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ACLU-Abortion     03-30 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ACLU-Abortion,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ACLU Opposes Restraining Order On Abortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union is
challenging an order that blocked a woman from having an abortion
because her estranged husband objected to her ending the pregnancy.
   The woman has a constitutional right to an abortion that the
judge should not have interfered with, the group said, citing the
Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion.
   The ACLU said it would go to court today to ask state judge
David S. Young to vacate the restraining order he granted last week
to Michael Jon Reynolds, whose wife Jennifer Franks Reynolds is
about two months pregnant.
   Utah is one of four states with laws requiring wives to notify
husbands of abortion decisions, said Planned Parenthood spokeswoman
Mary Carlson. However, Utah is the only state in which the
notification law hasn't been challenged in court or appealed.
   The ACLU said if Young doesn't change his ruling, it will take
the case to the Utah Court of Appeals.
   ``We feel (the order) is shocking and a restriction of personal
liberties,'' said Robyn E. Blumner, ACLU executive director. If the
order is allowed to stand, ``Utah will find itself once again a
target of national mockery,'' she said.
   Blumner said the case demonstrates that the state law should be
repealed.
   ACLU spokeswoman Michele Parish-Pixler said the U.S. Supreme
Court has ruled that no one can stop a woman from ending a
pregnancy in its first trimester. ``It's over-reaching on the part
of the judge to issue any type of restraint on the first
trimester,'' she said.
   Reynolds, who is seeking a divorce and custody of the couple's
10-month-old infant as well as the unborn child, obtained the
restraining order because he is morally opposed to abortion, said
his attorney, Evan Hurst.
   Mrs. Reynolds was served with the restraining order on the day
she was leaving home to have the abortion performed.
   Mrs. Reynolds' attorney, Julie Bryan, said the U.S. Supreme
Court ruled in the landmark Roe vs. Wade decision that husbands
have no veto power over their wives' abortion decisions.
   The high court said that when a husband and wife disagree over
an abortion, ``the view of only one of the two marriage partners
can prevail. Inasmuch as it is the woman who physically bears the
child and who is the more directly and immediately affected by the
pregnancy ... the balance weighs in her favor,'' Bryan said,
quoting from the decision.
   Reynolds' attorneys plan to argue that the Roe vs. Wade case
applies only to the state, not to private individuals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
