<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-FactoryOrders     03-30 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Factory Orders,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drop Is Second Straight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods fell 0.8 percent in February, the second consecutive monthly
decline, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said that orders for durable and
non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $210.86 billion
last month following a 0.6 percent January decline.
   The February drop was the largest since a 1.4 percent setback in
August. The back-to-back declines were the first such since the
summer of 1986.
   But analysts said they were not overly concerned about the
setbacks, contending that manufacturing will still be one of the
top performing sectors this year.
   They said the declines did show that economic growth slowed in
the first three months of the year as businesses cut back on orders
in an effort to work down a high level of unsold goods.
   But the production cutbacks have been less severe than once
feared and economists are now much more confident that the country
will be able to get through this year without a recession.
   The February setback included a drop of 1.1 percent in orders
for durable goods, which fell to a seasonally adjusted $118.5
billion. In an advance report last week, the government had put the
decline at a slightly larger 1.8 percent.
   Orders for non-durable goods, items not expected to last three
years, fell 0.4 percent in February to $97.9 billion.
   In the major categories, defense orders dropped 8.2 percent to
$8.4 billion. Without that decline, orders would have fallen 0.5
percent last month.
   Orders in the key category of non-military capital goods fell
3.9 percent last month to $33.4 billion. This category is expected
to provide major strength this year as manufacturers boost spending
on expansion projects to meet growing export demand for American
goods.
   Orders for transportation equipment were one of the few
categories showing strength last month, climbing 3.5 percent to $30
billion, with the aircraft component showing an even larger 6.8
percent increase.
   Shipments of manufactured goods edged up a slight 0.1 percent in
February to $207.4 billion.
</TEXT>
