<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1028EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CollegeDeseg     03-30 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-College Deseg,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Refiles Desegregation Suit Against Alabama
Universities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has refiled a
massive desegregation suit against Alabama's public universities,
alleging that state officials deliberately continued a system of
separate colleges for blacks and whites.
   The refiling of the 21-page lawsuit on Tuesday was prompted by a
ruling last year by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta, which found that significant errors had been made before
and during trial in federal court in Birmingham in 1985. The case
was initally filed in 1983.
   U.S. District Judge U.W. Clemon had ruled that Alabama maintains
vestiges of a dual school system. But before he could begin the
remedy phase of the case, his ruling was appealed by the state.
   The 11th Circuit ruled that Clemon, Alabama's first black
federal judge, should have stepped down because he took part in
landmark civil rights cases when he was a private attorney.
   ``I would not agree that the case is starting from ground zero
again,'' Nathaniel Douglas of the Justice Department's Civil Rights
Division said Tuesday from Washington.
   ``There have been efforts to resolve the case by negotiation,
and we are ready to continue to do that.''
   The suit filed by Douglas and his staff again charges that state
education officials have ``perpetuated a racial dual system in
public higher education.''
   The Justice Department said two of Alabama's predominantly black
schools _ Alabama A&M in Huntsville and Alabama State in Montgomery
_ operate near predominantly white schools and were intended for
black students only, while whites attended the other institutions.
   Justice Department lawyers said evidence exists of intentions by
state authorities to maintain the vestiges of the dual school
system.
   Federal attorneys cited a 1975 planning document of the Alabama
Commission on Higher Education that said ``with Alabama State and
Alabama A&M to meet the needs of the state's Negro citizens and
with the University of Alabama and Auburn University as major state
institutions, the state seemed relatively well served.''
   The Justice Department said state officials continue to allocate
``far greater resources'' to the major white schools than to the
predominantly black institutions.
   State authorities said the predominantly white and black schools
in Huntsville and Montgomery are the result of decades-old patterns
of preference by students.
</TEXT>
