<1ST_LINE>d a PM-ArmandHammer-Israel     03-30 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armand Hammer-Israel,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Jewish Groups Pledge Support For Hammer's Arab Center
in Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort to prove that Jews and Arabs can
live in harmony, oil tycoon Armand Hammer and local Jewish groups
have pledged to build a $30 million community center in an
impoverished Arab suburb of Tel Aviv.
   ``We will set an example for the rest of Israel and the Arab
world that Jews and Arabs can live together,'' Hammer said Tuesday.
   Hammer and fellow industrialist Guilford Glazer said they will
raise $1.6 million to help build the schools and recreation
facilities in Ajami-Lev Yaffo, a blighted suburb of Tel Aviv where
more than 12,000 Israeli Arabs live.
   The Jewish Federation Council of Greater Los Angeles hopes to
raise $10 million for the project.
   Hammer, chairman of Occidental Petroleum, said recent violence
in the predominantly Arab West Bank and Gaza Strip had nothing to
do with the center's conception. The territories were captured by
Israel in the 1967 Mideast War.
   Planning for the community center began more than two years ago,
he said.
   ``This center will bring people together,'' Hammer said. ``It
will restore pride and provide education and essential social
services so they can have peace of mind and body. Then, and only
then, can they hope to plan for the future.''
   The complex will feature upgraded elementary and high schools,
recreation and sports facilities, a library, and an auditorium.
</TEXT>
