<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1044EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-AsbestosFine     03-30 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asbestos Fine,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Companies Receive Record Fine For Asbestos Removal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two companies have been fined $130,000
each for the improper removal of asbestos during the demolition of
an old factory, a federal prosecutor said today.
   The fines were imposed for violations of the Clean Air Act, and
the combined $260,000 penalty was the largest ever imposed in the
nation for violation of the act's asbestos regulations, said U.S.
Attorney Stanley A. Twardy Jr.
   Consent decrees between the government and Big Apple Wrecking
Corp. of Middle Village, N.Y., and General DataComm Industries Inc.
of Naugatuck were filed Tuesday in federal court in New Haven.
   General DataComm owned the former Uniroyal Corp. shoe plant in
Naugatuck when it was razed about two years ago. Big Apple was the
demolition contractor.
   The federal government charged in a June 27, 1986, complaint
that the two companies failed to provide adequate notification to
the Environmental Protection Agency before removing asbestos from
the demolition site. The complaint also alleged that the contractor
failed to wet the asbestos during the removal and disposal process.
   After the complaint was filed, an injunction was imposed
requiring the remaining demolition to be completed in compliance
with federal regulations.
   ``In a state such as Connecticut, with its constant renovation
and demolition of aging industrial facilities,'' Twardy said, ``it
is crucial that proper precautions be taken by contractors in order
to prevent asbestos from being emitted into the air.''
</TEXT>
