<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Meese-Byrd 1stLd-Writethru a0558 03-30 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Byrd, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0558,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Leader Calls Meese `Crown Jewel of Sleaze'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 7th-11th grafs, A Republican, to update with Packwood
also calling for Meese resignation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd called
today for the resignation of Attorney General Edwin Meese III,
calling Meese ``the crown jewel of the sleaze factor in Reagan
administration history.''
   ``He ought to get out,'' Byrd, D-W.Va., told reporters. ``The
country cannot have confidence in the Justice Department when the
top law enforcement officer obviously has to spend an inordinate
amount of his time defending himself.''
   ``He should be spending his time fighting the war on drugs,
crime,'' Byrd said.
   Byrd opened his regular morning meeting with reporters by
saying: ``Mr. Meese has become the crown jewel of the sleaze factor
in Reagan administration history.''
   Byrd said he usually would not call on any official to resign
who hadn't been indicted for a crime, ``but we're talking about the
top law enforcement officer in this country.''
   ``It's just cloud after cloud after cloud, building in layers
over his head to the point where all confidence in this agency is
being seriously eroded,'' Byrd said.
   ``The president ought to ask somebody, if he doesn't want to ask
him himself, to ask Mr. Meese to step aside, step down,'' Byrd said.
   A Republican senator also called today for Meese to step aside.
   ``You finally reach a place where there is a cloud of suspicion,
a sufficient cloud of suspicion, that I think you owe it to the
president to remove yourself,'' Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon told
reporters at an informal news conference.
   Packwood said he did not expect Reagan would ask Meese for his
resignation.
   ``The president will clearly not fire a friend,'' Packwood said.
``The president does not do that to a friend.''
   Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns, Assistant Attorney General
William Weld and four of their aides abruptly resigned on Tuesday.
Burns and Weld offered little public explanation, but told
associates they were concerned that the nearly year-long criminal
probe of Meese is hurting the entire Justice Department, according
to several department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``I don't really see how he (Meese) can expect to continue to
lead the department after resignations and circumstances like
this,'' former Attorney General Elliot Richardson said on the CBS
show ``This Morning.''
   ``This man is the head of the chief legal agency, the law
enforcement agency of the United States government. And there comes
a point at which the mere fact that he is not indicted is
insufficient,'' said Richardson, who was attorney general during
the Nixon administration.
   ``I think it's just an extraordinary disaster,'' Rep. Barney
Frank, D-Mass., said of the resignations. ``...The attorney general
should quit. ...It's now clear that he can't run that department,
that we're paying a very high price for his stubborness.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
