<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1056EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Mail-OrderTaxes     03-30 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mail-Order Taxes,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors Group Says Mail-Order Sellers Tax Advantage Threatens
Main Street</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Governors' Association told
Congress today that a sales-tax advantage held by mail-order
sellers ``threatens the future of Main Street America.''
   ``Thousands of small retail businesses that support our
communities and local citizen programs and generate jobs will not
be able to compete in a market in which mail-order firms have a
price advantage that is greater than the actual profit margins of
these community businesses,'' said Gov. George Sinner of North
Dakota.
   Sinner, speaking for his fellow governors, urged a House
Judiciary subcommittee to give the states authority to tax
mail-order sales to out-of-state customers.
   That authority was wiped out by a 1967 Supreme Court ruling. The
court held that a state could not require a mail-order seller to
collect sales tax if the company's only contacts with the state
were in mailing catalogs and delivering merchandise by mail or
public package service.
   As a result, such giant mail-order companies as Maine-based L.L.
Bean can sell by mail to the other 49 states for prices on which no
taxes are collected. The decision does not affect companies such as
Sears, which have outlets in every state.
   Representatives of state and local governments say they are
losing more than $2 billion in sales taxes each year because of the
inability to collect on sales by out-of-state catalog companies,
television shopping clubs and the like.
   A House Ways and Means subcommittee already has approved a bill
by Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., that would allow states to require
large out-of-state retailers to collect the tax. Similar bills are
pending before the Judiciary subcommittee on commercial law.
   Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, a Judiciary member, said his bill
would allow a state to require a retailer to collect sales tax only
if the company regularly solicits sales in that state. It would
apply only to companies whose annual gross receipts exceed $12.5
million or whose sales in a state exceed $500,000.
   William J. Park, president of George W. Park Seed Co., Inc.,
Greenwood, S.C., opposed the bills. He said his company's average
mail order is $32 which, assuming a sales tax averaging 5 percent
nationwide, would generate a $1.60 tax.
   ``It would be prohibitive to collect the estimated tax of $1.60
if the customers did not voluntarily send it. We certainly could
not afford to pay it ourselves,'' Park said, adding that his
company averaged an after-tax net return of 3.5 percent last year.
   Mayor Bob Isaac of Colorado Springs, Colo., speaking for the
National League of Cities, said representatives of state and local
governments are close to agreeing on how to divide revenues from
mail-order tax collections among affected states, cities and
counties. Such an agreement is essential, he said.
   Isaac said he does not take lightly a concern expressed by some
state officials about being ordered by Congress to channel some tax
revenues down to cities and counties. But a reading of the Supreme
Court sales-tax decision ``provides the rationale for concluding
that such a requirement does not amount to an interference with a
state's prerogative,'' Isaac said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
