<DOCNO> AP880330-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GolfPesticide     03-30 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Golf Pesticide,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insecticide Use Restricted as Bird-Killer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Environmental Protection
Agency has banned use of the insecticide diazinon on golf courses
and sod farms because it kills too many birds, the agency said
today.
   The decision by Administrator Lee M. Thomas overrules an
administrative law judge, who on Jan. 25 found that the benefits of
using diazinon outweighed the risks and recommended continued use
under certain restrictions.
   The decision, effective on publication in the Federal Register
in a few days, represents the first time that the use of a
pesticide has been canceled solely because it killed birds, said
spokesman Al Heier. However, the harm to birds was a large part of
the reasons behind the 1972 ban on DDT.
   About 8 million pounds of diazinon are used each year to control
insects on farms, in nurseries and around homes and gardens as well
as on golf courses and sod farms. The two banned uses account for
about 572,000 pounds.
   In September 1986, the agency announced intent to cancel golf
course and sod farm use. At the time, it said it knew of 60
instances in 18 states where diazinon was a known or suspected
cause of large-scale bird killings. Many involved golf courses,
which some species favor as feeding sites.
   Four hundred ninety-four companies hold federal licenses to sell
diazinon products. The major manufacturer is Ciba-Geigy Corp.
</TEXT>
