<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson-Democrats 2ndLd-Writethru a0550 03-30 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Democrats, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0550,780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 17 grafs new with meeting comments; picks up 14th graf
pvs, ``He also said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson huddled today with the top ranks
of Washington's political establishment, a summit meeting one
participant called ``a bonding of the Democratic Party'' with the
preacher-turned-politician.
   With such party luminaries as Clark Clifford and John White at
his side, the Democratic presidential candidate said the meeting
was totally positive. Clifford and White denied there were
discussions of fears that Jackson could drag the party's ticket
down in the fall.
   ``No, not at all,'' said White, a former chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, told reporters after the meeting.
   ``We only see that in the press,'' said California Assembly
Speaker Willie Brown, Jackson's national campaign chairman. ``Maybe
people don't want to say that in front of us.''
   Jackson said the breakfast session was ``bringing together
Democrats who have traditional investment in the interests of the
country and the party and those who are new to the process.
   ``In this instance, we bring together old wineskins and new
wine, but the old wineskins are expanding and making room for new
wine,'' he added, using one of his favorite phrases from the 1984
campaign.
   Jackson picked up the backing of White.
   ``This meeting is a new maturing of the political process in
America,'' White said. ``It represents a growing-up of America. It
represents a bonding of the Democratic Party and a bond that
recognizes no class.''
   The one negative that came up at the meeting, according to
participants, was a question to Jackson about his relationship with
Black Muslim leader Louis Farrakhan.
   White said Jackson ``quoted Jesus about casting the first stone
and forgiveness and so anybody who hasn't made mistakes...let's not
be casting stones at each other about the past.''
   Farrakhan campaigned with Jackson early in the 1984 campaign,
but the tie was cut after the Black Muslim leader called Judaism as
``gutter religion'' and called Adolf Hitler ``a great man.''
   Many of those attending were already Jackson supporters,
including former federal budget director Bert Lance, Texas
Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower and Brown.
   Jackson's campaign manager, Gerald Austin, said attendance did
not indicate they were endorsing Jackson, but it would give them a
chance to get to know him.
   ``A lot more people want to talk to Jesse Jackson now than they
did a week ago,'' he said in reference to Jackson's big win in
Michigan on Saturday.
   The victory was followed Tuesday by an equally big loss in
Connecticut to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson, however, hailed Connecticut as a victory anyway,
because he got 70,000 votes. He said that showed his campaign is
expanding.
   He also said he would not react to the sharp criticism leveled
at him Tuesday by rival Albert Gore Jr., but instead would ``let
the people speak.''
   In the first harsh attack by a Jackson rival, Gore, the senator
from Tennessee, said Jackson has a ``complete and total lack of
experience in the national government. He hasn't served a single
day in the national government, or had a single day's experience in
foreign policy.''
   Answering questions in New York, Gore added, ``I also cannot
disagree more with Jesse Jackson's views on many foreign policy
issues. I categorically reject his notion that there's a moral
equivalence between Israel and the PLO. ... And I am dismayed by
his embrace of Arafat and Castro.''
   Jackson said he was unaware of ``any organized `stop Jackson'
movement'' but that in the face of his success, some Democrats
``are reacting with a sense of history, others are reacting with a
sense of hysteria.''
   The most prominent non-candidate, New York Gov. Mario Cuomo,
said it was wrong to talk of a ``stop Jackson'' movement.
   ``I reject the suggestion that it somehow presents us with a
dilemma if Jesse Jackson wins,'' said Cuomo. ``The person who gets
the most votes should be the candidate and all talk of introducing
somebody to stop Gore, to stop Dukakis or to stop Jackson, that's
all equally wrong.''
   Today's meeting, according to White, was set up even before the
Michigan contest.
   He said Jackson had indicated an interest in ``meeting with the
party regulars and talking about the parts of the political world
he might not be familiar with.''
   Ann Lewis, an adviser to Jackson said, ``The original idea was
to get Jesse together with the Washington establishment ... to
listen to them talk about issues and policies and then to answer
any questions they might have about him.''
</TEXT>
