<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0456 03-30 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0456,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supermarkets Reopen, Indicating Major Rupture in Anti-Noriega
Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with major supermarket chains
opening, government saying banks to reopen. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's three largest
supermarket chains reopened their stores today, signaling a major
rupture in a 10-day general strike aimed at toppling strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The government announced that the nation's banks, closed since
March 3 because of a cash shortage brought on by U.S. economic
sanctions, would reopen Thursday with limited service.
   It announced tight restrictions on withdrawals from savings and
checking accounts.
   The Gago, Rey and Super 99 markets in the capital were doing
brisk business after Panamanians rushed to buy food and essentials
that have been virtually unattainable.
   The weakening of the strike came two days after a harsh
crackdown on leaders of the National Civic Crusade, which is
leading the anti-Noriega fight. More than 20 crusade directors were
arrested Monday in a raid by soldiers and state security agents.
Most were detained overnight, then released.
   Owners of the reopened stores could not be reached for comment.
Crusade leaders, who vowed to continue the strike until Noriega
left Panama, have been reluctant to talk since their arrests. Some
of those not detained were said to be in hiding.
   The Roman Catholic church Tuesday joined opposition leaders in
calling for Noriega's resignation. But Noriega, leader of the
15,000-member Defense Forces and the power behind the civilian
government, said Tuesday night he had no intention of stepping down.
   ``Here, it is not one man who is the problem,'' said Noriega,
who blames his problems on what he considers a U.S. slander
campaign against him. ``This is a matter of dignity and conviction
involving the entire hemisphere.''
   In a speech to delegates of a Solidarity With Panama conference
in the capital, Noriega condemned the presence of the U.S.
helicopter carrier Okinawa on the Pacific end of the Panama Canal.
It passed through the canal Tuesday on its way to its home port,
San Diego.
   The U.S. Defense Department said in Washington that the passage
was ``routine.'' But Noriega called it ``a threat and an
aggression.'' There was no immediate indication how long the vessel
would stay in the area.
   Noriega claimed the United States had spent more than $100
million in the effort to topple him. ``But with all the gold in the
world they have not been able to bring this people or this
commander or these Defense Forces to their knees,'' he said,
shaking his fist to wild applause.
   Delegates from about 25 Latin American and Caribbean countries
attended the conference, but few represented governments. About 400
spectators were on hand in the convention center.
   Noriega's forces used a harsh irritant sprayed from water
cannons, tear gas and birdshot to break up a march Monday by 10,000
anti-government protesters. Many people were beaten with rubber
hoses and dozens were arrested.
   Almost all those detained were released by Tuesday. But Carlos
Gonzalez de la Lastra, a top leader of the opposition National
Civil Crusade, was still held at a military intelligence center
early today.
   He had not been allowed access to a lawyer or visits by family
members.
   ``We're worried. We have been told by sources in the Defense
Forces that he has been beaten,'' his wife Vilma, told The
Associated Press.
   Gonzalez de la Lastra apparently was not released with the
others because he had been out on bond on a previous sedition
charge.
   A church spokesman told a news conference on Tuesday that Panama
City Archbishop Monsignor Marcos McGrath contacted Noriega and the
opposition and the archbishop had ``a positive impression'' about
prospects for mediation.
   But the spokesman, auxiliary Archbishop Mons. Oscar Brown, said
there's still a lot to be done, ``and because of that we cannot
have an excessive optimism.''
   In a statement, the church said a committee of bishops met with
Noriega last week and asked him ``to separate himself from his
position as soon as possible.'' The statement said Noriega failed
to respond to the request.
   This critical phase of Panama's 10-month-old political and
economic crisis began Feb. 26, when Noriega orchestrated the ouster
of President Eric Delvalle. Hours earlier, Delvalle had tried to
fire Noriega, who has been indicted in the United States on
drug-trafficking charges.
   The Reagan administration continues to recognize Delvalle, who
is in hiding, as president. It has frozen Panamanian government
funds in U.S. banks, denying this country a supply of its official
currency, the U.S. dollar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1130EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     03-30 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Kill 11 Tamil Rebels, Government Bans Rallies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian peacekeeping troops killed 11
Tamil rebels, captured three others and recovered 17 AK-47
automatic rifles from a hideout in the jungles of north central Sri
Lanka, officials said today.
   Sri Lankan military officials, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules, said the attack late Tuesday was in Mankulam, near
the district capital of Anuradhpura, about 105 miles northeast of
Colombo. It came after rebels killed 10 Sinhalese farmers in the
region.
   The Sri Lankan government, meanwhile, announced a ban on all
meetings opposing elections in four of the island's nine provinces.
   ``The Cabinet discussed a report that certain political parties
were planning to hold meetings exhorting the people not to vote in
the elections,'' an announcement by the Information Ministry said.
   ``As this is an undemocratic step and may lead to public unrest
in those areas, it was decided that no permission for such meetings
should be granted by the police,'' it said.
   The elections are scheduled for April 28 and 436 candidates from
three parties are running for 155 seats. Sri Lanka Freedom Party,
the largest opposition party, is boycotting the polls and demanding
the government hold general elections.
   The attack in north central Sri Lanka came after suspected Tamil
militants Tuesday planted a bomb on a passenger bus in the same
area, killing 10 Sinhalese farmers and injuring 15 others.
   ``The haul of AK-47 rifles is regarded as the largest single
haul of the this type of weaponry by the Indian troops,'' a
military official said.
   More than 50,000 Indian troops are in Sri Lanka to disarm Tamil
militants under a peace accord signed last July. The accord grants
some autonomy to minority Tamils living in the north and east but
it has been opposed both by Tamil and Sinhalese extremists.
   Tamils say it does not give enough autonomy while Sinhalese
nationalists claim it grants too many concessions to the Tamils.
   In another incident, Sri Lankan police today opened fire ``at a
mob of more than 2,000 people who tried to storm the Trincomalee
police station and a nearby army camp,'' a military official
reported.
   Three policemen were seriously injured and many in the mob were
wounded, the official said. Trincomalee is an important port town
in the Eastern Province.
   The crowd was demanding the release of all Tamil political
prisoners and withdrawal from the area of Sri Lankan security
forces. The security forces are protecting Sinhalese settlements in
the east.
   More than 135 Sinhalese civilians have been killed this month in
attacks blamed on Tamil militants of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam. The group is the largest and most powerful rebel
organization.
   The government says the rebels are launching these attacks to
drive out Sinhalese and Moslems from the Eastern Province and
establish complete dominance. Tamils say the government has
deliberately settled Sinhalese people in the area to upset the
Tamils traditional majority in the area.
   Tamils, who are mainly Hindu, make up about 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people while the Sinhalese, who are Buddhists,
comprise 75 percent.
   Tamils say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who
control the government and the military.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1146EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Posner     03-30 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Posner,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge `Outraged' Over Posner Job Contact With Court Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court reporter for the federal judge who
sentenced millionaire industrialist Victor Posner in a tax evasion
case has been in contact with Posner's organization for a job, the
judge said in court today.
   U.S. District Judge Eugene P. Spellman, visibly perturbed, said
he first learned of conversations between court reporter Mario
Contillo and Posner on Monday afternoon.
   ``I'm not saying his conduct was illegal, but I feel it was
reprehensible, especially involving a friend of 30 years,'' said
Spellman, referring to Contillo, who the judge said was offered ``a
substantial amount'' to work for Posner. Details of the job were
not disclosed in court.
   Posner pleaded no contest Sept. 29 to evading more than $1.2
million in federal taxes by inflating the value of land he donated
to a Bible college as a tax exemption.
   Posner, who had faced up to 40 years in prison in an income tax
evasion case, was ordered to pay more than $4 million in back taxes
and fines and to give $3 million to help Florida's homeless in an
income tax evasion case.
   The Miami Beach businessman, whose holdings include controlling
interests in Royal Crown Cola and Arby's, also was sentenced to
5,000 hours in community service over five years.
   Spellman called U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Neal Cartusciello, who prosecuted the case, and Mary
Clark, an attorney for Posner, to a special hearing in his
courtroom to discuss his findings.
   Contillo announced last Friday that he was giving up his court
position, Spellman said. Spellman said he wanted Kellner to ``to
evaluate and comment if he wishes,'' on the disclosure.
   ``I don't know all the facts but I felt that as a member of the
federal judiciary it was incumbent upon me to draw attention to
this matter so it could be made public as quickly as possible,''
the judge said.
   ``When I found out, I went through a series of emotions ...
distress and outrage ... that a member of my staff is guilty at the
very least of impropriety,'' he said.
   Efforts by The Associated Press to reach Contillo at his office
or at home by telephone today were unsuccessful. Renee Mottram, a
spokeswoman for Posner, said that Contillo is not employed by
Posner at this time.
   Spellman said the job conversations took place sometime after
the Feb. 12 sentencing of Posner.
   Posner's 1986 conviction was set aside because of jury
irregularities, and he entered the no contest plea a month before
he was to be retried.
   Spellman said today it was his understanding that the court
reporter gave the impression the judge condoned his job
discussions, but the judge said, ``I had no knowledge of the
conversations and I do not condone them.''
   The judge noted that the 69-year-old Posner is on probation and
said: ``I have not taken this up with probation service. If they
feel that Mr. Posner violated his probation, they have the means to
bring it to the court's attention.
   ``I have no reason to believe it was other than an unthinking
and stupid act.''
   After the judge left the bench, Kellner was asked if he intended
to bring the actions to the attention of a grand jury.
   ``I am hearing this for the first time as you are. All I can say
is we will take a look at it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
