<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ArmsTreaty 2ndLd-Writethru a0578-580 03-30 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0578-580,730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee, by a
vote of 17-2, today gave its approval to the historic treaty
eliminating U.S. and Soviet medium-range nuclear missiles.
   The vote sends the treaty to the full Senate, which is expected
to vote next month after returning from its Easter recess. Leaders
of both parties say the treaty will win far more than the
two-thirds margin it needs to be ratified.
   But some Republicans said today the pact may be in jeopardy
because of a Democratic-backed amendment outlining how the treaty
can be interpreted by the White House. The only dissenting votes
today were cast by Sens. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and Larry Pressler,
R-S.D.
   The treaty, signed Dec. 8 by President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, requires both sides to desroy, within three
years, all nuclear-tipped missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400
miles. It will be the first nuclear arms control pact requiring the
destruction of weapons.
   Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., said the Democratic amendment was
``perhaps unconstitutional and very frankly, it may change my
position with respect to the treaty'' on the floor. But Boschwitz
supported the pact in today's vote.
   Pressler predicted the amendment ``will lead to the defeat of
this treaty because the votes aren't there.''
   But Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., the panel's chairman, said
``the amendment's importance has been exaggerated'' and predicted
its eventual approval by the full Senate.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., called the pact ``a very important
step forward'' for the United States.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., agreed. ``In effect, this is a
small step away from the nuclear brink,'' he told his colleagues.
   Today's vote came a day after the amendment was added, a move
that left some committee Republicans angry and threatening to
oppose the treaty when it comes to the floor.
   ``This has been made partisan, unnecessarily in my view,'' Sen.
Daniel Evans, R-Wash, said Tuesday. ``No one has worked harder for
this treaty than me, but I'm now going to seriously take a look at
whether I can vote for it.''
   Evans and other Republicans were unhappy about the
Democratic-written provision, which was added to the measure with
the help of Helms.
   The provision says no future president can change the U.S.
interpretation of the treaty without the approval of Congress,
either through a new pact or through a separate law.
   The measure arises from a longstanding fight between Reagan and
Congress over Reagan's assertion that the executive branch can
unilaterally change how the U.S. government interprets a treaty.
Congressional Democrats disagree with that statement, which Reagan
has used to justify some tests of his Star Wars missile defense
system.
   The tests would violate the original interpretation of the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
   Democrats want assurances that Reagan or another president won't
assert the same right to re-interpret treaties on the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces pact.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said Reagan already has agreed not
to change the U.S. view of the INF treaty and said the proposal
``is a deliberate attempt to embarrass the president.''
   But Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., told Lugar, ``those of us on
this side did not begin this process,'' a reference to Reagan's
assertion involving executive branch rights on treaty
interpretation.
   Helms said he offered his amendment, which he said made minor
changes in the Democratic-written proposal, to make sure the
Democratic measure was constitutional.
   But Lugar was suspicious. ``I frankly don't know at all what
this is about. I'm sure something important is going on,'' he said,
but ``I don't have any idea.''
   Earlier in the day, the Senate met in a rare secret session to
talk about intelligence estimates about the size of the Soviets'
force of SS-20 missiles, which will be destroyed under the treaty.
   The Soviets have admitted to having 650 of the weapons, but
Helms and other conservative critics argue that U.S. intelligence
estimates show that the Soviets may possess up to 1,000.
Administration officials dispute that contention.
   The secret session was the Senate's first since October 1986. It
was held in the Old Senate Chamber, down the Capitol hall from the
current Senate meeting place. The current chamber was unusable
because it is laced with electronic cables that could be tapped.
   Helms said later that his colleagues, ``heard some things they
hadn't heard before.''
</TEXT>
