<1ST_LINE>r a PM-China-Oxen 1stLd-Writethru a0410 03-30 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Oxen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0410,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Will Take Part In Beijing Presentation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 9-10, `The Chinese...' to CORRECT that Mrs. Miller
leaving late April and ceremony in May, sted she leaving in March
and ceremony in April.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOULTRIE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After the deaths of Milton and Matilda, two
musk oxen given to China by the United States in 1972, a Georgia
widow began a one-person campaign to replace them.
   Next month, Helen Miller travels to Beijing for a ceremony
marking the success of her efforts and the arrival of two new
animals.
   Mrs. Miller said she learned that just as pandas Ling-Ling and
Hsing-Hsing _ gifts from China _ had become popular at the National
Zoo in Washington, millions of Chinese children visited the Beijing
Zoo to see the oxen.
   So in 1980, after learning that the oxen had died, she began a
letter-writing campaign to the White House, the National Zoo and
officials of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
   She felt it was a matter of ``national honor'' to replace the
animals that had been presented when then-President Richard Nixon
made his historic trip to China as the two nations normalized
relations.
   ``I don't just think about things,'' she said in a recent
interview. ``If they are worth thinking about, they are worth
acting on.''
   Musk oxen, found only in Greenland and Arctic regions of North
America, have heavy fur coats and horns that dip down along their
heads and then up. Hunted for years, they now are protected.
   Mrs. Miller eventually learned that the University of Alaska had
a herd of the oxen and went there. University officials agreed to
donate Koyuk and Tanana, a pair flown to China on March 21.
   ``The Chinese are very excited about it,'' said Mrs. Miller, who
departs in late April. ``There's going to be a big presentation
ceremony. It took a long time, but it was interesting every step of
the way.''
   The ceremony, in early May, will be attended by U.S. officials,
the governor of Alaska and the head of the University of Alaska's
School of Arctic Biology, she said.
   Mrs. Miller's husband, Gibbs, died in 1960, leaving her with
four children. After attending vocational school, she got a job as
a construction estimator.
   ``I like to do things that no one else will do,'' said Mrs.
Miller.
   She has been a contestant on four TV game shows, winning a
Brazilian vacation, two cars, a 65-foot mobile home and two furs.
Three of her children also have appeared on game shows.
   Now that the oxen are in China, Mrs. Miller has a new project,
but for now it's a secret.
   ``You put your heart in it and go to work,'' she said.``If you
believe in something strongly enough, then put feet on your
prayers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
