<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0567,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arabs Reported Killed, Troops Close Arab News Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 6th pvs, `Only the...' to UPDATE with
details on clash. Pick up 7th pvs, `In the...' EDITS thereafter to
trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Arab protesters
fought Israeli troops today in defiance of a massive clampdown in
the occupied territories. Hospital officials said two Palestinians
were killed and 24 wounded.
   The army confirmed one death and said three people were wounded
on Land Day, an annual demonstration against Israeli confiscation
of Arab land.
   The West Bank and Gaza Strip were closed, and thousands of extra
police and soldiers were deployed. Six Arabs were killed in the
first Land Day protests 12 years ago.
   Police swept through the offices of a key Arab news service and
ordered it closed for six months.
   A Supreme Court panel denied a foreign press request to allow
media access to the occupied territories, but it ordered the army
to explain within 30 days why journalists should not be allowed
free access.
   Only the territories' 65,000 Jewish settlers were permitted to
travel freely.
   In Beit Sahour near Bethlehem in the West Bank, troops clashed
with about 200 protesters who pelted them with rocks, waved
outlawed Palestinian flags and set tires ablaze.
   An Associated Press reporter in the village saw roadblocks of
boulders, rusted barrels, twisted metal and garbage blocking dozens
of winding streets. Four tires smouldered nearby and hundreds of
baseball sized rocks littered the streets.
   In the West Bank village of Deir Abu Mashal, 20 miles northwest
of Jerusalem, soldiers killed a woman and wounded her husband and
two sons.
   The army and hospital officials gave conflicting accounts.
   Doctors at Ramallah Hospital told The Associated Press troops
entered the home of Wajalah Rabir, 50, while she and her family
were eating breakfast and fatally shot her in the head.
   A visitor to the hospital quoted Mrs. Rabir's 17-year-old
daughter, Zeinab, as saying the soldiers came in and asked if there
were any men in the house.
   The girl told the troops no men were home, but they entered
anyway, the visitor said. The visitor, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, quoted the girl as saying a soldier then shot one
brother who started to run. Other family members then lunged toward
the troops, who opened fire.
   Hospital officials said Mrs. Rabir's husband and two sons were
in serious condition from gunshot wounds. The officials, who have
been barred from speaking to journalists, insisted on anonymity.
   The army said the woman was shot after she attacked a soldier
with a rake. ``All those hurt were hurt during a very aggressive
attack on our soldiers,'' the commander said on Israel radio.
``They attacked with pitchforks, axes, clubs and metal bars in a
very aggressive way.''
   Officials at Nablus' Al Ittihad hospital said another
Palestinian, Khalid Salah, 22, died of a gunshot wound to the back
during a clash with troops in the nearby village of Burqa. They
said another Arab was wounded in the shoulder in that clash.
   The army said it was investigating the death which, according to
U.N. figures, brought to 121 the number of Palestinians killed by
soldiers since unrest broke out in the territories on Dec. 8. One
Israeli soldier has been killed.
   Hospital officials said 24 Palestinians were wounded by gunfire,
including a 12-year-old girl near Hebron.
   In east Jerusalem, police officers swept into the Arab-owned
Palestine Press Service and ordered it closed for six months.
   Ibrahim Kareen, publisher of the service, said police told him
the agency was being closed because it was funded by the Palestine
Liberation Organization. He denied PLO funding and vowed to
continue providing information.
   ``All we need is a telephone,'' Kareen said.
   An extra 4,000 police were stationed in Israel's Arab sectors.
   Telephone lines to Gaza remained severed, troops warned on
loudspeakers that curfew violators would be shot, and Gaza and the
West Bank were closed to most outside traffic.
   Reporters were barred from entering the territories without a
previously arranged army escort, and army spokeswoman Ofra Preuss
said violators would be prosecuted.
   The maximum penalty for entering a closed military area is five
years in prison.
   A general strike was observed in Israel's Arab towns, east
Jerusalem and the West Bank. Dozens of mounted police and foot
patrols moved through east Jerusalem's main Salah Edin Street.
</TEXT>
