<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Demjanjuk     03-30 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demjanjuk Verdict To Be Announced April 18</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The court presiding over the Nazi war crimes
trial of retired U.S. autoworker John Demjanjuk will announce its
verdict on April 18, the government said Wednesday.
   Demjanjuk, 67, is accused of being ``Ivan the Terrible,'' the
guard who operated gas chambers that killed 850,000 Jews at the
Treblinka death camp in Nazi-occupied Poland.
   If convicted, Demjanjuk could be sentenced to death. The
Ukrainian-born defendant claims he is a victim of mistaken identity.
   Demjanjuk was extradited to Israel in February 1986 from the
Cleveland suburb of Seven Hills.
   His trial ended Feb. 10 after a year of testimony. The
three-judge panel reopened hearings for two days in March to
introduce new evidence at the request of defense attorney Yoram
Sheftel.
   Sheftel presented the court with statements from 12 camp
survivors who did not identify Demjanjuk as ``Ivan.''
   At the beginning of the hearings, five prosecution witnesses
identified Demjanjuk as the Treblinka camp guard from photographs.
   The prosecution's key piece of evidence is an alleged SS card
stating that Demjanjuk was trained as a concentration camp guard.
Demjanjuk says the card is a forgery.
</TEXT>
