<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Faure     03-30 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Faure,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Statesman Edgar Faure Dead At 79</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edgar Faure, the brilliant statesman who died
Wednesday at the age of 79, was hailed by friends and foes alike
for his political savvy, intelligence and wit.
   Faure occupied every important post in the French government
except the presidency during a career that spanned four decades.
   President Francois Mitterrand, a fellow socialist, called Faure
``a remarkable man who marked the history of our Republic.''
   Jean-Marie Le Pen, presidential candidate from the extreme-right
National Front, praised Faure's ``intelligence and tolerance,''
despite ``our differing conceptions of political action.''
   The bespectacled, balding father figure, known to the French
simply as ``Edgar,'' was best remembered as one of the nation's
most progressive education ministers.
   Under Gen. Charles De Gaulle, during the 1968 student uprising,
he masterminded vast reforms that allowed French universities more
autonomy.
   Faure was a member of the French Academy and wrote books on
subjects ranging from French oil policy to modern China.
   A Renaissance man, Faure even wrote musical scores. Under the
pseudonym Edgar Sanday, he published detective novels.
   Faure was born on Aug. 18, 1908, in the southwestern city of
Beziers, where his father, an army doctor, was stationed. He
graduated from high school at the age of 15, earned his doctorate
in law at 19 and was a practicing lawyer at 21.
   He was fluent in Russian, and years later, would stun a Soviet
trade delegation negotiating without a translator for four hours
straight, stumbling only once _ over the word ``corkscrew.''
   Yet he had an old-fashioned sense of honor and once challenged a
prominent magazine reporter to a duel for having questioned in
print his motives for reducing taxes on race horses. Notoriously
near-sighted, he was already waving the pistol when a colleague
managed to talk him out of it.
   Faure's successful law career was interrupted by World War II.
In 1942, Faure and his wife Lucie Meyer, the elegant publisher of a
political review, fled France for Algiers.
   After the war, he was financial adviser to Socialist governments
led by his close friend Pierre Mendes-France.
   In 1947, he was elected to public office for the first time,
serving as a deputy for the Jura department in eastern France.
   From that time on, he served in the cabinets of numerous prime
ministers, holding more ministerial appointments than any other
public official.
   Faure's first wife, Lucie Meyer, died in 1977. He is survived by
his second wife, Marie-Jeanne Vuez, and two daughters. Burial will
be Saturday in Paris following services at his church and at the
National Assembly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0117 </DOCNO>
