<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolsSaved     03-30 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schools Saved,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Sold To Raise Money To Keep Cocke County Schools Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SHARP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocke County officials knew they had to
come up with $345,000 quickly to keep public schools open after
spring break. So they decided to sell the county-owned hospital.
   The deal negotiated between the county and Baptist Health
System, which was renting the hospital, benefits everyone, but
primarily prevents the nightmare of closing schools, County
Executive Charles Lewis Moore said Tuesday.
   ``We can't have that,'' he said. ``That's absolutely not
satisfactory to anyone. One concern was that some seniors who have
scholarships and financial assistance would lose it, plus it would
affect employees and parents.''
   The $1 million sale was approved 20-0 by the Cocke County
Legislative Body on Monday night.
   The county lawmakers then provided the school system with
$200,000, the minimum on which the schools could operate the rest
of the term, and agreed to invest the remainder in an industrial
park.
   The sale includes a 74-bed hospital, a 56-bed nursing home and a
building housing three doctors' offices. Baptist Health System,
based in Knoxville, had leased the hospital since 1982, and last
year extended that lease through 1999.
   At any point during those 17 years, Baptist had the option of
buying the hospital for $1.58 million, or $580,000 more than the
actual sale price.
   But county officials say they can get roughly $3.6 million out
of the deal in interest on the remaining $800,000, plus money saved
because the deal exempts the county from funding care of indigents
at the hospital for the next 12 years. That had been costing about
$35,000 a year.
   County officials praised Baptist Health for coming to the
county's rescue.
   ``We frankly had not intended to buy right now,'' said Robert
Chandler, president of Baptist Health System. ``But they were
having some financial problems, especially with funding the school
system. So we felt we could help by buying now. Helping the schools
was our main motivation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
