<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   03-30 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: American politics.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 25
   Red Wing (Minn.) Republican Eagle on George Bush's presidential
campaign:
   If there's any political fallout over the Civil Rights
Restoration Act, it's likely to land on George Bush.
   Although his support of a presidential veto will enhance his
standing with conservatives, it will hinder his efforts to attract
blacks and other minorities into the Republican Party.
   Democrats are sure to exploit the issue. ... Once again, he's
perceived to be (President Reagan's) puppet.
   Democrats will take any fallout they can get. If the election is
close, the failure of the Republican Party to attract more blacks
and minorities because of Bush's stance on the veto might be the
difference.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 25
   The Honolulu Advertiser on the cease-fire in Nicaragua:
   Some sort of humanitarian aid for the Contras is necessary for
the period of phasing down and out. Withdrawing our troops from
Honduras _ with no arms left behind _ is necessary.
   At some point, there must be talks between Washington and
Managua on a more normalized relationship.
   Many will continue to question whether the whole Contra
operation was necessary and worth the cost in terms of bloodshed in
Central America and damage in the U.S. government process.
   There may have been better ways to deal with whatever dangers
the Sandinistas pose in the region.
   Yet it could end up a no-lose situation for President Reagan. If
the cease-fire and peace process work, there is little doubt he
will say that his tough policy worked. And if they fail, he can
blame the Congress and others for killing off the Contras.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 27
   The Evansville (Ind.) Courier on preventing teen suicides:
   We are shocked and saddened by the three suicides involving
present and former Reitz High School students. Yet our grief now
must give way to concern.
   There seems no direct connection among the three, other than
what experts call a copycat syndrome. One person commits suicide;
another troubled individual learns of it, even sees it as an escape
from despair, and the chain reaction begins.
   It's critical now that those closest to students _ parents,
school personnel, classmates _ see that the chain is broken. ...
   Talk to your children, talk to your classmates, and if you're
troubled yourself, seek someone who will listen _ no problem is so
insurmountable.
   So often when we learn of suicide, we hear the word
helplessness. No, we can't help those who have already taken their
lives, but for others who may be troubled, we are not helpless,
especially now that our consciousness has been raised so tragically.
   We must be alert; we must care; we must talk.
</TEXT>
