<DOCNO> AP880330-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrainDisease     03-30 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brain Disease,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Lab Workers May Have Gotten Brain Infection from Job Exposure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two laboratory workers died of a rare brain
infection called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, and both might have
resulted from on-the-job exposure to contaminated tissue, doctors
report.
   The cases were reported in separate letters to the editor in
Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine.
   In one letter, Douglas C. Miller of New York University Medical
Center described the case of a 62-year-old woman who had worked in
a medical lab for 22 years. Her duties included preparing slices of
human brains.
   After she died of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, doctors discovered
she had worked with tissue from two people who had also died of the
disease 11 and 16 years earlier.
   Miller said the woman's illness ``most likely'' resulted from
occupational exposure.
   In the other letter, Lucian Sitwell and colleagues from Ottawa
Civic Hospital in Canada outlined a similar case in a 75-year-old
physician who dissected tissue, mostly from animals, in a medical
school.
   Sitwell said the man may have been exposed to tissue from sheep
that had scrapie. Some experts theorize that scrapie and
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease are caused by the same, so far
unidentified infectious agent.
   Creutzfeldt-Jacob diseases causes slow, progressive loss of
mental faculties. It has been spread through transplants of brain
tissue and corneas as well as growth hormone derived from human
pituitary glands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
