<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0437 03-30 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MILWAUKEE</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Teeley comments today; pick up 3rd graf
pvs bgng ``Meanwhile Bush...; Delete final graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush would have ``no
reluctance'' to criticize Jesse Jackson if he is the Democratic
nominee, a spokesman said today.
   Bush, rejoicing in his clear path to the Republican presidential
nomination, is starting to focus on the general election campaign,
including strategy against his eventual Democratic opponent.
   ``If Jackson is the nominee, we will feel very willing to attack
him on the issues. There will be no reticence, there will be no
reluctance,'' Bush spokesman Pete Teeley said aboard Air Force II.
   Jackson's Democratic rivals have left Jackson alone until
recently, working under the conventional assumption that Jackson
could not win the nomination. But as Jackson racks up win after
win, Sen. Albert Gore Jr. has expressed a willingness to criticize
Jackson on the issues and his lack of experience in government.
   Bush, assured of the GOP nomination, will continue to campaign
hard to guard against complacency, Teeley said.
   ``It feels great,'' Bush declared Tuesday, giving a thumbs-up
sign to reporters after learning of the withdrawal of Sen. Bob
Dole, the same day Bush sailed to an overwhelming win in the
Connecticut primary.
   Meanwhile, Bush organizers are scurrying to find new ways to
keep attention focused on the candidate now that he is without a
major GOP rival.
   For one thing, Bush plans to continue to make high-profile
campaign appearances in states with key primaries _ including New
York, Pennsylvania, Ohio and California.
   ``The immediate task ahead is unity,'' Bush told a GOP dinner
Tuesday night after his Connecticut victory was announced. ``We
Republicans have no reason for complacency.''
   He said that Republicans now must present their party as ``a big
party with big open doors.''
   ``The challenges we face will never be met unless we meet them
together, hand-in-hand, as brothers and sisters, as blacks and
whites, as northerners, southerners, East and West, the wealthy and
the wanting,'' he said.
   He complimented Dole for a ``very gracious statement'' in
dropping out of the race. ``I know exactly how he must feel. I was
there, eight years ago,'' Bush said, referring to his unsuccessful
1980 presidential bid.
   Not all Bush supporters were as jubilant about recent
developments as were the vice president and his top strategists.
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, said that Dole's exit could hurt
Bush's chances in the fall campaign now that ``it's obvious he's
going to win the nomination.''
   ``I can't see the fact that the vice president doesn't have any
more opposition is that good for him. It's good to have a
primary,'' said Thompson, a strong Bush backer.
   Thompson, who has been accompanying Bush in his three-day
campaign swing in advance of the April 5 Wisconsin primary, said
many Wisconsin independents and some Republicans are now likely to
vote in the Democratic primary.
   ``Those individuals who come out of a hotly contested primary
can use it as a springboard to solidify the party,'' Thompson said.
   The Republican governor, who earlier in the week had suggested
he would vote for Democrat Jesse Jackson were he a Democrat,
indicated Jackson would be hard for Bush to beat in November.
   ``He (Jackson) is a viable candidate. He's very exciting. I like
the guy,'' Thompson said.
   GOP officials in Wisconsin urged party members who had supported
Dole against crossing over and voting in the Democratic primary
next week.
   And top Bush aides conceded that lack of a contest could steal
the spotlight away from their candidate.
   ``We're going to have to display some creativity'' in keeping
Bush's candidacy before the public, said Bush aide Peter Teeley.
   Although Bush is running virtually alone for the GOP nomination,
it will be at least a couple of weeks before he can gain enough
delegates for a majority at the GOP convention.
   Assuming he wins every delegate that can be won from now on, he
would cross that threshold on May 3, when Ohio, Indiana and the
District of Columbia hold their primaries. But if he picks up
Dole's delegates _ now counted as uncommitted _ he could go over
the top as early as April 15, when Minnesota holds its GOP state
convention.
   Bush's sole remaining challenger is former television evangelist
Pat Robertson, who has but 17 delegates.
   Bush had said he would keep on campaigning hard, right up until
the time Dole announced he was retiring from the race. Dole's exit
makes the April 5 GOP primary moot.
   ``It changes some of the dynamics. It removes some of the
tension,'' Bush said of Dole's withdrawal.
   ``I don't like running against other Republicans,'' he added.
   Bush said he had called Dole to ``congratulate him on a
hard-fought race...He has been a worthy warrier and a tough
competitor.''
   Bush said that, while he intends to continue to ``campaign'' in
key states, ``the schedule will be somewhat lighter. And I'll have
more time to flesh out the issue positions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
