<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Drugs-Landlords     03-30 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Drugs-Landlords,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Dealers' Landlords Must Pay for Cops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The landlord of a building where
150 narcotics officers conducted a raid will reimburse police for
the cost of the bust and to move innocent tenants to safer
apartments, authorities said.
   The agreement was part of a judgment in San Mateo County
Superior Court announced Tuesday.
   District Attorney Jim Fox said it is the first in the region in
which law enforcement officials successfully sued apartment
building owners under a state nuisance abatement law intended to
combat drug dealers.
   The action ``sends a message to property owners that they have
an affirmative duty'' to stop drug dealing in their buildings, Fox
said.
   There were more than 75 drug-related arrests at the building
from June 1985 to the December bust, when 22 people were taken into
custody.
   The landlord, 2001 Manhattan Apartments Inc., of Sausalito,
agreed to pay $25,000 in civil penalties, $7,500 to the drug task
force and $2,500 to the East Palo Alto police for the cost of
enforcing drug laws at the building.
   The owners also have paid $13,000 in relocation expenses for
eight families.
</TEXT>
