<HEAD>Man Ordered To Help at Shelter After Shooting Dog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been ordered to work 200 hours
at an animal shelter after he admitted trying to kill a stray dog
with arrows.
   Joseph T. Irvine of Las Vegas says he will appeal his conviction
Tuesday of injuring, torturing or abandoning an animal.
   Justice of the Peace Bill Jansen ruled Irving was not legally
justified when he armed himself with a hunting bow and shot the dog
twice.
   The judge could have imposed a six-month jail term and a $1,000
fine, but said community service at the animal shelter might teach
Irvine respect for animals.
   The dog, which has since been adopted and named Lucky, sat in a
chair in the courtroom Tuesday.
   Irvine claimed the animal followed him into his home after he
tried to befriend it. He said he shot the dog once in the head with
an arrow, then decided it was not enough and loaded the bow, then
``let him have it again.''
