<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     03-30 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Meets With Party Elders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson
and key members of his party's establishment held a summit meeting
Wednesday, showing, he said, that ``old wineskins are expanding and
making room for new wine.''
   Jackson huddled for a breakfast meeting with more than two dozen
well-known figures in the party. Afterward, they said no one had
brought up reported party concerns that his nomination could damage
Democratic chances of winning the White House next November.
   ``We only see that in the press,'' said California Assembly
Speaker Willie Brown, Jackson's national campaign chairman. ``Maybe
people don't want to say that in front of us.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jackson are locked in a
tight race for the lead in national convention delegates, after a
big Jackson win in the Michigan caucuses last weekend and a Dukakis
victory in the Connecticut primary Tuesday.
   In addition to private concerns about Jackson, another
Democratic contender, Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, has begun
strong criticism of Jackson's experience and his stands on issues.
   ``I categorically reject his notion that there's a moral
equivalence between Israel and the PLO,'' Gore said Tuesday in New
York. ``And I am dismayed by his embrace of (PLO leader Yasser)
Arafat and (Cuban President Fidel) Castro.''
   Jackson brushed aside those criticisms, and Gore sought a
meeting with Jackson late Wednesday in Washington before Jackson
was to fly to Wisconsin to campaign for the primary there next
Tuesday.
   After the breakfast meeting, former Defense Secretary Clark
Clifford, one of the solid figures of the party establishment, had
nothing but praise for Jackson.
   ``What he is also doing is bringing a new maturity to the
American political scene,'' said Clifford. ``His candidacy could
not have occurred 50 years ago, 25 years ago, or perhaps even 10
years ago. It is ... an important breakthrough in our constant
seeking to bring more fairness to our political process.''
   Jackson said the breakfast brought ``together Democrats who have
traditional investment in the interests of the country and the
party and those who are new to the process.''
   ``In this instance, we bring together old wineskins and new
wine, but the old wineskins are expanding and making room for new
wine,'' he added, using an image he used frequently in his 1984
campaign.
   Former Democratic Party Chairman John White, who put together
the breakfast, is joining the campaign as an informal adviser.
   ``This meeting is a new maturing of the political process in
America,'' White said. ``It represents a growing-up of America. It
represents a bonding of the Democratic Party and a bond that
recognizes no class.''
   Participants in the breakfast said one concern about Jackson was
posed to him in a question about his relationship with Black Muslim
leader Louis Farrakhan.
   White said Jackson ``quoted Jesus about casting the first stone
and forgiveness and so anybody who hasn't made mistakes ... let's
not be casting stones at each other about the past.''
   Farrakhan campaigned with Jackson early in the 1984 campaign,
but the tie was cut after the Black Muslim leader called Judaism a
``gutter religion'' and called Adolf Hitler ``a great man.''
</TEXT>
