<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DisneyDressCode     03-30 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disney Dress Code,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Disneyland Hotel Workers Fired for Refusing to Shave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Disneyland Hotel employees who opted
for whiskers over work were fired when they reported to their jobs
still sporting facial hair, a violation of new rules.
   Mike Searles, a hotel engineer who has a walrus-style mustache,
and Mike Ferrington, a bartender who wears a beard, gave the hotel
no choice, Disneyland spokesman Bob Roth said Tuesday.
   Searles had worked at the hotel for more than 10 years, Roth
said. He was unaware how long Ferrington had worked there.
   The Walt Disney Co. bought the hotel, across the street from
Disneyland, from the Wrather Corp. in January. With the purchase
came a dress and appearance code for the hotel's 1,600 employees.
   The code, established for Disneyland employees in 1957, requires
men to be clean shaven and keep their hair short. Men cannot wear
gold chains or earrings or have visible tattoos. It also prohibits
women from having long fingernails or wearing eyeshadow.
   Searles and Ferrington were among six hotel employees suspended
last week for three days without pay and told they would be fired
if they didn't shave. Two have complied and two others also face
dismissal, Roth said,
   At least 12 male hotel employees have filed union grievances.
The five unions have vowed to fight the rule.
</TEXT>
