<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Ball-Swearing-In     03-30 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ball-Swearing-In,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Secretary Takes Oath of Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Ball was sworn in Wednesday as the
nation's 67th secretary of the Navy, pledging to keep his forces
``strong and prepared'' to meet any challenge.
   Standing in an ornate Old Executive Office Building room first
used by Navy Secretary Richard Thompson in 1879, Ball said that by
maintaining military strength, the United States ``preserve the
peace and ultimately extend the special gift that is freedom the
world over.''
   President Reagan, making remarks at the swearing-in ceremony for
his former legislative liaison, said Ball had ``won the respect of
the leaders of both parties.'' He said ``I've repeatedly turned''
to Ball for help and advice in recent years.
   White House chief of staff Howard Baker swore in Ball as several
Cabinet officers, members of Congress and military officers looked
on. After Thompson, who served under President Rutherford B. Hayes,
14 Navy secretaries used the room, heavily decorated in naval motif.
   ``Will takes over the Navy at a critical time,'' Reagan told the
audience. ``The defense budget (requested by the administration)
has now been cut for four consecutive years. And yet we must
maintain the gains this administration has made in rebuilding our
naval and military capabilities. The 600-ship Navy remains our
goal.''
   Ball, 39, succeeds James Webb, who resigned in a dispute with
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci over Pentagon budgetary
priorities, including a delay in reaching the 600-ship level for
the Navy.
   Reagan said ``Will's job will be to skipper our naval forces
through some troubled waters while keeping our Navy and Marine
Corps team second to none.''
   ``Keeping re-enlistments high and the quality of our recruits
the best it's ever been, will be Will's other big assignment,'' he
said.
   In brief remarks, Ball noted that he had recently visited the
USS Coral Sea, which had just returned after six months of duty in
the Mediterranean Sea with the U.S. 6th Fleet.
   ``On that great ship, I was immediately able to see one of the
many legacies that you will leave to history,'' Ball told the
president.
   ``It is indeed written on the faces of those Coral Sea sailors,
in their spirit and their dedication. ... It signifies what you
have done ... for our seagoing people, who are proud once again.''
</TEXT>
