<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RanchoSeco     03-30 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rancho Seco,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuclear Plant Restarted After 27-Month Shutdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rancho Seco nuclear power plant, shut
down for 27 months, was restarted today after plant officials
received final approval from the federal Nuclear Regulatory
Commission.
   An electronically transmitted letter from the NRC approving the
restart arrived at 6:53 a.m., said Kerry Shearer, a spokesman for
the Sacramento Municipal Utility District, which owns the plant 25
miles southeast of Sacramento.
   The letter was in response to an official approval request sent
by the authority to Washington on Tuesday.
   Authority nuclear chief Carl Andognini ordered restart of the
plant at 7:04 a.m., Shearer said. Starting up the plant will take
eight to 10 hours.
   ``We're obviously very, very happy to have come to this point
after 27 months of effort,'' said Shearer.
   The plant, whose reactor is a twin of the Three Mile Island
reactor in Pennsylvania, has been closed since a severe overcooling
accident in December 1985.
   The startup process will be completed later Wednesday when
operators finish diluting the amount of boron in the reactor's
cooling water and withdraw control rods, Shearer said.
   ``The combination brings the reactor to the point where the
nuclear chain reaction is self-sustaining,'' he said. Officials
call that milestone ``criticality'' and plan to operate the reactor
for 10 to 14 days before beginning to produce electricity.
   On Tuesday morning, operators finished testing repairs made to
the plant's electrical system over the weekend. A valve problem and
excessive vibration in two back-up diesel generators were also
fixed over the weekend.
   But opposition to the plant has grown during the long series of
restart delays. A majority of the Sacramento City Council,
including Mayor Anne Rudin, and at least one county supervisor have
announced support for a June ballot measure calling for the plant's
closure.
   A citizen-sponsored initiative calls for immediate shutdown of
the plant. A competing SMUD-sponsored measure asks voters to
approve operation of the plant for at least 18 months.
   The utility has spent more than $400 million during the past 27
months to overhaul equipment and management at the plant, which has
generated an average of only 40 percent of the electricity it was
designed to produce since it was opened in 1975.
   Michael Remy, director of the group sponsoring the plant closure
initiative, said the utility was under pressure to restart the
plant because a major delay could diminish public support for the
facility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
