<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 3rdLd-Writethru a0637 03-30 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0637,0857</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Son Lied In Dealership Testimony, Bookkeeper Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs, more details on Christman's testimony;
picks up 9th graf pvs, ``Yes, there was ..''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's son lied in his
testimony on an impeachment allegation that the governor misused
$80,000 from his protocol fund by loaning it to his auto
dealership, the company's former bookkeeper told the Senate today.
   Dennis Mecham, general manager of Mecham Pontiac, said last week
that the dealership was in ``very strong'' financial shape, but
former bookkeeper Lee Christman testified today that the company
actually needed hundreds of thousands of dollars when it borrowed
the $80,000 in July 1987.
   On Tuesday, Dennis Mecham announced that the dealership was
being sold because of lagging sales blamed on bad publicity that
has dogged his father since he took office in January 1987.
   Asked today by defense lawyer Jerris Leonard whether she
contacted prosecutors on her own initiative, Ms. Christman
answered, ``Yes, when I heard Dennis lie.''
   Leonard immediately objected, and the presiding officer said Ms.
Christman's answer went beyond what the question sought.
   Later, Ms. Christman told prosecutor William French she was
upset with Dennis Mecham because she felt he had blamed her for
things that were not her fault.
   Democratic Sen. Jesus ``Chuy'' Higuera, then asked if there were
other instances in which she believed the governor and his son had
not told the truth.
   ``They were misstating various facts which would lead one to
believe that the inefficiencies were in the accounting office,
rather than the fact that there was a lack of money,'' Ms.
Christman said.
   French asked Ms. Christman, ``Was there an immediate need for
cash in July 1987?''
   ``Yes, there was,'' she answered. She said Dennis Mecham had
told her the company needed $497,000 in cash flow, and that he
called her to his office and handed her an $80,000 check.
   ``Did he use the word `protocol fund?''' French said. ``Yes,''
she answered.
   Ms. Christman worked for Mecham Pontiac from November 1986 to
February 1988, when she said she was asked to resign because
someone else was hired to handle the computer.
   The financial condition of Mecham Pontiac has been a central
issue in the charge that Mecham miused the protocol fund by loaning
to $80,000 to the dealership. The charge is the second of three
impeachment charges against him.
   After the prosecution finished its case with rebuttal testimony
from Ms. Christman and another witness, the Senate was expected to
consider whether to vote on the first two impeachment articles,
even though no testimony has been heard during the month-long trial
on the third charge _ that Mecham concealed a $350,000 campaign
loan.
   A vote to convict the first-term Republican governor would
automatically remove him from office.
   Dennis Mecham said Tuesday, ``The confusion and questions this
avalanche of negative publicity has caused ... has forced my family
to come to this decision to sell Mecham Pontiac while the condition
of the company remains solvent and saleable.''
   Mecham also faces a May 17 recall election spurred in part by
actions and comments that critics have considered slurs against
blacks, Jews, homosexuals and the Japanese.
   Oldsmobile dealer Kemp Biddulph, whose dealership is next door
to Mecham's in suburban Glendale, said he hoped to close the
purchase by May 1.
   In the impeachment trial, the prosecution claims the dealership
desperately needed the $80,000 loan to meet its payroll in July
1987, but that the governor's protocol fund, which was derived from
inaugural proceeds, was public money.
   The defense claims, however, that the dealership was in good
financial shape at the time of the loan, which was intended to
provide higher interest to the protocol fund. Defense witnesses
have insisted the fund was private money.
   Last week, a motion to allow an immediate vote on the first
impeachment charge that the governor tried to thwart an
investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official was
withdrawn when many senators voiced opposition.
   The third impeachment charge is also the subject of the
governor's April 21 criminal trial, and Mecham has insisted that
allowing the Senate to hear testimony on that charge might
jeopardize his chances of a fair trial.
   Some senators have said they do not want to run the risk of
forcing the criminal charges to be thrown out. Others, however,
including Majority Leader Bob Usdane, a Republican, have insisted
lawmakers should hear evidence on all three charges before voting
on any of them.
   Also on Tuesday, a Maricopa County Superior Court judge refused
to dismiss the criminal charges against Mecham. The defense had
claimed the governor was a victim of selective prosecution and was
charged under the wrong law.
   Judge Michael Ryan also refused to separate the governor's case
from that of co-defendant Willard Mecham, his brother and 1986
campaign treasurer.
   Elsewhere, opening arguments were expected this afternoon in the
political extortion trial of Mecham's former aide, Sam Steiger.
</TEXT>
