<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Picou     03-30 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Picou,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jazzman Theodore Picou Dies At 53</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theodore Picou, a jazz saxophonist and composer
who toured internationally with his musical groups, has died of
lung cancer. He was 53.
   Picou, who died Sunday at his home, is credited with teaching
and influencing many saxophonists, including Harold Land, Herman
Riley and Charles Owens, relatives said.
   Picou was born in Calexico, Calif., on April 19, 1934. His
parents were Creole, from the New Orleans area, and French and
Creole music influenced the family, said his sister, Cecile.
   Picou's family moved to San Diego when he was a child, and he
began taking music lessons at 4. His mother bought him his first
saxophone, and he was playing publicly by age 13.
   Teddy Picou and His Jazz Quartet were playing locally until
recent weeks. His last recording was ``Experience,'' which featured
his own compositions.
   With his quartet and another group, Ted Picou and His Band, he
toured Africa and Europe as well as the United States.
   Survivors include his former wife, Bernestine Picou of San
Diego, two sons, a daughter and his mother. Services were scheduled
Thursday.
</TEXT>
