<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Media Bjt   03-30 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Media, Bjt,0709</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Shuts Arab News Service, Court Denies Media Access</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JER1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army on Wednesday padlocked the Arab-owned
Palestine Press Service, cutting off a key source of information in
a campaign to curtail media coverage of Arab unrest in the occupied
territories.
   The news service, which reports on activities in the West Bank
and Gaza Stip, was ordered closed for six months.
   ``We were just too efficient. That's what we got closed down
for,'' reporter John Mellor told The Associated Press.
   In another slap against the media, the Supreme Court rejected a
foreign press appeal for access to the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which have been closed since Monday. But the judges ordered the
government to explain within 30 days why reporters should not be
allowed free access to the areas.
   The moves indicated the importance Israel attaches to curbing
news coverage. Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and other government
officials have accused the media of fueling nearly four months of
violence in the occupied territories.
   The army said journalists would be prosecuted if found violating
the access ban, which carries a maximum penalty of five years in
jail.
   Lawrence Grossman, president of NBC News, rejected the
government view that a media presence had aggravated the problems.
   ``There hasn't been a single killing of an Arab when the cameras
are there,'' Grossman said in an interview with the Jerusalem Post.
   He added that Israel was ``putting itself in the least favorable
imaginable position in view of South Africa's reputation.'' In
South Africa, police have the right to close an area to journalists
at a moment's notice.
   Israeli officials have been particularly sensitive about
comparisons of Israel's treatment of Palestinians with the
treatment of blacks in South Africa. In that country, the black
majority has no voice in national affairs.
   The order against the Palestine Press Service, signed by West
Bank commander Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna and taped on the agency's
door, said the closure was ``necessary for maintaining public
safety and public order.''
   Army troops ordered agency staffers out of the office and placed
two large padlocks on the doors. In defiance, the agency clamped on
two padlocks of its own.
   ``It's a horrible day. The army has now made the blackout in the
occupied territories complete,'' the agency's publisher, Ibrahim
Kareen, told The AP. He said four of his staffers have been
arrested since unrest began Dec. 8.
   The army has arrested more than a dozen Arab journalists who
have acted as interpreters for foreign reporters.
   The order, the first ever against the 11-year-old agency, was
authorized under 1945 emergency regulations imposed by the British
in pre-Israel Palestine.
   Kareen said officials told him they were closing the agency in
part because Israel believed it received funding from the Palestine
Liberation Organization. Kareen denied PLO funding and said the
real reason for the closure was that his agency provided tips to
journalists about Palestinian deaths or injuries far more quickly
than the army.
   The Supreme Court heard 2{ hours of arguments Wednesday on an
appeal from the Foreign Press Association, which sought a reversal
of Monday's order closing the occupied territories until early
Friday.
   Yisrael Leshem, an attorney for the association, argued the
closure order was a blow to freedom of the press and set a
dangerous precedent.
   ``If the army makes this condition now, what's to stop them from
banning coverage of any event?'' Leshem said. He criticized as
insufficient pool coverage arrangements offered to journalists who
went in with an army escort.
   A military officer argued the army arrangements actually helped
reporters by protecting them from demonstrators.
   Although the closure order remained in effect, Robert Slater,
president of the Foreign Press Association, said he considered the
decision ``a great victory'' because the government was required to
explain its decision.
   ``We weren't fighting for five minutes or 10 minutes in the
territories,'' Slater said. ``We were fighting for the principle.
This order sends a clear signal to the army that in the near future
we should be permitted to enter the territories freely.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
