<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--TallShip     03-30 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tall Ship,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard's Eagle Back From Down Under</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard's 295-foot Eagle, the
government's only tall ship, returned to the United States on
Wednesday after two months down under to help celebrate Australia's
bicentennial.
   The square-rigged, steel-hulled bark entered the breakwater at 8
a.m. and led a two-hour boat parade through the Los Angeles-Long
Beach harbors before docking at the Long Beach Naval Station.
   The Eagle and its 175-member crew are visiting briefly on a
return voyage to the ship's New London, Conn., homeport. The ship
departs Friday and continues its voyage via Acapulco and the Panama
Canal.
   The public was invited to board the ship Thursday.
   A seagoing classroom for cadets at the Coast Guard Academy in
New London, the ship was built in Germany in 1936 as a training
ship for German navy cadets. It was seized as a war prize in World
War II.
</TEXT>
