<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Welcome to Atlanta. If you are going down the
escalator, you will be entering the transportation mall ...''
   Millions of travelers each year hear the message at Hartsfield
Atlanta International Airport, and the woman whose voice is behind
the words says they've given new meaning to her life.
   Lee McAllister's taped announcement began running when the new
midfield terminal opened in 1980. ``People immediately wanted to
know who the voice was, and I made sure word got around,'' she said.
   She now has more than 1,800 radio and TV commercials to her
credit and is always a hit at parties. ``People are always saying,
`Do the airport voice, Lee, do the airport voice,''' she said.
   Airport officials hired Ms. McAllister because ``we needed
someone who could guide people through the airport, whose voice was
calm, collected and soothing,'' said J.R. McIntyre of the Atlanta
Airlines Terminal Corp. ``It's kind of like the cowboys who sang to
the herds.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The helicopter ride to Cleveland Metropolitan
General Hospital took just 12 minutes, but when it arrived, there
was another passenger on board.
   Four-pound, 1{-ounce Calvin Williams was born Tuesday seven
weeks premature as his mother, Dina Williams, 29, of Lorain, was
being rushed from Amherst Hospital to Metro General, which has a
neonatal intensive care unit.
   When the staff at Amherst realized Mrs. Williams was in labor,
they contacted Metro General for a Life Flight Helicopter, said
Metro General spokesman George Stamatis. The helicopter, carrying
two pilots, a nurse and a doctor, arrived at Amherst within a
half-hour, and soon after that, it was aloft again with Mrs.
Williams.
   Mrs. Williams said contractions became more severe during the
flight. ``I kept saying it was too early,'' she said from her
hospital bed. ``Then I figured it would wait until we got here, but
it didn't.''
   Five minutes before the helicopter landed at Metro General,
nurse Cathy Gilman and Dr. Peter Capicotto delivered Calvin.
</TEXT>
