<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FactoryOrders     03-30 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Orders,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Factory Orders Down for Second Month, But Analysts Not Alarmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods fell for the second month in a row in February, but analysts
said the 0.8 percent decline was not a cause for alarm.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that orders for durable
and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $210.86
billion last month following a 0.6 percent decline in January.
   The February setback was the biggest since a 1.4 percent drop
last August and marked the first time that factory orders have
fallen for two consecutive months since the summer of 1986.
   Economists said the declines showed that businesses did cut back
on orders in the early part of the year in an effort to trim high
levels of unsold goods that had built up in the final three months
of 1987.
   While this process will dampen growth, economists said it
appeared that the cutbacks had been moderate and would set the
stage for faster growth in the months ahead.
   ``The economy is expanding at a moderate pace. We are not
looking for either a boom or a bust,'' said Bruce Steinberg, an
economist with Merrill Lynch in New York. ``Although we had
declines in orders in the past two months, those declines came off
a very high level of demand in the fourth quarter.''
   Even with the two months of declines, total factory orders were
8.3 percent higher than a year earlier, reflecting the strong
growth in manufacturing demand in 1987. Analysts also noted that
the backlog of unfilled orders continued to grow in February,
rising by 0.8 percent to $412.3 billion, indicating production will
have to remain high to fill those orders.
   Economists expect manufacturing to be one of the major sources
of strength for the economy this year as American companies
continue to benefit from a weaker dollar, which has made their
products competitive again on world markets.
   This export boom is expected to spur U.S. companies to boost
their investment spending plans for new plant and equipment,
further adding to overall economic growth.
   However, the February report said the key category of
non-defense capital goods fell 3.9 percent, although the sector was
still 23 percent higher than a year ago. This category is
considered a good gauge of business spending plans on capital
equipment.
   Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist for the National Association
of Manufacturers, said the weakness in stock prices and fears about
higher inflation rates may be causing some companies to lower their
investment spending somewhat.
   The February decline in factory orders included a drop of 1.1
percent in orders for durable goods. These items, expected to last
three or more years, fell to a seasonally adjusted $118.5 billion
last month. An advance report last week had put the decline in
those orders at a sharper 1.8 percent.
   Orders for non-durable goods fell 0.4 percent in February to
$97.9 billion.
   Orders for military equipment fell 8.2 percent to $8.4 billion
last month, but military demand was still 14 percent higher than a
year ago. Without the drop in defense orders, total orders would
have fallen by a slightly smaller 0.5 percent in February.
   Orders for transportation equipment were one of the few areas of
strength last month, climbing 3.5 percent to $30 billion. The
aircraft component showed a 6.8 percent increase.
   Orders for primary metals, such as steel, edged up 1.4 percent
and were 26 percent higher than a year earlier.
   Orders for electrical machinery fell 7.4 percent, while orders
for non-electrical machinery were off 5.4 percent.
   Shipments of manufactured goods edged up 0.1 percent in February
to $207.4 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
