<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     03-30 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenians Vow to Continue Strike Until Government Gives In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenians threatened to continue a general strike
paralyzing the main city of a disputed southern region until the
government agreed to make the region part of Aremenia, newspapers
reported Wednesday.
   For the first time, an official Soviet newspaper, Komsomolskaya
Pravda, used the word ``strike'' to describe what was previously
was referred to as truancy or absenteeism in Stepanakert, the
central city of Azerbaijan's Nagorno-Karabakh region.
   The Soviet press generally uses the word ``strike'' only to
describe labor unrest in the West. But Komsomolskaya Pravda, the
organ of the youth organization Komsomol, took advantage of Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's drive for openness to break from
tradition.
   The daily also provided the first official confirmation that the
strike was part of a series of labor protests in Stepanakert and
that the walkout started March 24, not Saturday as other newspapers
have indicated.
   All but essential services such as bakeries and dairies, some
public transportation and medical clinics were reported to be shut
down in Stepanakert, a city of more than 33,000 people. The
government has lost millions of rubles in revenue because of the
strike, newspapers said.
   ``We're only two or three steps from catastrophe,'' Vasily
Atadzhanyan, the director of a shoe factory, told Komsomolskaya
Pravda. ``We will pay huge fines for not fulfilling our obligations
to our customers. We say directly: `Not coming to work is
sabotage.'''
   Only about 120 of 1,500 workers showed up for work Monday at the
shoe factory, the newspaper said.
   ``People are sitting home ... without noise and without
demonstrations,'' said a man answering the telephone at the
official newspaper in Stepanakert, Sovietsky Karabakh. ``People say
they are going to stay away until they get a decision from the
government in their favor.''
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda said many Stepanakert
residents were upset that Soviet newspapers were not accurately
reporting the dispute.
   ``We want everyone to know the truth. The absences from work
will continue until our matter is settled,'' Pravda quoted one
resident as saying.
   Early press coverage claimed that Armenians, who are mostly
Christian, and Azerbaijanis, who are mostly Shiite Moslem, live
together in harmony. It blamed the unrest, in which at least 32
people have died, on a few ``extremists.''
   Authorities have been meeting with residents to urge them to
return to their jobs and vowed not to bow to pressure to annex
predominantly Armenian Nagorno-Karabakh to Armenia.
   Instead, authorities have unveiled a plan to spend up to 400
million rubles, or $640 million, to improve social and economic
conditions in the Aremenian-dominated region.
   The labor newspaper Trud said people in Stepanakert were
grateful for the government's efforts but that some still believed
it was necessary to stay away from work to press their demand.
   The newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya said about 100 specialists and
workers appeared for work at an electrical-technical factory
Tuesday morning.
   Ninety percent of the workers at a plant manufacturing
construction materials appeared at work Monday morning, only to
walk out en masse, Komsomolskaya Pravda said.
   Armenians began mass street rallies and strikes in Stepanakert
on Feb. 13. The turmoil spread to the capital of the Armenian
republic, Yerevan. On Feb. 28, ethnic rioting broke out in Sumgait,
a industrial city in Azerbaijan, and officials said 26 Armenians
and six Azerbaijanis were killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
