<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1542EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-TeenSex     03-30 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Teen Sex,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Aid to Church Groups for Chastity Programs Challenged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal law aimed at encouraging chastity
among teen-agers provides money to religious groups that, in one
instance, advised ``young girls to pretend that Jesus is their
date,'' the Supreme Court was told Wednesday.
   ``We're not saying that chastity cannot be a secular value, but
it has been misused'' by religious groups funded under the 1981
law, argued Janet Benshoof, an American Civil Liberties Union
lawyer.
   As a result, she contended, the law unconstitutionally promotes
religion.
   But the Reagan administration's top-ranked courtroom lawyer
defended the law.
   Solicitor General Charles Fried conceded that ``there may have
been some departures'' from past Supreme Court rulings on
church-state relations by some private organizations carrying out
the law's purpose. But he said such ``constitutionally
troublesome'' spending of federal money has been corrected, and
that the law can be carried out in a constitutionally acceptable
way.
   The law, known as the Adolescent Family Life Act, was passed by
Congress ``in response to grave social, economic and health costs''
of early-adolescent pregnancy, Fried said.
   He noted that religiously affiliated groups for years have
participated in government programs dealing with juvenile
delinquency, foster care, adoption and drug prevention.
   The disputed law, sponsored by former Sen. Jeremiah Denton,
R-Ala., and ushered through Congress by fellow conservatives,
provided millions of dollars for three general program categories _
care, prevention and research.
   ``Care services'' include pregnancy testing, maternity
counseling, adoption and referral help.
   ``Prevention services'' are those aimed at discouraging
adolescent sexual relations, and include programs offering
counseling and family planning.
   The law requires applicants for funding to describe how, in
providing services, they will ``involve religious and charitable
organizations, voluntary associations and other groups in the
private sector.''
   The law also allows religiously affiliated organizations to
receive money for such programs.
   A federal judge here struck down the law last year, ruling that
its primary effect is to promote religion and that it fosters an
excessive entanglement between government and religion.
   The administration then asked the Supreme Court to salvage the
law. The justices are expected to announce their decision by July.
   Benshoof acknowledged that federal money may be used to cope
with the problem of teen-age pregnancies. More than 1 million
unmarried girls become pregnant each year, and about half obtain
abortions.
   But the ACLU lawyer added that the 1981 envisions a
constitutionally suspect ``union between government and religion.''
   ``Not once in seven years has (the Department of Health and
Human Services) questioned the religiousity of any institution
receiving aid'' under the law, Benshoof contended.
   When Justice Antonin Scalia asked whether Congress could spend
money to encourage self-restraint by teen-agers, Benshoof said
groups receiving the money ``can't do it by telling young girls to
pretend that Jesus is their date.''
   The ACLU says a Virginia organization that received $150,000
under the law offered such advice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1543EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Salvador     03-30 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Salvador,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Assails Guerrilla Escalation Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans by Salvadoran guerrillas to escalate
their war against the U.S.-backed government reinforce their
``well-deserved reputation for ruthless and indiscriminate
violence,'' the State Department said Wednesday.
   The rebel plan was disclosed by the insurgents' high command at
a news conference with foreign journalists in guerrilla-held
territory. Among other steps, the rebels said they intend to target
U.S. military advisers for assassination.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the United States
obviously ``will not be intimidated by threats against its
personnel. The U.S. commitment to assist the democratic government
of El Salvador, backed by a strong bipartisan consensus, remains
firm.''
   The rebel leaders said they plan to increase attacks in San
Salvador, the capital, targeting the country's upper class, to use
surface-to-air missiles against military helicopers and to step up
attacks against military installations.
   Redman said the proposed rebel offensive ``once again confirms
their disregard for the well-being of the Salvadoran people and
their commitment to achieve power and install a totalitarian
dictatorship at any price.''
</TEXT>
