<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1619EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WheatGrowers     03-30 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheat Growers,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer Group Urges Incentive To Sell Grain On Open Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat farmers should be provided with some
kind of incentive to sell grain on the open market rather than have
to forfeit it to the government when price support loans come due,
the National Association of Wheat Growers said Wednesday.
   Frank Johannsen, association president, said wheat farmers
deserve the same kind of consideration given corn producers who are
being allowed to keep their grain under federal price support for
an additional year.
   That was a reference to Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng's
announcement Tuesday that price support loans for some old-crop
corn and sorghum will be extended a year longer than their normal
maturity dates.
   Johannsen, a Bayard, Neb., wheat farmers said in a statement
released here that the association is ``seeking a way to encourage
growers to settle their maturing loans'' by paying them off with
generic certificates. The certificates are issued by USDA as
payment-in-kind under crop programs and can be exchanged for
surplus commodities owned by the department's Commondity Credit
Corp.
   If the price support loans are not repaid, a farmer must forfeit
the grain to the CCC, which cancels the debt.
   Once the CCC takes over the grain, it must be moved into
government storage. Much of the CCC wheat is currently being sold
back into the market in weekly auctions.
   ``Since current estimates are that it costs the government at
least 20 cents a bushel to move, store, catalog and exchange
forfeited wheat through weekly auctions, our proposal won't cost
anything extra and it will reduce some of the government's
logistical problems,'' Johannsen said. ``It has the added benefit
of keeping wheat moving in the pipeline of our much-improved
market.''
   Besides, he said, grain farmers ``have a right to expect
even-handed treatment'' from the department. ``Forcing farmers to
forfeit their loans only broadens the government's role in
markets.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
