<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Democrats 1stLd-Writethru a0678 03-30 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Admit Apprehension About Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 2nd graf bgng ``Democratic'' to restore dropped word
`and'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An adviser to Jesse Jackson said Wednesday he
detected the beginnings of an anonymous ``Stop Jackson'' movement
in the Democratic Party, and a Southern party chairman acknowledged
there is ``an awful lot of apprehension out there'' about the
possibility of Jackson's nomination.
   Democratic establishment leaders gathered here with Jackson, and
after that meeting, Jackson supporter Rep. Mickey Leland of Texas
said he understood an effort to stop Jackson was afoot.
   Leland said he did not know who was behind the attempt, and said
he knew of no party leaders joining such a movement. But he said it
did not appear to be confined to Southern white Democrats.
   ``There is some movement afoot,'' Leland said. ``We can't put
our hands on it. We don't know who the leader is. But we do
understand ... different players of the Democratic Party have been
approached.''
   He named Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk and House
Speaker Jim Wright as among those approached. Contacted later, Kirk
and a spokesman for Wright said no one had talked to them about
keeping the nomination away from Jackson.
   ``I haven't talked to anyone, and no one's approached me,'' said
Kirk, who earlier this week rejected talk of a movement to block
Jackson.
   Although Jackson fell substantially behind Michael Dukakis in
Connecticut's primary Tuesday, his 2-to-1 victory in Michigan on
Saturday has forced Democratic leaders to confront the possibility
that Jackson could end the primary season as top vote getter and
perhaps delegate leader.
   In recognition of that, a group representing the top ranks of
Washington's old-line Democratic establishment _ including
presidential adviser Clark Clifford, former party chairman John
White and one-time Mondale aide Richard Moe _ met with Jackson over
breakfast at a downtown hotel.
   They came away praising Jackson and insisting they wouldn't be
party to any effort to block him.
   ``I don't think there will be at this particular time,
especially from the South, a stop Jesse Jackson movement,'' said
Charles Whitehead, state Democratic Party chairman from Florida,
after the session.
   Whitehead acknowledged widespread concern among Democrats about
the prospect of Jackson winning the nomination, however. In the
wake of Michigan, some Democrats have privately voiced the fear
that the liberal black Jackson could prove an unelectable nominee
in the fall and damage other Democratic candidates.
   ``I would be less than honest with you if I didn't tell you
there is absolutely an awful lot of apprehension out there among an
awful lot of Democrats about the nomination of Jesse Jackson,''
Whitehead said. ``Sure there is.
   ``They're afraid of nominating someone that they consider
unelectable,'' he said.
   But Whitehead, whose state primary was won by Dukakis, the
Massachusetts governor, said there was ``that same apprehension
about nominating an Eastern liberal.''
   ``You've got a fear there if you nominate an Eastern liberal,
you've nominated another (Walter) Mondale,'' who lost 49 states as
the 1984 nominee, he said.
   Most Democratic Party insiders have said this week that any
public effort to block Jackson would be damaging and alienate
blacks and other voters the party will need in the fall, no matter
who the nominee is. ``You can't win with him and can't win without
him,'' one political source said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Another source close to Democratic Party politics said concerns
among party leaders had eased with the Connecticut vote following
``two days of gnashing of teeth.''
   He said a feeling was growing that Jackson was strengthening the
party with new voters, and that they should not be discouraged by
suggestions Jackson would be denied the nomination. But, he
contended, the remaining calender of big-state primaries decreases
the likelihood Jackson would end up with the most delegates.
   Fueling talk of a stop-Jackson effort was a campaign begun this
week by Alabama Democratic Chairman John Baker. He suggested in a
letter to party leaders around the South that they form a group of
unpledged convention delegates who will commit themselves to ``the
most electable'' presidential candidate.
   Baker denied his effort was aimed at Jackson, but he came under
fire in his own state. A black state senator, Michael Figures of
Mobile, a Jackson supporter, accused Baker of racist remarks.
   ``It's not my intention to sound racist,'' Baker said. ``But I
need to be candid, and I need to talk practical politics. We've got
to think who can beat George Bush and the rest of the Republicans.''
</TEXT>
