<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     03-30 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli-Backed Militia Storms Shiite Village</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's surrogate militia raided a south
Lebanon town in tanks Wednesday with support from helicopter
gunships, killing seven people, wounding 15 and knocking down
scores of houses, police reported.
   The assault on the Shiite Moslem town of Kfar Roumman at 9:45
a.m. coincided with a general strike and joint Lebanese-Palestinian
demonstration in Lebanon's Moslem sectors in solidarity with the
4-month-old Arab rebellion in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   Police and U.N. observers said militiamen of the South Lebanon
Army in 12 Soviet-designed T-54 tanks advanced to Kfar Roumman,
half a mile west of the ``security zone'' Israel maintains in south
Lebanon, and fought guerrillas of the Hezbollah, or Party of God.
The tanks were supplied by Israel, which captured them from Arab
armies.
   Police said SLA militiamen killed five civilians and two
Hezbollah fighters in a house-to-house search of Kfar Roumman, a
town of 2,000 people, and pulled back to the security zone four
hours later.
   Israeli helicopter gunships strafed Kfar Roumman with machine
guns, police reported.
   They said the militiamen advanced behind a barrage of 155mm
howitzer fire from Israeli positions in the zone.
   According to the police report, Kfar Roumman was hit with more
than 140 rounds from tank cannon and mortars before the assault and
13 people were wounded. They said two other people were wounded by
shells that fell on Nabatiyeh, a market town nearby.
   A police spokesman said the militia apparently was pursuing
Hezbollah fighters who attacked two of its outposts before dawn.
   ``Islamic resistance (Hezbollah) fighters were seen withdrawing
from Kfar Roumman. The village has been devastated by shelling,''
said the spokesman, whose name was withheld in keeping with
regulations.
   U.N. peacekeeping observers in the south said Israeli troops and
SLA militiamen had expected attacks on Land Day, which marks a
clash on March 30, 1976, between Israeli troops and Arab citizens
over land confiscation in the occupied territories.
   Banks, schools, shops, restaurants and other businesses were
closed in Beirut, the northern port of Tripoli, the Bekaa Valley of
east Lebanon and the southern ports of Sidon and Tyre. The strike
was called by the National Committee in Support of the Palestinian
Uprising.
   Several demonstrations were held in Jordan, most of whose
citizens are Palestinian. More than 500 students chanting
``Revolution Until Victory!'' rallied at the Jordan University
campus in Amman.
   About 10,000 Palestinian and Lebanese leftists marched in Moslem
west Beirut, escorted by police and carrying banners. Similar
demonstrations were reported in Sidon and Tyre.
   Banners reading ``The Youngsters of Lebanon Praise the Uprising
in Palestine'' and ``Down with Shultz's (peace) Plan'' were among
those raised in Beirut.
   Leaders of Palestinian groups, some of them at odds, and
representatives of several leftist militia factions united in the
throng that marched across Beirut's main Corniche Mazraa
thoroughfare.
   It was the strongest Lebanese expression of solidarity with the
Palestinians since the invading Israeli army drove the Palestine
Liberation Organization out of the country in 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
