<DOCNO> AP880330-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1547EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     03-30 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Moves Away From Meese Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, moving quickly
to put distance between himself and the controversy surrounding
Attorney General Edwin Meese III, said Wednesday the Justice
Department ``has to be above reproach.''
   Bush said he was troubled by the resignation of top Justice
Department officials, but ``I'm not going to pass judgment'' on
whether Meese should resign.
   The Republican presidential candidate, in a statement devoid of
any support for the embattled attorney general, said Meese must
make up his own mind on quitting.
   Bush said Meese would not hold the top law enforcement post in a
Bush administration.
   Campaigning for the first day without a major GOP rival, Bush
was peppered by reporters with questions on the Meese controversy.
   Two top Justice Department officials quit on Tuesday amid
reports of Meese's mounting legal difficulties.
   Clearly eager to keep the matter from becoming a campaign issue,
Bush told reporters, ``Morale in (the) Justice (Department) is very
important.''
   ``It seems to me that the Justice Department has to be above
reproach.propriety,'' he said.
   Speaking for himself, Bush said, ``I want to hold an ethical
standard so high that there's no perception of wrongdoing.''
   Asked whether Meese would be attorney general in a Bush
administration, the vice president said, ``No, nor would any other
member of the (Reagan) Cabinet, because I want to have a new
Cabinet.''
   When a reporter suggested that Bush's position on whether Meese
should resign remained unclear, Bush responded: ``That's what I
intend.''
   He also said he didn't think the affair would rub off on his
campaign, but suggested, ``I'm sure my opponents will try to use
it.''
   ``I'm not going to prejudge Mr. Meese. I'd like to find out a
little more about what is happening here,'' Bush said.
   Meanwhile, Bush told a lunchtime rally that it didn't matter to
him which candidate the Democrats finally nominate.
   ``I will take on whoever the Democrats put up,'' he said.
   As to whether Republicans would prefer running against Democrat
Jesse Jackson rather than Michael Dukakis, Bush said, ``I don't
plan to get in there and fine-tune what's happening on the
Democratic side.''
   Bush wrapped up three days of campaigning in Wisconsin. During
his visit, he picked up the endorsement of former rivals Rep. Jack
Kemp and Sen. Bob Dole quit the race, giving him a virtual lock on
the GOP nomination.
   Bush aides said the vice president would skip a visit back to
Wisconsin that had been tentatively planned for Monday so he can
focus his attention on consolidating his support and planning
future campaign appearances.
   Spokesman Pete Teeley said Dole, who withdrew from the GOP race
on Tuesday, was expected to make campaign appearances on Bush's
behalf _ but specifics had not been worked out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
