<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1600EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole     03-30 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Says Tactical Campaign Mistakes Didn't Doom Candidacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole said Wednesday that his failed
presidential campaign had made serious tactical mistakes but added
that they weren't the main reason for his downfall.
   In an interview a day after he quit the presidential race, the
Kansas Republican expressed some of his frustrations over his
unsuccessful battle with Vice President George Bush for the GOP
nomination.
   ``The bottom line is that you can't beat Ronald Reagan,'' Dole
said. ``I was running against Ronald Reagan Jr. in the South.''
   That was a reference to Bush's success in campaigning as
Reagan's vice president and logical heir. ``It's just this
promotion idea that you just ought to go up the ladder,'' Dole said.
   He also said Republican Party ``winner-take-all'' rules in the
primaries and caucuses contributed to his exit from the campaign.
   If delegates were divided proportionally, he said, ``I'd still
be in the race.''
   Asked the one thing he would do differently in his campaign,
Dole replied: ``Keep the press off the plane.''
   He complained that reporters on the campaign plane ``sit back
there and they scheme up these little things and the next thing
they're in Time or Newsweek.''
   Dole said he thought he had received some unfair news coverage
during the campaign. For example, he singled out the numerous
stories written about one of his Kansas associates, Dave Owen, who
resigned as national finance chairman of the Dole campaign in
January after reports raised questions involving his financial
dealings.
   But apart from all that, Dole said that his campaign
organization had blundered, particularly in New Hampshire and South
Carolina, and that those mistakes weakened his candidacy early in
the nominating process.
   For example, he did not respond to last-minute New Hampshire
television ads by Bush raising questions whether Dole cowld
increase taxes. In addition, his campaign spent heavily early in
the nominating process, which caused problems in later contests.
   ``South Carolina we probably should have bypassed instead of
getting in there,'' said Dole.
   Bush's win in South Carolina, he maintained, delivered a boost
to the vice president and helped him sweep the Super Tuesday
primaries that followed in the South, including North Carolina,
Missouri and Oklahoma _ states the Dole campaign had hoped to win.
   ``Now had we won New Hampshire, we still would have had a tough
race,'' Dole said.
   Illinois was the next battleground after Super Tuesday, and Dole
said, ``I knew that we weren't going to win Illinois and I knew
then it was probably over.''
   He said many of his friends and advisers urged him to remain in
the presidential race even when it appeared he had almost no chance
to win the nomination.
   ``You can't do it unless you've got the money,'' said Dole.
   The campaign, he said, would end with a ``little debt'' but he
said he didn't know the exact amount.
   Overall, Dole said, he was pleased with the fund-raising ability
of his campaign and said he had ``good organizations in a number of
states.''
   But he expressed reservations about the management of the
campaign, saying, ``I think as far as organization, I'm not certain
whether we had enough direction.''
   Dole did not criticize William Brock, his campaign chairman who
directed the operation, but said the national political director,
Norman Watts, ``I don't believe was strong enough.''
</TEXT>
