<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GossipWar Bjt   03-30 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gossip War, Bjt,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>James Says He Feels Cheated; Suzy Says He's a Rat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James and Suzy are having a tiff. And to the
delight of gossip-loving New Yorkers, they're having it out in
public _ in the columns they write for New York Newsday and the New
York Post.
   It began last week, when James _ that's James Revson, Newsday's
new society columnist _ wrote that he felt ``cheated and used'' by
Suzy, who wrote in the Post about a party she did not attend.
   What specifically bothered Revson (one of THE Revsons, of Revlon
cosmetics fame) was that Suzy mentioned 32 people who supposedly
were at the party, but only 12 of whom actually showed up.
   Suzy was on vacation (``on the sunswept isle of Mustique'') when
both her column and Revson's appeared. But by Wednesday she was
back. And Suzy _ that's just plain Suzy to you, Aileen Mehle to her
friends _ was furious.
   In a column that combined the tact of Joan Rivers with the
politesse of Sean Penn, Suzy called Revson ``a liar,'' ``a rat,'' a
``know-nothing,'' ``a nut,'' ``a jerk'' and ``a snake.'' Among
other things.
   To be sure, Suzy admitted she had written about the party,
thrown by Metropolitan Museum Chairman (and New York Times
Publisher) Arthur ``Punch'' Sulzberger, in advance. She said it was
the only way she could get out of town for her vacation (which was
``heaven.'').
   And yes, she said, it's true that some of the people she said
were at the party never did show up.
   And yes, ``I should have yanked the whole thing or at least the
names the (press) release said would attend.''
   But is she apologizing? Not a chance.
   ``I bow in accuracy and meticulousness and decency to no one,''
she wrote. ``That is the reason I have survived as a star all these
long years _ that and because in my field I am the best and the
brightest there is.''
   ``And dear readers, fans and publicity-seekers, I would like to
go on record as telling the world that any place Rat Revson is, I
will not be. Do not invite me anywhere if you invite him. Just call
it a boycott _ or even a Suzycott.''
   The target of the Suzycott says he is unimpressed. ``I'm not
joining it,'' he said. ``I refuse to join it even if she asks me.''
   Revson said he thought Suzy's column ``showed a certain lack of
restraint on her part. ... I didn't know that a lady knew those
words, or how to spell them.''
   ``On a serious note,'' he added, ``columnists are journalists,
columnists are reporters, and there are ethics. And nobody is
allowed to break those.''
   Is he worried about the effect of the Suzy controversy on his
fledgling column?
   ``I'm delighted,'' said Revson, obviously holding to the theory
that any publicity is good publicity. ``The next time I see her, I
may buy her a drink.''
</TEXT>
