<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RabiesOutbreak     03-30 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rabies Outbreak,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chester County Health Officials Say Rabies Outbreak Worsening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rabies outbreak in nearby Chester County
has prompted health officials to warn residents to avoid wild
animals and take extra measures to protect pets and farm animals.
   ``The problem is big, and it is growing,'' Harold Russell, chief
veterinarian for the county Health Department said Tuesday. ``What
we are seeing is the tip of a very massive iceberg.'' Eastern parts
of Chester County are some 20 miles west of Philadelphia.
   He warned the rabies virus, which last week forced officials to
kill a horse, is likely to spread into Philadelphia, especially
among raccoons in the city's sprawling Fairmount Park.
   A total of 23 rabies cases have been confirmed in Chester County
this year, compared to 36 in all of 1987, said Ruthie Ketterer,
secretary for the state Health Department's Acute Infectious
Disease division.
   Lancaster County, the next county west of Chester, has reported
37 cases. The total for the state for 1988 is 101, Ketterer said.
   Dr. Robert Sharrar, director of Philadelphia's Office of Health
Promotion and Disease Control, said Wednesday the city was
monitoring the rabies situation in Chester County and surrounding
counties and states.
   The last known case of human rabies in Philadelphia was in 1938,
and the last case in a dog was 1948, he said. Health officials
declared the city rabies free in 1975, but would revoke that
designation at the first rabies case and recommend rabies treatment
for anyone bitten by dogs or cats thereafter, he said.
   Rabies is a viral disease that attacks the brain and is almost
always fatal. A vaccine for humans and dogs was developed by Louis
Pasteur in the 1880s and scientists are working to develop an oral
vaccine which would work when eaten by wild animals.
</TEXT>
