<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-US     03-30 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-US,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Remain in Honduras to `Turn out the Lights'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Honduras-Troops, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven hundred of the U.S. troops
sent to Honduras on March 17-18 left Palmerola air base for the
United States and a U.S. spokesman said the rest will be home by
Thursday.
   ``The guys that turn out the lights will be leaving tomorrow
(Thursday),'' said Maj. Gary Hovatter, U.S. military public affairs
officer at Palmerola.
   Hovatter said planes left at a rate of about one an hour
Wednesday carrying the 700 soldiers and equipment back to Fort Ord,
Calif.
   President Reagan sent 3,200 American soldiers to Honduras after
President Jose Azcona Hoyo asked for help. Azcona said that
Sandinista troops from neighboring Nicaragua had invaded Honduras
in pursuit of Contra rebels.
   The Sandinistas reportedly retreated after the Honduran air
force twice bombed the border region, but the U.S. troops stayed on
to finish emergency training exercises with Honduran troops at five
bases throughout Honduras.
   The soldiers from the 82nd Airborne Division at Fort Bragg,
N.C., and the 7th Light Infantry Division at Fort Ord began to
return home Monday.
   Hovatter said the last of the soldiers, about 80 from the 82nd
Airborne, would leave Thursday after ``policing up the place.''
   The United States maintains a permanent operation of about 1,100
to 1,500 soldiers in its Joint Task Force Bravo operation at
Palmerola, the largest and most important U.S. military
headquarters in Central America north of Panama.
   The base is about 40 miles northwest of Tegucigalpa, the
Honduran capital.
   Hovatter said by telephone Wednesday that ``some of the planes
are carrying more equipment than people.''
   The Americans brought about 2.3 million pounds of equipment with
them, including two tanks, 12 105mm howitzers, machine guns,
ammunition and helicopters.
   ``It's gone very smoothly,'' Hovatter said of the redeployment.
``We've had minimal delays and no incidents or accidents.''
</TEXT>
