<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Simon     03-30 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon, Stressing His Experience, Enters Jackson Territory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon, entering territory staked
out by fellow Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson,
stood in front of a Chrysler Corp. plant Wednesday and declared he
is more qualified to take workers' concerns to the White House.
   When asked whether he has hesitated criticizing Jackson for fear
of offending black voters, Simon said: ``You have to be careful.
You don't want to be perceived as anti-black.'' But he added, ``I
don't have problems running against anyone.''
   ``I'm not here knocking others,'' Simon said, ``but I think
experience is one of the things you should look at.''
   Jackson had led an emotional rally earlier this year at the auto
plant, where 5,500 workers are scheduled to be laid off by the end
of September. Jackson's support for the workers and his call to end
``economic violence'' won him the endorsement of the United Auto
Workers union Local 72.
   Simon, at a news conference next to the plant, said he has a
similar message plus the congressional experience to translate it
into action.
   ``I have been fighting for (workers') policies on the Washington
scene, not just with speeches,'' Simon said. ``I offer not only
passion, but programs.''
   Simon, who won the March 15 Illinois primary, is campaigning for
support in Wisconsin's primary April 5. ``I'm going to do well in
Wisconsin,'' he said, ``and we're going on to Atlanta,'' site of
the Democratic National Convention July 18-21.
   About 20 Simon supporters were on hand for the news conference,
along with some auto workers.
   ``I think he is speaking for the workers as well as Jackson,''
said Bill Seep, an employee of the plant.
   Another employee, Phil Haney, said he expected the workers to
stay unified behind Jackson, though he added some might choose
Simon when they cast their ballots. ``You can't fault anyone who
votes for Simon,'' he said.
   Simon said he would try to rebuild the country's manufacturing
base by removing tax breaks for companies that move jobs overseas
and by giving corporations incentives to boost production in the
United States.
   He added that he came to Kenosha ``because of this plant and
what it represents. What we have had is an administration that has
elevated and sanctified greed.''
   He accused Chrysler of deciding to halt production without
giving enough consideration to the impact on the workers and the
community.
</TEXT>
