<1ST_LINE>r w AM-KidneyStones     03-30 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidney Stones,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lithotripsy Machine Effective On Small Kidney Stones, Panel Finds</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Fredric is cq in 6th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A machine that sends a shockwave into the body
to break up kidney stones is effective and less risky than invasive
surgery, a panel of experts concluded Wednesday following a
conference at the National Institutes of Health.
   The panel, organized to reach a consensus on how best to treat
and prevent kidney stones, recommended use of the extracorporeal
shockwave lithotriptor to treat kidney stones smaller than 2
centimeters in diameter. It said that a combination of therapies,
which may include surgery, may be needed for larger stones.
   The lithotriptor, introduced in the United States in 1984, uses
a fluid shockwave, generated by an electrical pulse, to break up
stones in the kidney or in the duct that drains the kidney. Once
the stones are broken up, they can be more easily passed out of the
body. The procedure routinely does not require surgery.
   More than a half million people have been treated with the
lithotriptor worldwide, the panel said, and it has been proven to
be effective.
   But the experts cautioned that because lithotriptsy is new,
``the long-term effects of the therapy are unknown.''
   Dr. Fredric L. Coe, a professor of medicine at the University of
Chicago and chairman of the panel, said there have been reports of
elevated blood pressure among some lithotriptsy patients, and there
have been cases where the therapy causes kidney injury. He said
these problems need to be further studied.
   For kidney stones larger than 2 centimeters, the panel
recommended the use of a combined therapy that would include a
surgical procedure called nephrolithotomy. Using this technique,
surgeons make a small incision near the kidney and then insert a
flexible tube that can be manuevered to the site of the kidney
stone. By manipulating instruments through the tube, the surgeon
can break up the kidney stone and remove it.
   Coe said the panel recommended a therapy system in which stones
larger than 2 centimeters would be removed by nephrolithotomy.
Small stones or fragments could then be treated with lithotripsy.
Later, if needed, a second removal surgery could be performed. He
said this combination was preferrable to repeated sessions of
lithotripsy.
   Open surgery, where a wide incision is made and the kidney
exposed, is required now only in rare cases involving special types
of stones or other physical factors, Coe said.
   Kidney stones account for seven to 10 of every 1,000 hospital
admissions in the United States. There are seven to 21 cases of
kidney stone annually for every 10,000 persons. Though the stones
may cause great pain, they are rarely life-threatening.
   Coe said about 70 percent of all kidney stone cases can be
treated using lithotripsy.
   For prevention of stones, the panel recommended the use of
medication for certain types of stones, a modification of diet
where indicated, and increased fluid intake. Increased urination,
caused by a higher fluid intake, the panel said, can lower the
concentration in the urine of chemicals that tend to form stones.
   Kidney stones are formed when chemicals in the urine crystalize.
About 80 percent of the stones are formed of calcium oxalate
crystals. Others are of calcium phosphate salts, uric acid, cystine
or a combination of magnesium, ammonium and phosphate.
</TEXT>
