<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HandicapClothing     03-30 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Handicap Clothing,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FSU Students Design Clothing For Children With Medical Devices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fashion students at Florida State
University are putting their design talents to work for children
stuck with cumbersome or awkward medical devices.
   ``Parents of handicapped children buy ready-made clothes, then
slash them and cut them to make them fit,'' Emma Kittles, a
professor of clothing, textiles and merchandising said Wednesday.
``It's almost impossible to buy clothing to fit the devices their
children have to wear.''
   Kittles has challenged a class to design clothing that is
functional, comfortable and has style. Their results will be
compiled in a step-by-step teaching manual on designing clothing
for disabled children.
   Thinking of children 2 to 13, the students must design clothes
that would be easy to put on and would camouflage any medical
devices.
   For children in wheelchairs, the students must design outfits
that eliminate excess folds and bulk and that are made of fabrics
that don't chafe.
   Another challenge for the students is designing clothes that
make it easier for children to dress themselves with the help of
front or side fasteners, such as Velcro, large snaps and zippers
with large tabs.
   ``Children are at the stage that they are learning things to
make them independent; one of those things is dressing
themselves,'' said Kittles. ``But even if the child cannot dress
himself, the therapist and parents want clothing that is easy to
manipulate on these children.''
   Because each child's needs are different, the students will
interview the parents before measuring, buying fabrics and
designing outfits. The child also shares personal preferences, such
as favorite colors.
</TEXT>
