<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Israel,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patriarch Of Jerusalem Makes Holy Week Appeal For Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic patriarch of Jerusalem,
in a Vatican Radio interview Wednesday, appealed to Christians and
``responsible politicians'' to work for peace in the Holy Land.
   Monsignor Michel Sabbah, a Palestinian, said unrest in the
Israeli-occupied territories seemed worse as ``we celebrate Holy
Week by reflecting on the suffering of Christ and of the people of
Jerusalem and of all those in prison, dead, injured and suffering
from hunger.''
   He said the church could only pray and ``appeal to the whole
world, to all the responsible politicians ... to put an end to this
human tragedy that we have been living for so many years.''
   Sabbah, the first Arab patriarch for Latin rite Catholics in the
Holy Land, did not criticize either Israelis or Palestinians for
the violence, and said both groups were suffering.
   He told the station in the telephone interview that he did not
think the violence would disrupt Easter ceremonies in the region.
But he said is appealing to all Christians to pray that political
leaders can bring peace to the Holy Land.
