<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     03-30 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikhs Kill 15, Bringing Toll to 50 in Three Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh radicals killed 15 more people in
Punjab, bringing the death toll to 50 in three days of attacks
linked to their violent separatist campaign, police reported
Wednesday.
   Attacks blamed on Sikh militants have taken at least 580 lives
already this year in Punjab, India's main agricultural region and
the only state where Sikhs are the majority. The death toll for all
of 1987 was about 1,000.
   This week's violence has included the first successful use of
rocket-propelled grenades against police. Izhar Alam, the Punjab
police chief, said he believes arms are being smuggled in from
Pakistan.
   Seven people killed Tuesday night were members of two Sikh
families in the Amritsar district adjacent to Pakistan, Alam said.
   Many attacks involve random fire. On Monday night, gunmen killed
10 people at a Sikh wedding party, including the bride and groom. A
survivor said the raiders shouted that family members were police
informers.
   Although members of the sect have a majority in Punjab, Sikhs
make up only 2 percent of India's 800 million people, more than 80
percent of whom are Hindus.
   Targets of the Sikh gunmen include moderate Sikhs who oppose a
separate state, as well as Hindus. At least 328 of this year's
victims have been Sikhs.
   An increasing worry for Punjabi authorities is the more powerful
weaponry being introduced, including grenade launchers and AK-47
assault rifles.
   No casualties were reported in the first attack with
rocket-propelled grenades, made on a police barracks last week. On
Tuesday night, however, 10 men were wounded by grenades fired at a
truck carrying paramilitary personnel of the Border Security Force
in the Gurdaspur district north of Amritsar.
   Police found an underground arms cache in the Amritsar district
Sunday that included 14 Soviet-made RPG-7 launchers along with
HE-80 anti-tank grenades, said S.S. Virk, a senior officer of the
paramilitary Central Reserve Police.
   Alam's claim that arms have come from Pakistan conforms with
Indian allegations that Pakistan arms the militants, a charge the
government in Islamabad denies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
