<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador     03-30 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winning Party in Election Pulls Out of Vote Counting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rightist Arena party has
withdrawn from vote counting in the March 20 election, claiming
others are trying to deprive it of victory, officials said
Wednesday.
   Election officials announced soon after the election that Arena,
an abbreviation of Republican Nationalist Alliance, had defeated
the Christian Democratic Party of President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   It appeared at the time that Arena would get at least 31 of the
60 National Assembly seats under the system of proportional
representation, with about 22 being assigned to Christian Democrats.
   Arena left the count Tuesday night by taking its representative
off the three-member Central Elections Council, which does the
tallying. It was protesting a council decision to consider
challenges to the elections of three Arena candidates.
   Francisco Merino, the party's council representative, said the
other members wanted to make a ``game of the vote tallies in order
to change the results of the elections.''
   The other members are the council president, Mario Samayoa of
the Christian Democrats, and Arturo Mendez Azahar of the
conservative National Conciliation Party. Two votes are enough to
approve any decision.
   Roberto d'Aubuisson, the former army major who founded Arena,
told reporters recently that if his party did not receive 31 seats
it would be a case of ``fraud and we will withdraw from this
democratic process.''
   Alfredo Cristiani, president of Arena, said in a television
interview Wednesday: ``The people are being defrauded. This could
explode at any moment, something difficult to stop (could) occur.''
   In a recent interview, Samayoa denied the accusation of fraud in
the vote-counting, which he said ``only exists in the mind of those
who have manipulated the information about the results in their
favor.''
   He said officials completed the official tallies and assignment
of seats last Saturday for 11 of the 14 provinces, but some
recounts would be needed in the other three because of challenges.
   The Arena upset presented Duarte, a staunch U.S. ally, with dim
prospects for his last year in office. Presidential elections are
set for March 1989.
   Arena benefited from popular discontent about Duarte's failure
to meet his 1984 campaign pledges of improving the economy and
ending the 8-year-old civil war with leftist guerrillas.
   Both unemployement and the annual inflation rate are estimated
at 40 percent.
</TEXT>
