<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PublicWorks     03-30 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Public Works,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rep. Howard's Death Could Cause Public Works Committee Shifts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of Chairman James Howard of the
House Public Works and Transportation Committee paves the way for a
relatively obscure Californian to take over the panel, and for
possible shifts among subcommittee leaders.
   Rep. Glenn Anderson of Los Angeles is acting chairman of the
public works panel and its ranking Democrat. Anderson's top aide,
Jeremiah Bresnahan, asked Wednesday if the lawmaker would want to
become the panel's permanent chairman, said, ``I can't imagine he
wouldn't want to be.''
   Other legislators and committee aides, asking to not be
identified, said it appeared certain that Anderson would become
committee chairman, probably next month, and that he was not likely
to be challenged for the job.
   Anderson, 75, is a former California lieutenant governor who was
elected to the House in 1968. He is a strong union supporter who
has been an advocate for many projects the committee oversees, but
he has been one of the least visible members of the panel's
leadership.
   The real question is whether Anderson will choose to retain his
chairmanship of the surface transportation subcommittee when he
takes control of the entire committee. That subcommittee, which
oversees enormous highway, water and mass transit programs, is
generally considered the most desirable on the committee.
   Under House rules, Anderson could retain both posts.
   Robert Maitlin, an aide to Rep. Robert Roe, D-N.J., who ranks
behind Anderson in seniority, said it is ``very doubtful'' Roe
would give up his chairmanship of the Science, Space and Technology
Committee to take over the surface transportation subcommittee.
   Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., said he might be interested in
heading the surface transportation subcommittee if Anderson vacated
the job. Mineta now chairs the committee's aviation subcommittee.
   House Democratic rules call for a nominee to head a committee to
be selected by the Democratic Steering and Policy Committee, a
panel of 31 Democratic representatives dominated by the party's
leadership. That selection must then be approved by a vote of the
257 Democrats in the House, and then by the entire House.
   The 60-year-old Howard, D-N.J., died last Friday, a day after
being stricken with a heart attack while playing golf in suburban
Maryland.
</TEXT>
