<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CornPesticide     03-30 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corn Pesticide,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Scientists See No Danger From New Genetically Engineered
Pesticide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental Protection Agency scientists can
foresee no risk to humans or other organisms from a proposed field
test in Maryland of a new genetically engineered pesticide, the
agency said Wednesday.
   The pesticide, if eventually approved, would be used against the
European corn borer.
   Crop Genetics Inc. of Hanover, Md., applied to both EPA and the
Agriculture Department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service
to test the new substance on its farm near Ingleside, Md., and at
the Agriculture Department's research station at Beltsville, Md.
   The report by microbiologists and plant pathologists from the
hazard evaluation divison of EPA's pesticides office said the
properties of the engineered organism and results of lab tests on
mice ``indicate that there are no human health risks.''
   The report said it is difficult to transfer the organism from
one plant to another except on the blades of cutting tools, and the
engineered organism eventually should die out in competition with
the natural strain.
   ``For this small-scale field test, providing all the
containment, monitoring and contingency procedures are adhered to,
we can foresee no risk to non-target insects and no effect on
endangered species,'' and the organism may be used, the group said.
   The report will be considered at a public meeting April 18 of a
subcommittee of EPA's pesticide scientific advisory panel. The
panel's report is expected in time for a decision on the permits in
May.
</TEXT>
