<2ND_LINE>AM-ANC Killing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Offices Attacked in Paris and Marseille</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, In Marseille ... CORRECTING definition of
SS to elite guard sted secret police. Picks up 11th graf pvs, About
1,000 ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded near the South African Embassy here
Wednesday, a few hours after police arrested more than 80 people
protesting the assassination of an African National Congress
official.
   In the southern port city of Marseille, at least six gunshots
were fired Tuesday night at a building in front of the South
African Consulate. The gunmen fled in a car and no arrests were
made.
   No injuries were reported from the bomb which exploded about 3
a.m. Wednesday at a Paris office building a few blocks from the
embassy. Police said no claim of responsiblity had been received.
   Late Tuesday night, police arrested 41 demonstrators who broke
into and smashed the South African Tourism office, and 46 others
who painted anti-apartheid slogans on the home of the South African
ambassador in Paris.
   Police identified the protesters only as young leftists who
supported the ANC. All but four were released overnight.
   They were protesting the slaying of Dulcie September, 53, the
ANC representative to France, Switzerland and Luxembourg, who was
found dead Tuesday outside the door of the ANC's Paris office. She
had been shot in the face.
   Police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at the
time that the killing looked like ``the work of a professional.''
   The ANC, the main guerrilla group fighting the apartheid
government of South Africa, blamed Pretoria for September's death.
The South African government denied responsibility and said the
attack was related to strife within the ANC, which was banned by
South Africa in 1960.
   A French Foreign Ministry spokesman said Tuesday that no claim
of responsiblity had been received.
   In Marseille, the gunshots were fired at 11:15 p.m. Tuesday at
the windows of a building in front of the consulate. The building
was painted with the slogan, ``Botha, assassin, SS,'' a reference
to South African President P.W. Botha and to Adolf Hitler's elite
guard, the most powerful instrument of Nazi power.
   About 1,000 people marched peacefully in a separate protest in
Paris Tuesday evening.
   President Francois Mitterrand said Tuesday he would ask South
Africa about the attack and reaffirmed his ``condemnation of the
regime of racial segregation.''
   A colleague of Ms. September's claimed that she had requested
protection from the Interior Ministry after receiving death threats
and being followed. The Interior Ministry denied that Ms. September
had requested protection.
   ``If she had asked, we would have given it to her,'' a ministry
spokeswoman said.
   Ms. September came to Paris after spending five years in a South
African prison for her outspoken criticism of apartheid.
   Ms. September's sister, Stephanie Arendse, said that after she
was released from prison ``she became quiet and didn't talk about
her politics so much.''
   In an interview published Wednesday in the South African daily,
the Cape Times, Mrs. Arendse said the family was uncertain whether
Ms. September's body would be returned to South Africa for burial.
   Ms. September, the oldest of three daughters and a teacher by
training, was tried in 1963 along with 10 others for treason and
sabotage and sentenced in 1964 to five years in prison, at the age
of 29.
   On her release in 1969 she was placed under house arrest and
confined to Wynburg, in northern Cape province.
   Mrs. Arendse said her sister left South Africa on an exit visa
in 1973 and settled in London, where she attended a nursing school.
   She was an administrative secretary at the ANC's Lusaka, Zambia,
headquarters and served in other capacities before 1984, when she
became representative for France, Luxembourg and Switzerland.
   An ANC spokesman on Tuesday called Ms. September one of the
organization's ``most vigorous activists.''
</TEXT>
