<HEAD>Pecks Again Host A Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHIPPEWA FALLS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean and Leonard Peck, having
breakfast Wednesday with Democratic presidential candidate Albert
Gore, said they didn't mind having that media crowd in their
kitchen _ they'd seen it all before.
   Exactly 12 years earlier, a Georgia peanut farmer, Jimmy Carter,
had visited the Wisconsin dairy farm family on his way to the White
House.
   ``I guess we have a popular farm,'' Leonard Peck, 67, said after
Gore, his press entourage and Secret Service agents left. ``It's a
lot of work, but it's a thrill,'' said his wife. ``I think it
worked better this time because we had been through it before.''
   Gore, a senator from Tennessee, spent Tuesday night at the Peck
farm. He put on work clothes and helped prepare cows for milking
and put straw in animal stalls before joining the family for a
breakfast of pancakes, sausage and a family specialty made with
cornflakes, ice cream, strawberries and cream.
   Gore's farm background came through. ``You could tell that he
knew his way around the farm and he could handle a fork and acted
at home with the cows,'' Leonard Peck said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Gore Aide Questions Jackson's Plan To Deliver Easter Sermon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to presidential hopeful Albert Gore says
Jesse Jackson may be using Easter as a ``political pulpit'' if he
solicits campaign funds during a sermon Sunday.
   ``If we were to use Easter Sunday as a political pulpit, you
guys in the newspapers would beat us to death,'' Mike Veit, Gore's
Colorado campaign coordinator, told The Denver Post Tuesday.
   ``If we went in and raised money in a Sunday church service,
you'd beat us up even worse,'' added Veit, stressing his comments
reflected his views and not those of Gore.
   Colorado's presidential caucuses will be held the day after
Easter, and campaign staffers for Gore, a senator from Tennessee,
and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis have been reluctant to
schedule big political events for the religious weekend.
   Jackson is to deliver a sermon Sunday at the First Baptist
Church in Denver's Capitol Hill, where the pastor says Jackson's
appearance will be part of a worship service, not a political
rally. But the pastor says three collections will be taken _ one
for the churches, one for missionary work, and one for Jackson's
campaign.
