<HEAD>Dukakis Leads Jackson, Bush In Poll Of New Yorkers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll says Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
leads Jesse Jackson among Democrats likely to vote in New York's
April 19 primary but Jackson has an edge among those strongly
committed to a candidate.
   According to a Chicago Sun-Times-Gallup Poll released Tuesday,
Dukakis was the only Democrat to lead Vice President George Bush
among New York voters. In general election matchups, Dukakis led
Bush 49 percent to 41 percent, while Bush led Jackson 55 percent to
31 percent.
   Of the New York Democrats interviewed, 44 percent preferred
Dukakis, 28 percent favored Jackson, 3 percent chose Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore and 2 percent backed Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois.
   But only 14 percent of Democrats who said they were strongly
committed to a candidate planned to vote for Dukakis, while 21
percent favored Jackson.
   The results were based on telephone interviews with 1,205
registered New York voters conducted between Friday and Sunday. The
sample included 421 likely to vote in the Democratic primary and
329 in the Republican primary. The margin of error was 5 percent
among Democrats and 3 percent for general election matchups.
</TEXT>
