<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Marcos     03-30 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos To Philippines: I'll Be Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos, the exiled former president of
the Philippines, says negotiations for a return to his homeland are
under way and he will likely go back ``very soon,'' a published
report said.
   ``If I have a political role to play, we will negotiate that
later,'' Marcos was quoted as saying in the latest edition of Paris
Match, which goes on sale Thursday.
   The Philippine government has said it sent emissaries to talk to
Marcos in January and February. Mrs. Aquino has said that before
Marcos returns, he must give back billions of dollars he allegedly
stole during his 20-year rule. Marcos has denied stealing any money.
   ``Negotiations have started between the government of Mrs.
(Corazon) Aquino and myself,'' Marcos was quoted as saying in an
interview in his exile home in Honolulu. ``These negotiations are
continuing at this moment and going very well. I hope that we can
very quickly set the date of my return, as well as the conditions.''
   Asked when he would return, he responded, ``Man proposes and God
disposes ... I will be going home very soon,'' the magazine said.
   Marcos fled the Philippines during a civilian-military revolt in
the wake of fraud-tainted Feb. 7, 1986 presidential elections in
which both he and Mrs. Aquino claimed victory. Mrs. Aquino revoked
his passport.
   In the Paris Match interview, Marcos was quoted as expressing
his admiration ``for the way Mrs. Aquino is confronting all sorts
of problems.'' But he also expressed fears that her government
could soon disintegrate.
   ``The communists will then have a free field to immediately take
power,'' he is quoted as telling the weekly photo magazine, in a
reference to leftist rebels.
   ``For me the only way to make a contribution to national unity
is to return to my country, with respect for all conditions we can
agree to.''
   Marcos also is quoted as saying that he needs to return for
health reasons, especially old war wounds acting up, and to settle
lawsuits filed against him since he was deposed.
</TEXT>
