<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugTesting     03-30 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Testing,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judicial Panel Sets Aside Injunction Barring Army Random Drug
Testing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preliminary injunction barring random drug
testing of 9,400 civilian Army employees was set aside by a federal
appellate court Tuesday while it considers the Justice Department's
appeal of a lower court order.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here
granted a stay that was sought by the Justice Department of the
preliminary injunction issued by U.S. District Judge Thomas F.
Hogan on March 1.
   Hogan had ordered the Army to stop random urine testing of
civilian Army employees, finding that the practice was an
``excessively intrusive'' search prohibited by the Constitution.
   The preliminary injunction was issued in a case brought by
public employee unions representing civilian Army employees at Ft.
Stewart, Fla.; Aberdeen Proving Ground, Md.; and the Sharp Army
Depot in Lathrop, Calif.
   The injunction banned random testing of all 9,400 civilians in
sensitive jobs who were subject to the anti-drug program, including
pilots, guards and police officers on military bases.
   In issuing the injunction, Hogan had expressed regret that it
``removes what might be a powerful weapon from the nation's arsenal
in the campaign against illegal drug use, but the values
represented by the Constitution and Fourth Amendment are
transcendent.''
   Citing a legal precedent that allows stays of judicial decisions
when a party is likely to prevail on the merits of a dispute,
Circuit Judges Stephen Williams, James Buckley and D.H. Ginsburg
said ``a stay is warranted in this case.''
   Kenneth T. Blaylock, president of the American Federation of
Government Employees, expressed disappointment that the appellate
judges had set aside the injunction against random testing. He said
the union was ``determined to continue its fight to protect
employee rights under the Constitution.''
   Justice Department spokesman Amy Brown said the department was
pleased with the court's decision to stay Hogan's order. The Army
had no immediate comment.
   No date has been set for a hearing on the department's appeal in
the case.
</TEXT>
