<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 2124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-UraniumBill 1stLd-Writethru a0722 03-30 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uranium Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0722,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Plan To Revitalize Ailing U.S. Uranium Industry</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 11th graf pvs, bgng: They argued, to clarify objections
to bill</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate passed 62-28 on Wednesday a bill
designed to revitalize the devastated U.S. uranium industry and
restructure the government's own failing program to sell enriched
fuel to nuclear power plants.
   The bill, which faces an uncertain future in the House, also
would establish a $1 billion fund to clean up or stablize large,
mildly radioactive piles of uranium tailings at 26 sites in seven
Western states. The cost would be shared equally by uranium mill
owners, nuclear utilities and the government.
   Among its more controversial provisions, the legislation _ which
took six years to clear the Senate _ would:
   _Impose a schedule of escalating fees on nuclear utilities that
load their reactors with more than 37.5 percent foreign uranium.
Beginning in 1995, however, utilities could buy up to half their
uranium from foreign suppliers without penalty. Opponents,
including Sens. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., and Daniel Evans, R-Wash.,
argued that this would violate the spirit of the recent free trade
pact signed with Canada, a leading exporter of relatively
inexpensive, high-grade ore. Bradley and Evans lost an attempt,
47-45, to delete the import restrictions from the bill.
   _Settle the nuclear industry's debt to the U.S. treasury for
past purchases of enriched uranium at $364 million. Opponents
argued that the figure should be as high as $8.8 billion.
   _Convert the Department of Energy's uranium enrichment program,
supposedly self-financing but a multibillion-dollar loser since the
mid-1970s, into a corporation owned by the government. If and when
the enterprise begins turning profits, the treasury could sell the
stock in a bid to recover previous investments.
   Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., who guided the measure through
his Energy Committee, said it is ``the culmination of six years of
legislative effort to fashion a sound, sensible and well-balanced
program to address the challenges we face today in the uranium
industry and the nuclear fuel cycle.
   ``We're not here to debate the Canadian trade deal,'' Johnston
said. ``Let's keep American jobs at home.''
   He estimated the bill would restore 20,000 jobs in the uranium
mining industry, which has dwindled in this decade to 2,000 workers
at just three mines. And he estimated the uranium enrichment
workforce, cut by half since 1980, could be restored to at least
12,000 jobs.
   The National Taxpayers Union, the Environmental Policy
Institute, the Union of Concerned Scientists, the U.S. Public
Interest Research Group and Environmental Action all opposed key
provisions of the bill, particularly the feature which limits the
government's recovery of uranium enrichment costs to $364 million.
   The groups argued that charging just $364 million is an
unprecedented bailout for the nuclear industry since the White
House has estimated that the industry should be billed $3 billion
and the General Accounting Office said the government should charge
$8.8 billion.
   The 1954 Atomic Energy Act required the government to be fully
compensated for its enrichment of nuclear fuel used by commercial
utilities.
   Enrichment is a critical process in nuclear power. It involves
increasing the percentage of fissionable material in natural
uranium from 0.7 percent to about 3 percent, the amount necessary
for use in light-water reactors.
   When the government began enriching commercial fuel in 1969, the
United States was the only free-world supplier of the service for
nuclear utilities and business was booming. Predictions of
burgeoning demand led to the expansion of the three DOE plants,
and, even then, all capacity was committeed.
   But then came a drastic decline in the demand for nuclear power,
with utilities canceling plans for more than 100 additional
reactors since the late 1970s. Meanwhile, two European consortiums
and the Soviet Union began to supply foreign utilities with
enriched uranium, and by the 1980s, the U.S. monopoly had dropped
to 50 percent of the market. Even some U.S. utilities found it
cheaper to buy foreign uranium.
   Adding to the government enrichment program's woes was the fact
that the Energy Department contracted with the Tennessee Valley
Authority for billions of dollars worth of electricity to operate
its production plants. But when demand fell off, that electricty
wasn't used _ even though TVA charged for it anyway. The Senate
legislation settles that long-term debt at $1.2 billion.
</TEXT>
