<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Resignation     03-30 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Resignation,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel's Ambassador To United Nations Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benjamin Netanyahu, who gained prominence as an
articulate defender of Israel's policies in his post as ambassador
to the United Nations, announced his resignation Wednesday.
   Netanyahu became Israel's permanent representative to the United
Nations in September 1984 after serving two years as the deputy
chief of mission at the Israeli Embassy in Washington.
   He is known for his forceful views on terrorism and is the
editor of a 1986 book called ``Terrorism: How the West Can Win.''
   Netanyahu, 39, plans to compete for a seat in the Parliament,
running as a candidate of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
right-wing Likud Bloc, Israel Radio said.
   ``I have accelerated my resignation because, as I think, we are
facing fateful decisions,'' Netanyahu said on Israel Television.
``I think we must ... create a policy based on the correct reading
of the international map.''
   ``As an ambassador, I could not voice my thoughts. I certainly
plan to do so and to influence the policy,'' he said.
   He said that ``Israel has to maintain a full military control
over all the territory west of the Jordan River'' and reject the
U.S. peace proposal, which he called a ``dangerous plan.''
   Israel has faced nearly four months of unrest in the occupied
West Bank of the Jordan River and the Gaza Strip, which it seized
in 1967.
   Netanyahu, the son of a Cornell University professor, has lived
in the United States most of his life. He attended high school in
Philadelphia and studied business administration at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   His education was interrupted when he returned to Israel in 1967
for a five-year stint in the army, during which he reached the rank
of captain.
   Netanyahu's brother Jonathan was killed during Israel's 1976
rescue of hostages in Entebbe, Uganda.
  
</TEXT>
