<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     03-30 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Stresses His Experience Compared to Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael Dukakis,
seeking a way to open a lead over Jesse Jackson, began Wednesday to
show how he might deal with his charismatic rival _ by stressing
his government experience.
   Dukakis sought to sidestep any direct criticism of Jackson,
whose campaign has boosted the Democratic Party with many new
voters who will be needed in the November election. But he
indirectly raised the issue of qualifications.
   ``I think (voters) want to know which one of us has the strength
and the experience and the values to lead this country, to build a
strong future. ... That's what this race is all about, that's what
the presidency is all about,'' Dukakis said at a Statehouse news
conference.
   Jackson's victories on Super Tuesday and in Michigan have made
him Dukakis' principal challenger, and Dukakis has been struggling
to find an effective way to fight off Jackson without alienating
Jackson's backers.
   Dukakis was drawing fire from another Democratic contender, Sen.
Albert Gore Jr., who accused him Wednesday of being overly
reluctant to specifically spell out his differences with Jackson.
   ``He was asked: Why would you make a better president?'' Gore
said of Dukakis. ``He said, `I'm not going to answer that question.
I think that's ludicrous.''
   However, Dukakis has been using the experience theme to separate
himself from Jackson, who has never held elective office.
   ``I'm a doer. I just don't talk about these things. I've created
jobs. I'm building housing for families of low and moderate
income,'' Dukakis told an interviewer on the CBS ``This Morning''
show.
   But at his Boston news conference, Dukakis was at pains to say
he considers himself on friendly terms with Jackson.
   ``We get along. We enjoy each other's company. He knows about
the things we're doing here. We know about the things he's doing,''
the governor said.
   Pressed, however, Dukakis mentioned two broad areas in which he
and Jackson differ.
   ``We don't agree on Middle East policy. We don't agree on some
aspects of economic policy here in the United States,'' Dukakis
said.
   He refused to go into detail, promising to do so in a speech in
Wisconsin later this week.
   Dukakis said he spoke to Jackson by telephone Wednesday morning,
just hours after taking a 2-to-1 victory over Jackson in the
Connecticut primary. However, the Massachusetts governor refused to
say what the two men discussed.
</TEXT>
