<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AFL-CIO-Coors-Teamsters     03-30 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AFL-CIO-Coors-Teamsters,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO Gives Teamsters Sole Organizing Rights At Coors Brewery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO on Wednesday awarded its
once-bitter rival, the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, sole
oranizing rights to attempt unionizing the Adolph Coors Co.'s lead
brewery at Golden, Colo.
   The labor federation ordered one of its veteran affiliates, the
Machinists Union, to halt efforts to organize the same 3,200 Coors
workers, saying the Teamsters had a much better chance of
succeeding.
   The decision was an outgrowth of the Teamsters' decision last
October to reaffiliate their 1.6 million members with the AFL-CIO.
The union had been expelled 30 years earlier on charges of
corruption.
   Last September, before the Teamsters reaffiliation, the labor
federation had awarded sole organizing rights to the Machinists
Union at Coors. But the Teamsters challenged that ruling as soon as
they were readmitted.
   Facing ongoing organizing efforts by the Teamsters over the past
two years, Coors and the AFL-CIO last August ended one of the most
prolonged and heated labor-management disputes in the country.
   In that agreement, the labor federation brought to an end its
10-year-old nationwide boycott of Coors beer. In exchange the
company agreed to forgo erecting legal roadblocks often used by
management against an attempt by an AFL-CIO-affiliated union to
organize its workforce.
   But that was before the Teamsters were again an AFL-CIO
affiliate. And Teamsters officials admitted they had concerns now
about how the Coors-AFL-CIO pact will hold up in the face of the
federation's decision Wednesday.
   ``We're elated,'' said Charles Klare, director of the Teamsters'
100,000-member brewery and soft drinks division. ``But there's a
lot to be found out yet. We've got to meet with Coors and determine
if they accept the fact that the AFL-CIO picked us.''
   The Machinists Union had argued before Murray Finley, a former
president of the Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers Union who
was picked by AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland to arbitrate the
dispute, that the Teamsters should give up the Coors effort based
on last September's decision.
   The Teamsters countered they had an ongoing organizing campaign
at Coors a year before the Machinists entered the picture and had
gotten more than 30 percent of the workers at Golden to sign
Teamster union cards.
   Kirkland agreed with the Teamsters, according to witnesses at
the arbitration proceedings.
   ``It was a black-and-white case, based on the facts,'' said
Vicki Saporta, the Teamsters' director of organizing. ``We were
there first and they didn't even have a single card signed. We're
also the predominant union in the industry. We have contracts at
all 12 Anheuser-Busch breweries covering some 9,000 workers.''
</TEXT>
