<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ActivistSlain 1stLd-Writethru a0738 03-30 0924</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Activist Slain, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0738,0947</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Activist Eulogized At Memorial Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with special prosecutor
appointed, congressman asking for subcommittee hearing, quotes from
later funeral service, remove outdated and redundant material.
Pickup 11th graf pvs, `There's a tremendous...' SUBS 19th graf,
bgng `Chavis' father' to DELETE first reference to Britt.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEMBROKE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special prosecutor was appointed
Wednesday to investigate the death of Julian Pierce, an Indian
activist running for a judgeship who was eulogized as Robeson
County's ``best hope for change.''
   The appointment by the state attorney general's office was made
at the request of county District Attorney Joe Freeman Britt, who
had been Pierce's opposition in the race for the Superior Court
judgeship.
   Pierce, who was found dead Saturday, has been mourned by
supporters who at first said they suspected he was killed because
someone did not want a Lumbee Indian to be elected judge. More than
2,300 people attended a funeral and a memorial service for the
activist Wednesday.
   Sheriff Hubert Stone said Pierce's slaying was apparently the
result of a broken romance, not a political vendetta, but that he
was still investigating comments made by Sandy Gordon Chavis.
Chavis had has been charged with murder in the incident; another
man involved in the shooting committed suicide Tuesday, officials
said.
   Senior Deputy Attorney General Jim Coman, a member of the
attorney general's special prosecution unit, was appointed special
prosecutor in the case, said John Simmons, a spokesman for Attorney
General Lacy Thornburg.
   Coman said he hoped to begin meeting with investigators next
week.
   Earlier, Rep. Harles Rose, D-N.C., whose district include
Robeson County, said he has asked for a congressional criminal
justice subcommittee, headed by Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., to hold
a hearing in the county.
   ``The only role a subcommittee would have would be to look at
how the federal government is interfacing down here,'' Rose said.
``I want to know, is this county getting the kind of federal help
it needs?''
   About 1,500 people attended a memorial service at Pembroke State
University and 800 mourners later jammed a small church in Maxton
for Pierce's funeral.
   ``He was loved. He was respected,'' said the Rev. Johnnie Chavis
during services at the Sycamore Hill Independent Holiness Church.
``That says a lot more than we can say about a lot of people.'' The
minister said he was a distant relative of the man who was arrested.
   Pierce's family filled up half of the seats in the 400-seat
church. Several hundred others sat on wooden chairs outside.
   At the Pembroke memorial service, Christine Griffin, acting
co-director of Lumbee River Legal Services, said Pierce's
compassion was ``overwhelming and all-consuming.''
   ``He was the best hope we had,'' Mrs. Griffin told the packed
auditorium. ``If he were here, he would say to us not to use the
same weapons that were used against him to bring about change.''
   ``We will keep up the peaceful fight for change through the
courts and through the ballot box,'' said the Rev. Joy Johnson.
   ``He was our first real hero for meaningful change in Robeson
County,'' said Johnson. Pierce had been the legal services
executive director until he resigned to run for judge.
   Despite the arrest of Sandy Gordon Chavis, Indian leaders said
racial tension would not go away.
   ``There's a tremendous amount of suspicion ... that perhaps all
the answers have not been put forward,'' Vernon Bellecourt, a
representative of the American Indian Movement, said Wednesday.
   Chavis said that John Anderson Goins, also 24 and a Lumbee
Indian from Pembroke, shot and killed Pierce, Stone said. Goins
committed suicide Tuesday.
   Stone said the killing appeared to stem from Goins' personal
problems with 16-year-old Shannon Bullard, the daughter of Pierce's
girlfriend, Ruth Locklear. The sheriff said Goins may have felt
Pierce helped Ms. Locklear get trespass warrants against him.
   Although he hasn't entered a formal plea, Chavis has told a
family friend he was not involved in the slaying, the News and
Observer of Raleigh said. The newspaper said Chavis told Ruth
Godwin that Goins asked him Saturday to go for a ride.
   The two stopped near Pierce's home, but Chavis said he thought
Goins was getting out of the car to go to the bathroom, the
newspaper reported.
   ``I heard three shots,'' Chavis said, according to Mrs. Godwin.
``I was stunned.''
   Stone declined comment on whether Chavis knew Goins' intentions.
   Goins left flowers, a teddy bear and some cards on the doorstep
of his former girlfriend's home before he killed himself, officials
said.
   Chavis' father, Ronald, helped bring the suit that prompted the
General Assembly to create a separate Superior Court district for
Robeson County.
   The law was intended to help a non-white candidate get elected
in a county where blacks and Indians make up 58 percent of the
registered voters.
   Under state law, Britt, who is white, will become judge because
he is now unopposed. Gov. Jim Martin said he would meet Thursday
with Indian leaders calling for a special Legislative session to
allow an opponent in the May 3 vote.
   The sheriff expressed regret at his comment Tuesday that the
slaying was ``just another murder.'' ``One person's life is just as
important as another's,'' Stone said.
   In Lumberton, a bomb threat emptied the Robeson County
courthouse on Wednesday, but employees were allowed to return in
less than two hours. No bomb was found and officials said they did
not know if the threat was connected to the Pierce case.
</TEXT>
