<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-Schools 1stLd-Writethru a0702 03-30 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Schools, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Considers Challenge to School Busing Fees</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Fixes spelling of Kdrmas thruout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case of particular
importance to rural areas, was urged Wednesday to compel states to
provide free bus transportation for poor school children.
   Duane Houdek, representing a family challenging busing fees in
North Dakota, said the state unlawfully discriminates against some
people who have trouble affording the busing charges.
   The Bismarck, N.D., lawyer was asked by Justice Byron R. White
whether North Dakota is constitutionally required to provide
transportation for poor people.
   ``That's a fair characterization'' of his argument, Houdek
replied.
   But some justices indicated their decision, expected to be
announced by July, could be based on narrower grounds. They said
the question may be whether North Dakota discriminates improperly
because it treats some school districts differently than others.
   North Dakota law provides free bus transportation to those
living in districts that have reorganized to broaden their tax base
and improve education. Only those districts that have not
reorganized are allowed to charge parents for busing costs.
   The law was intended to spur reorganization while assuring
people in those districts they would not have to pay for
transportation.
   Attorney General Nicholas Spaeth of North Dakota defended the
system as ``permissible geographic discrimination'' that does not
unfairly harm the poor.
   ``It's one way economic benefits are dispensed,'' he said. He
argued that the law does not deprive anyone of a public school
education.
   The law was challenged by Paula Kdrmas from rural Dickinson,
N.D. She said the statute denied equal educational rights to her
daughter, Sarita, because the family could not afford a $97 annual
bus fee.
   Ms. Kdrmas has driven Sarita the 16 miles to school rather than
pay the fee.
   George T. Dynes, a lawyer representing the local school
district, said it would have been cheaper for the Kdrmas family to
pay the bus fee _ which he said would be about 1.7 cents per mile.
   Bus service in Dickinson is offered for a fee to elementary
school students who live more than three miles from school and to
high school students who live more than four miles away.
   The North Dakota Supreme Court upheld the law, saying local
school officials rationally may decide their limited resources are
needed for services other than transportation.
   ``A statutory scheme under which a school district offers to
provide student transportation at considerably less expense to the
parent than self-transportation would entail does not constitute a
deprivation which offends either federal or state equal protection
rights,'' the state court said.
   The case is Kdrmas vs. Dickinson Public Schools, 86-7113.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
