<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chess-WorldCup     03-30 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess-World Cup,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chess World Cup Opens Two-Year Competition In Brussels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first stage of the $600,000 World
Cup Grand Prix chess competition opens in Brussels on Friday,
beginning a new and lucrative battle among the world's top chess
players.
   The top-ranked 25 players internationally will each compete in
four of the six World Cup tournaments during 1988-89. The overall
champion will get $100,000, in addition to winnings from the
individual tournaments.
   The card for the opening $104,000 tournament in Brussels is
headed by Soviet Anatoly Karpov, the former world champion;
Dutchman Jan Timman and Swiss veteran Viktor Korchnoi.
   World Champion Garri Kasparov, a favorite to win the overall
competition, will sit out the first tournament.
   The World Cup is organized by the Grandmasters Association,
established recently by some of the world's best players to counter
the influence of the World Chess Federation.
   After the World Championship, the World Cup Grand Prix provides
the biggest prizes for the international grandmasters.
   The World Cup is aimed at increasing the popularity of chess and
making it more accessible to the media, while providing more money
for top players. Organizers it will provide continuous competition,
unlike the World Championship, held every few years.
   The World Chess Federation said in a statement that the World
Cup competition was ``a great step in the promotion of chess.''
   Each of the six tournaments will involve either 16 or 18 of the
selected players. The three best tournament finishes of each player
will count for the final standings.
   Other stages of the competition will be held in Belfort, France;
Reykjavik, Iceland; Barcelona, Spain; Rotterdam, the Netherlands;
and Skelleftea, Sweden.
   The three-week Brussels tournament is dominated by six Soviets
while players from Hungary, the United States, Switzerland,
Yugoslavia, Cuba, Britain, Sweden, and the Netherlands are also
scheduled to take part.
   The World Cup players were selected on the basis of their
international ranking.
   The next World Championship tournament is scheduled in 1990,
while the next two-year World Cup is set for 1990-1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 2145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     03-30 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Save Essence of My Trade Plan, Gephardt Urges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Richard A. Gephardt, out of the
presidential race but still campaigning on the trade front, called
on lawmakers Wednesday to save the heart of his plan to fight
foreign barriers with import curbs.
   ``I think that we can come up with something that will be
positive,'' the Missouri congressman told a House-Senate conference
committee that is drafting a compromise version of rival 1,000-page
trade bills approved by both houses last year.
   Gephardt told reporters earlier that he would push for the
conference committee to adopt his plan as it was approved by the
House. The Senate takes a differing approach to unfair foreign
trade barriers.
   But Gephardt seemed to acknowledge that his plan was bound to be
modified by the conference committee in the long run, something
that lawmakers have been conceding for weeks.
   He said any final version should focus on key countries
employing unfair trade practices as part of a systematic trade
strategy. Wholesale negotiations should be shunned in favor of
working on major trade trouble spots, Gephardt said.
   Mandatory retaliation is needed when negotiations fail, he
noted, saying ``You have to have a stick in the closet.'' But he
added that flexibility is necessary in dealing with trading
partners and thus the president should have the power to waive
retaliation when necessary.
   The conference committee stopped short Wednesday of action on
any of the major issues remaining before it puts the finishing
touches on a compromise.
   ``I'm not going to kill myself to have that guy downtown say
he's going to veto everything,'' said Rep. Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., chairman of a House-Senate conference committee on trade
legislation.
   It was the latest Democratic comment on a drumroll of warnings
from the Reagan administration that the bill could be inviting a
veto. The vice chairman, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said Tuesday
that he was tired of hearing veto threats.
   Rostenkowski said he still hoped to wrap up work by the close of
business on Thursday, when lawmakers leave on their spring break.
But it remained unclear that he could meet that deadline.
   ``We're what you call clearing away brush,'' said Rep. William
Frenzel, R-Minn. ``We're to the small sapplings now and we haven't
gotten to the part of the forest where the big redwoods are.''
   Besides the Gephardt amendment, lawmakers have not resolved what
the bill should do to overhaul existing law under which U.S.
industries endangered by surges in foreign competition can obtain
import restrictions from the government.
   Whether to ban Toshiba products because of that company's sale
of submarine silencing equipment to the Soviets remains undecided,
as do provisions involving Third World debt and requiring foreign
owners of U.S. property to disclose their identities and the extent
of their holdings.
   Bentsen is campaigning to hang onto a Senate provision to repeal
the windfall profits tax on oil companies, a move that is opposed
by Rostenkowski.
   New protests that the bill already has been diluted came from
lawmakers representing industrial areas where Japanese imports have
cut into jobs.
   ``I doubt that I can vote for it,'' Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., told
the conference committee. ``Because I don't want to be a part of
some great trade bill that has no teeth and doesn't do anything at
all for the industry of this country.''
   ``The House has given up an awful lot and the administration has
gotten a lot of what it wants and the Senate has also,'' Rep. Don
Pease, D-Ohio, said. ``The final product ought to be a legislative
product and not just a product of the administration and ratified
by us.''
   Rostenkowski and Bentsen repeated their goal of producing
legislation that President Reagan would be willing to sign.
   ``Or one that would embarrass him if he vetoes it,''
Rostenkowski said.
   In a speech in Richmond, Va. on Monday, Reagan threatened to
veto the legislation if it contained mandatory import curbs, forced
disclosure of foreign ownership or a measure requiring employers to
give notice of plant closings or large-scale layoffs.
   The plant-closings provision was adopted by a House-Senate panel
Tuesday night. Rostenkowski was asked Wednesday if he regarded it
as a permanent feature of the legislation.
   ``I see it as a big problem for getting the president's
signature,'' he replied.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 2018EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ContraAid 4thLd-Writethru a0802 03-30 1073</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Aid, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0802,1,040</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves $48 Million Contra Aid Package</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 11th graf bgng: Senate Majority ... to
UPDATE with Contra reax. Picks up 12th graf pvs bgng: The
legislation ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House overwhelmingly approved on Wednesday
a $48 million package of humanitarian aid for the Contra rebels in
Nicaragua and for children injured in nearly seven years of civil
war.
   The aid bill, passed on a 345-70 vote, was portrayed as a
gesture of U.S. support for a temporary truce reached last week
between the rebels and the Sandinista government, and for
continuing talks aimed at achieving a long-term end to hostilities.
   ``The hope is that this will lead to political instead of
military processes now taking over'' in Nicaragua, said House
Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash.
   ``This war is over, whether some like it or not,'' said Rep.
Leon Panetta, D-Calif.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said after the House
vote, ``We are pleased and look forward to the vote tomorrow in the
Senate.''
   Despite producing the first strong bipartisan vote on U.S.
policy toward Nicaragua in more than five years, lawmakers showed
more weariness than joy as they plodded through two hours of debate.
   ``It is not the magic key to facilitate a cease-fire in place or
fruitful negotiations and all the rest,'' said Minority Leader
Robert Michel, R-Ill., who said it has become clear Congress is no
longer inclined to grant the military aid he would prefer. ``But
for the moment it's the only thing we have to give.''
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, noting the years of previous
acrimony on the issue, called the broad support for the bill ``very
impressive'' and said it should ``provide encouragement to both
sides in Central America.''
   Some Democrats called the vote another victory for Wright on the
Central American issue, which he has dominated on the U.S. side
since a five-nation peace accord was signed in Guatemala last Aug.
7.
   ``The speaker has invested tremendous risk, and has been almost
totally successful in saying, `I'm going to stick my neck out for
peace down there,''' said Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Wash.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., promised speedy
consideration on the other side of the Capitol, and it appeared
likely that the matter could come to a vote on Thursday.
   Officials of the Nicaraguan Resistance, a Miami-based umbrella
group of the Contra rebels, said they were elated with the package.
   ``This is what we have been waiting for, for a long time _ a
broad bipartisan aid package for the resistance,'' said Alfredo
Cesar, a director of the resistance. He said it sends ``a strong
political message to Central America in general and to the world
that the United States is not abandoning the resistance fighters in
the mountains.''
   The legislation would renew aid to the rebels, whose last U.S.
support ran out Feb. 29, and keep them together as a fighting force
while they wait in cease-fire zones inside Nicaragua for a
long-term truce to be worked out with the Sandinista government.
   ``It sends a message to the Contras that they are not abandoned,
that we do care about them and want to keep them healthy and a
viable force,'' said Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., who participated
in negotiations to draft the compromise.
   ``And it lets the Sandinistas know that it's important to the
United States Congress that the talks that take place down there
take place with good faith, and that they move toward
democratization,'' Edwards added.
   The agreement, made possible by a 60-day cease-fire reached by
the two warring sides last week, broke a weeks-long deadlock in
Congress over whether to keep up the flow of U.S. aid. The House
had killed efforts to provide new supplies to the rebels on two
earlier occasions this year.
   In agreeing to the deal, Republicans accepted Wright's
assurances that he would give any future request from President
Reagan for military aid for the rebels ``fair and orderly''
consideration.
   The White House apparently dropped its past insistence on an
ironclad legal guarantee of an expedited vote, settling instead for
the pledge contained in a letter from Wright to the president and
to Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill.
   Wright's pledge says Reagan can ask Congress for additional
rebel aid if Nicaragua's leftist government violates the March 23
cease-fire or any later peace accord and if the Contras continue to
observe its terms. Wright would send Reagan's request to the
appropriate House committee, which would have 10 days to act and
return the measure to the full House for action.
   Wright said other than the 10-day limit on committee
consideration, the letter simply laid out the normal procedures of
the House and in that sense represented a relatively small
concession.
   The letter suggests, but does not require, that Reagan first get
advice on whether new military aid is warranted from a verification
commission established by the March 23 agreement to oversee the
cease-fire.
   The commission includes Nicaraguan Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo, a government critic who is seen as partial to the rebels,
and Joao Baena Soares, secretary general of the Organization of
American States, who is aligned more with the leftist government.
   Under the bill, $16.2 million in ``humanitarian'' aid _ defined
as food, clothing, medical supplies and family support payments _
would be sent to the Contras at a rate of $2.7 million a month for
the next six months. It would be delivered by a neutral
organization instead of the CIA, which has delivered past aid when
hostilities were under way.
   Of that amount, $2.2 million is earmarked for a Miskito Indian
Contra group which already had reached its own peace accord with
the Sandinistas.
   The rebels would get another $1.5 million to buy communications
gear, deemed essential to keeping Contra troops in touch with their
commanders during the cease-fire period. That pushes the total
rebel aid to $17.7 million.
   An identical amount would go to create a new program of medical
and humanitarian help for children who have been injured or
suffered as a result of the civil war, which has claimed some
40,000 lives since 1981.
   In addition, the legislation provides $10 million to pay
expenses of the verification commission and $2.5 million to pay
administrative overhead for the State Department's Agency for
International Development, which would handle distribution of the
money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
