<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CollegeDeseg     03-30 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-College Deseg,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Denies Alabama Universities Segregated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public universities in Alabama are not
racially biased, despite the accusations of a U.S. Justice
Department lawsuit, a lawyer for the major state university said
Wednesday.
   ``We feel the same as we always have _ that we're not guilty of
segregating our schools,'' said Robert L. Potts, an attorney for
the University of Alabama System. ``When we get to the merits of
the case in court, I think we'll prove that.''
   The federal government suit was filed Tuesday in U.S. District
Court. It was first filed in 1983, but had to be refiled after an
appeals court ruled that the judge who heard the first case should
have disqualified himself because he had participated in landmark
civil rights cases as a private attorney.
   ``I would not agree that the case is starting from ground zero
again,'' said Nathaniel Douglas of the Justice Department's Civil
Rights Division in Washington, D.C.
   ``There have been efforts to resolve the case by negotiation,
and we are ready to continue to do that.''
   The refiled suit charges again that state education officials
have ``perpetuated a racial dual system in public higher
education.''
   The Justice Department said two predominantly black schools,
Alabama A&M in Huntsville and Alabama State in Montgomery, are
close to mainly white schools and were intended for black students
only, while whites attended the other institutions.
   Justice Department lawyers said evidence exists of intentions by
state authorities to maintain vestiges of a dual school system.
   Federal attorneys cited a 1975 planning document of the Alabama
Commission on Higher Education, one of the defendants, that said
``with Alabama State and Alabama A&M to meet the needs of the
state's Negro citizens and with the University of Alabama and
Auburn University as major state institutions, the state seemed
relatively well served.''
   The suit also names as defendants the state, Gov. Guy Hunt, and
several universities in the system. Spokesmen for both the governor
and for Auburn University said they had no comment for the present.
   The suit said the state continues to allocate far more money to
the major white schools than to the mainly black ones.
   State authorities contend the predominantly white and black
schools in Huntsville and Montgomery are the result of decades-old
patterns of preference by students.
   In 1985, U.S. District Judge U.W. Clemon ruled after a five-week
trial that Alabama maintains vestiges of a dual school system.
Before he could begin the remedy phase of the case, his ruling was
appealed.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta ruled last
year that Clemon, Alabama's first black federal judge, should have
stepped down because of the rights cases he handled when he was a
private attorney.
</TEXT>
