<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Contras     03-30 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Military Leader Declares Support for Truce</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief Contra military field commander, who has
expressed reservations about the rebel truce with the Nicaraguan
Sandinistas, said Wednesday he supports the truce agreement and
will comply with it.
   Col. Enrique Bermudez, who has said he doesn't trust the
Sandinistas, told reporters his concerns about the truce do not
mean he opposes Contra leadership on the touchy issue.
   ``We understand there can be differences, but during
negotiations we have to have a single position,'' he said at a news
conference.
   As an indicator of that continuing mistrust, the Contras said
Wednesday they have filed a formal complaint with the Nicaraguan
government about the way the Sandinistas handled the weekend
release of 100 political prisoners, a release called for in the
truce agreement.
   Contra spokeswoman Marta Sacasa said the rebels gave the
Sandinistas a list Saturday of the 100 Contras they wanted
released, but only nine or 10 of those prisoners released were on
the rebel list.
   She said the Sandinistas had made a ``verbal agreement'' to use
the Contra suggestions but their response ``does not show enough
good faith or trust.''
   Bermudez's comments Wednesday came at the same time that Contra
directors are taking to the Miami airwaves to calm opposition and
fear in the Nicaraguan community that the Contra leadership gave up
too much.
   Fourteen Nicaraguan exile leaders held a news conference in
Miami on Monday to call for the Contra leadership's resignation.
   ``Sometimes it's very easy, sitting here in Miami, to say, `My
God, look what's been agreed to in Sapoa,' without remembering that
the fighting men, who are dying in the mountains of Nicaragua, have
been abandoned'' by Congress, said director Alfredo Cesar, one of
the leaders who helped negotiate the cease-fire. Sapoa is the
Nicaraguan border town where the truce talks were held last week.
   Congress has voted against continued military aid for the
Contras, though the House on Wednesday approved a package of
humanitarian aid.
   Speaking on radio station WAQI-AM, Cesar denied the truce was
tantamount to surrender.
   But he said an armed guerrilla movement has been allowed to stay
in place, while its leaders travel to the capital to discuss the
nation's future.
   ``There is no precedent for this _ not even in Guatemala, a
democratic country, which requires that the communist guerrillas
put down their arms before discussing the country's future,'' Cesar
said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
