<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-MiddleEast 1stLd-Writethru a0791 03-30 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Middle East, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0791,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO, Arab Speakers at U.N. Demand Independent Palestinian State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with U.S., PLO,
Israeli speakers. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab leaders and the PLO bitterly
condemned Israel's crackdown in the occupied territories and called
Wednesday for an international peace conference to create an
independent Palestinian state.
   In an emergency Security Council meeting, Israel rejected a
conference and asked instead for direct negotiations with its
neighbors.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun accused the Arabs of ``extreme
rhetoric'' and said Secretary of State George P. Shultz will seek a
forum in his forthcoming Middle East mission that would permit
direct negotiations leading to a comprehensive settlement.
   The 15-member council heard 10 speakers denounce Israel's
occupation of lands captured from the Arabs and call for a
U.N-sponsored peace conference involving all parties to the
conflict, including Israel, the PLO and the five permanent members
of the council.
   They denounced Israel's sealing off the West Bank and Gaza, its
imposition of a curfew and banning of journalists. Saudi Arabian
and Libyan envoys compared Israel's treatment of Palestinians to
Nazi persecution of Jews.
   The council adjourned without a resolution or a vote but agreed
to meet again to consider the situation in the occupied
territories. Since the Palestinian protests began in December, the
council has condemned Israeli practices as violating Palestinian
human rights.
   Farouk Khaddoumi, the top envoy of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, told the council, ``Peace can only be established
through an end to Israeli occupation and security can only reign if
an independent Palestinian state is established.''
   Khaddoumi is director of the PLO Political Department, its
equivalent to foreign minister. He accused the United States of
supporting repression in the occupied territories and said
Washington encouraged Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel, whom
he called ``a terrorist.''
   The United States, he said, is using its veto power to prevent
the Security Council from adopting measures that would prevent
Israeli ``crimes'' against Palestinians.
   He said the Palestinian people would never accept Israel's
proposal of autonomy as a substitute for sovereignty.
   The United Nations recognizes the PLO as the only legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people.
   Israel considers the PLO a terrorist organization.
   Israeli Ambassador Johanan Bein, the deputy permanent
representative, condemned recent PLO broadcasts which he said
exhorted Palestinians to throw rocks and attack Israeli security
forces with knives.
   ``The PLO solution is dissolution of Israel,'' Bein said. ``This
will not be the case. The PLO has shown it will continue to fight
to the last Palestinian child, but this will never constitute a
basis for peace, but only for violence.''
   He said Israel regrets the loss of life of Arab or Jew, ``But
when confronted by unbridled mob violence, with stones, iron bars,
fire bombs and even live ammunition, it has no alternative but to
attempt to quell the violence and restore order.''
   Foreign Minister Ahmed Taleb Ibrahimi of Algeria told the
council ``it is high time for resolute action'' by the world
community and asked for a U.N.-sponsored Middle East peace
conference to set up a Palestinian state.
   ``There will only be peace,'' Ibrahimi said, ``if there is total
and unconditional evacuation of Israel from all Arab territories.''
   Ibrahimi is the leader of a high-level Arab delegation visiting
New York.
   More than 120 Palestinians and one Israeli soldiers have been
killed since riots began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza, which
Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Speakers on the Wednesday agenda included Ibrahim Massoud,
minister of state for foreign affairs of Saudi Arabia; Foreign
Minister Farouk Al-Shara of Syria, and Chedli Klibi, the Arab
League secretary-general.
   Diplomats said earlier that a resolution and vote were unlikely,
because resolutions critical of Israel often are vetoed by the
United States.
</TEXT>
