<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     03-30 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two White Police Convicted of Murdering Two Blacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two white police officers were
convicted of murder Wednesday in the killings of two black men said
to be drug dealers.
   The Rand Supreme Court convicted both Sgt. Robert van der Merwe,
30, and Capt. Jack La Grange, 40, on two counts of murder and one
count of intent to murder after a three-week trial.
   Van der Merwe testified he shot the men because La Grange duped
him into believing they were linked to the African National
Congress guerrilla movement.
   ``I believed that what I was doing was in the national interest
and it would never have occurred to me to question an order from an
officer,'' he said.
   The blacks, who were alleged drug dealers, were killed in
separate attacks last September and October.
   Van der Merwe testified he knew of ``clandestine operations'' in
which security police carried out missions to kill suspected ANC
operatives.
   ``I realize that such actions are illegal in terms of the law,
but I deem them lawful in terms of head office orders,'' he said.
   Both van der Merwe and La Grange had pleaded innocent. They
could face the death penalty, although there was no immediate word
on sentencing.
   The ANC is the main guerrilla group fighting apartheid, the
system of racial segregation in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs and the 5 million whites control the
economy and maintain separate districts and services.
   In other developments Wednesday:
   _Police arrested 106 men and women demonstrating Tuesday against
a labor bill which would restrict union rights, according to Frank
Meintjies, spokesman for the Congress of South African Trade
Unions, the nation's largest labor federation.
   Police said in their daily unrest report for the preceding 24
hours that they arrested 124 people in industrial areas for
gathering illegally and refusing to disperse. They gave no details,
except to say they used batons and dogs to disperse one group.
   _Authorities also reported that an unknown gunman wounded a
28-year-old municipal policeman in the chest in Soweto, the black
township outside Johannesburg.
   _Police said they used batons to disperse people gathered
outside a court building in the mixed-race township of Wynberg in
Cape Town, but reported no injuries or arrests. No reason for the
gathering was given.
   The Star newspaper reported that the police charged a crowd of
friends and relatives of 11 people on trial on treason charges in
Wynberg courthouse. Magistrate A.S. McCarthy ordered the courtroom
cleared after defendants and court spectators joined in singing a
Zulu anthem, ``God Bless Africa.''
   _In Pretoria, police cordoned off streets around the Union
Buildings, where the government has its offices, and declared it an
emergency area when 70 students from eight universities gathered to
present petitions to President P.W. Botha's office.
   The petitions protested last month's banning of 17
anti-apartheid organizations and recent government restrictions on
protest activity on campuses.
   _In Grahamstown, in eastern Cape province, four black residents
of Uitenahage township were sentenced to death Wednesday for the
murder of a youth activist they allegedly believed had become a
police informer. The sentences brought to 50 the number of people
on death row for offenses connected with the three years of
nationwide unrest from 1984-1987.
</TEXT>
