<2ND_LINE>AM-Well Rescue-Benefit,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jessica McClure Helps Raise Money for Ill Boy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN7</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica McClure, whose rescue from a
Midland well attracted international attention, arrived Wednesday
to help raise funds for a boy with serious lung problems.
   Jessica, who turned 2 last Saturday, will participate in a
balloon release Thursday to benefit 5-year-old Brennan Bolin, said
benefit coordinator Bonnie Arnold.
   The families of the children are acquainted and that is how
Jessica got involved, according to Mrs. Arnold.
   Jessica and her mother, Cissy McClure, were flown to Lancaster
Municipal Airport on a private plane for a noon reception, said
Mrs. Arnold.
   Brennan has idiopathic pulmonary hemosiderosis, a rare condition
in which bleeding occurs within the lungs' lining.
   Mrs. Arnold, wife of Lancaster Mayor Walter D. Arnold III, said
the boy needs a heart-lung transplant at the University of
Minnesota.
   ``They're hoping that unless anything goes wrong, he will be
weaned from steroids for six weeks, as of June 1, and he will be
relocating to Minnesota to await a donor,'' she said.
   The surgery will cost $650,000 and all but $125,000 is covered
by insurance, she said.
   Lancaster residents had already donated $15,000 even before
Thursday's official start of the fund-raising campaign.
   Jessica will release the first balloon, followed by children
from Lancaster elementary schools, said Mrs. Arnold.
   ``These children will have each donated one dollar to Brennan's
cause. Their name and a special message will be in each balloon,''
said Mrs. Arnold. ``There will be a drawing among those children
for two toys signed by Jessica.''
   Mrs. Arnold says the boy's grandmother, Sue Ellen Nall, lives in
Midland, where Jessica fell into an abandoned water well last
October. It took 58 hours for rescuers to get the toddler out in a
dramatic, nationally televised climax to her ordeal.
   A task force to help the Lancaster boy was organized by First
United Methodist Church.
