<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Bombs     03-30 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Bombs,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes In Cordoba; Bomb Threats in Buenos Aires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb damaged a textile plant in
Cordoba early Wednesday and more than 20 telephoned bomb threats
were received in Buenos Aires, police reported.
   Bombs exploded in three Buenos Aires movie theaters Tuesday,
wounding four people, including a national policeman who lost a
hand and an eye.
   President Raul Alfonsin blamed ``terrorists'' trying to ``put an
end to democracy'' for the explosions.
   In addition to the blast at the Pompas Brothers plant in
Cordoba, an industrial city in central Argentina, and the three
theater explosions in the capital, 16 bombings have been carried
out or attempted since January. Most were in Buenos Aires.
   Telephoned threats were reported throughout the day Wednesday
but no bombs were found, officials said. Banks, hospitals,
municipal buildings and shopping arcades were evacuated because of
the calls.
   A group has left leaflets at most bombing sites carrying the
initials ``O.A.S.-M.R.P.'' The meaning of the initials is not known.
   Officials say the group is thought to be linked to former Lt.
Col. Aldo Rico, 44, who led two unsuccessful rebellions in army
units during the past year.
   Rico, however, issued a communique Wednesday night denying any
connection with the bombings.
   The uprisings he led were the most serious threats to Alfonsin
since his civilian government took office in December 1983, ending
nearly eight years of military rule.
   Rico's communique said the bombings were ``contrary to the
essence of `Operation Dignity,''' his effort to win pardons for
officers accused of human rights violations during the government's
1976-83 campaign against suspected leftist subversives.
   At least 9,000 people were abducted and vanished without a trace
during what became known as the ``dirty war'' under military rule
in Argentina, officials say.
   The former colonel is being held at the Magdalena military
prison 60 miles south of Buenos Aires.
</TEXT>
