<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brawley-Classmate     03-30 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley-Classmate,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Classmate of Tawana Brawley Had Also Claimed Kidnap and Assault</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen months before Tawana Brawley's alleged
abduction, a schoolmate told police a markedly similar story of
being kidnapped and sexually assaulted, according to broadcast and
published reports.
   In a story published Wednesday, sources told the Daily News that
the unidentified teen-ager reported to police in 1986 that she had
been abducted by men in a green car and taken to a wooded area and
attacked.
   The charges were investigated by the Poughkeepsie police, who
determined that they were unfounded and apparently fabricated to
cover up sexual abuse by a male relative, the News said.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, an adviser to the Brawley family, angrily
denounced the News story, and he and one of the Brawleys'
attorneys, Alton Maddox, asserted that it had been leaked by state
Attorney General Robert Abrams, the special prosecutor in the case.
   ``It's ridiculous to take a story that no one has established
that Tawana had any knowledge of and imply that she was trying to
use it,'' Sharpton said.
   A spokesman for Abrams, Timothy Gilles, declined to comment on
the reports, but denied that Abrams' office had been the source of
the story.
   The case has received wide attention, in part because the family
has refused to cooperate with officials, accusing them of racial
bias in their handling of the investigation.
   Poughkeepsie radio station WKIP said a woman saying she was the
mother of a girl with a similar story called the station's nightly
talk show last week. The station rebroadcast parts of that
interview Wednesday.
   The caller, who declined to give her name, said during the
broadcast that Miss Brawley and her daughter had talked at a
shopping mall the night before Miss Brawley's disappearance last
November.
   The girl eventually recanted her story, the woman said.
   Miss Brawley, who was reported missing for several days in
November, has told her family she was abducted in a green or blue
car, taken to a wooded area and sexually abused by six white men.
One of the men flashed a police-like badge, she said.
   Four days later she was found near her family's former apartment
in Wappingers Falls, dazed, covered with animal excrement and with
racial epithets written on her body. Miss Brawley is black.
</TEXT>
