<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Libya     03-30 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Libya,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Libyan Attempt to Improve Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state-owned magazine says a ranking Libyan
visited Egypt in an attempt to mend relations between the North
African neighbors, which have been at odds for years and fought a
brief border war in 1977.
   In the edition appearing Thursday, the weekly Al-Mussawar said
Col. Abdel-Fattah Younis Farag came to Cairo after Egypt allowed
the return of four Libyan warplanes whose pilots landed on the
wrong side of the border March 1 because of bad weather and lack of
fuel.
   On Monday, Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi said he was withdrawing
his forces from the border and asked nothing in return. He said
Libya would not use force to get President Hosni Mubarak's
government to renounce the peace treaty Egypt signed with Israel in
1979.
   Mubarak reacted to that gesture Wednesday by warning Gadhafi not
to conceal terrorist plans behind expressions of good will.
   Al-Mussawar said Farag, commander of the border military zone,
came to thank Mubarak for returning the Soviet-built MiG-23s. The
magazine did not say if he met Mubarak, but said the colonel was
expected back in Cairo soon to ``continue talks with the Egyptian
leadership.''
   It said Farag was close to Gadhafi and visited Egypt several
times before, trying with little success to ``open a dialogue.''
   In his comments Wednesday, Mubarak questioned the motive for
Gadhafi's statement that he was opening the border.
   ``Might it be to smuggle in bombs?'' the president said at a
political meeting in Giza province. ``I strongly warn him. I know
all his tricks.''
   His comments, carried by the Middle East News Agency, apparently
referred to charges that Gadhafi arranged bombings in Cairo and
other cities in 1975-76.
   Egypt also has said it suspected Libya of laying mines in the
Gulf of Suez and Red Sea that damaged 20 ships in the summer of
1984.
   Mubarak said Gadhafi's statements ``have no impact on
relations.''
   Gadhafi recently freed and repatriated 36 Egyptian prisoners,
among them three soldiers whose return Mubarak had requested
publicly. Egypt sent home five members of the Libyan air force who
flew to Egypt last year in three separate incidents but who did not
request asylum.
   Libyan-Egyptian relations soured in 1972 when Egypt rejected
Gadhafi's proposal that the two countries merge. They got worse
when the late President Anwar Sadat made the American-mediated Camp
David agreements with Israel in 1978 that led to the peace treaty.
</TEXT>
