<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0692 03-30 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Kuwait</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iranian Gunboats Hit Cypriot Supertanker, Set It On Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, with Thursday dawn
attack by Iran reported against supertanker. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian gunboats struck at the Cypriot
supertanker Haven near the entrance to the Persian Gulf at dawn
Thursday and set it on fire, shipping executives reported.
   The executives said the raid near the Strait of Hormuz was
apparently in retaliation for an Iraqi attack Wednesday on a
different Cypriot supertanker under charter to Iran.
   They said the 109,700-ton Haven came under attack by the the
Iranians at dawn off the emirate of Ras al-Khaimah.
   Salvage tugboats rushed to aid the stricken tanker, but it was
not known immediately if the crew suffered casualties or what the
extent of damage was. The gulf-based executives, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, did not know the Haven's destination.
   Iran attacks neutral commercial vessels in the southern gulf
near the Strait of Hormuz on a ship-for-ship basis in the so-called
``tanker war,'' in which about 500 vessels have been hit by both
sides in the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war, with about 300 seamen
killed.
   In other developments in the Iran-Iraq war, Iranian rebels
operating from Iraq claimed to have killed 2,000 Iranian
Revolutionary Guards in a two-day battle in the oil-rich Khuzestan
region of southern Iran. A statement from the National Liberation
Army of Iran said its force of 15 brigades had returned to Iraq.
   Iraq said it fired three long-range missiles into Isfahan, a
city in central Iran, and its planes bombed Iranian towns. Tehran
radio said the missiles killed five people in Isfahan, wounded
several and destroyed houses and a mosque.
   Dispatches from Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency
said Iranian planes dropped 10 tons of bombs on Sulaymaniyah,
provincial capital of northern Iraq, and hit border towns with 14
short-range missiles. Iraq said civilians, including three
children, were killed in missile and shelling attacks.
   Also, the Kuwaiti government and shipping agents said three
Iranian speedboats fired from several hundred yards away Wednesday
at Bubiyan, a Kuwaiti island off Iraq, wounding two soldiers. Iran
denied it.
   Iraqi warplanes Wednesday raided the 259,447-ton Cypriot
supertanker Anax chartered by Iran and set it on fire 70 miles
south of Kharg, the executives reported earlier. It was the seventh
strike reported in 11 days on a tanker owned or leased by Iran.
   Iranian retaliatory strikes are mainly carried out by
speedboats, darting from the southern gulf island of Abu Musa. The
Iraqis usually attack by warplanes using radar-guided missiles in
the northern gulf near Iran's big Kharg Island oil terminal.
   The Anax, also hit Dec. 2, is part of a fleet that shuttles
Iranian oil from Kharg to makeshift terminals in safer waters 450
miles down the waterway.
   No injuries were reported on the Anax. A fire in the engine room
was said to be under control, but Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence
Unit in London described the ship as ``dead in the water.''
   In reporting the tanker raid Wednesday, Iraq said its jets
scored an ``accurate and effective hit'' on a ``large maritime
target.''
   Shipping agents, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Iranian speedboats sped away from Kuwait's Bubiyan island after
Wednesday's attack, which appeared to be for propaganda purposes
rather than to cause damage. The reports did not say what weapons
were fired, but Iranian speedboats normally carry machine guns and
grenade launchers.
   Bubiyan is about 20 miles from Iraq's Faw peninsula, part of
which Iran seized early in 1986.
   Iran considers Kuwait an ally of Iraq in the war that began in
September 1980.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
