<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Falklands-Britain     03-30 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Falklands-Britain,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Begin Returning Home from Exercise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN LEONARD</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANLEY, Falkland Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British soldiers began
returning home Wednesday from the first major military exercise
held by Britain in the Falkland Islands since it freed them from
Argentine occupation in 1982.
   Argentina and other Latin American nations had fiercely
denounced the reinforcement exercise, calling it aggressive.
Britain denied the allegation.
   ``The whole exercise has been worthwhile,'' Maj. Gen. Neil
Carlier, commander of British forces on the remote South Atlantic
islands, said Wednesday.
   ``We have proven that we can reinforce with speed, and maintain
the integrity of the airfield.''
   The deployment of nearly 1,000 troops in an exercise codenamed
Fire Focus began March 7 and military officials said it ended with
no injuries and no accidents.
   The maneuvers involved bringing troops, planes and equipment
8,000 miles from Britain.
   On the island, 2,000 permanently stationed soldiers also took
part in the exercise.
   Britain freed the colony after a 74-day conflict which left 712
Argentines, 255 Britons and three Falkland Islands civilians dead.
   Argentina, which is 325 miles west of the islands, claims the
Falklands are an inheritance from the days of Spanish colonial rule
and were stolen by Britain, which has ruled them as a colony since
1833.
</TEXT>
