<HEAD>Famous Stores Owner Plays Clerk for a Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Harrods department store, where
bluebloods browse, played hired helper for a day Wednesday, slicing
meat at the butcher's counter.
   Other executives joined Mohamed al-Fayed in serving customers,
because the boss believes ``everyone has to feel that the customer
comes first, always first.''
   The Egyptian entrepreneur and his two brothers bought the huge
store in fasionable Knightsbridge three years ago.
   ``People have to feel that you are just like them, not the man
who owns the place,'' said al-Fayed, who wore a straw hat with his
cleaver Wednesday.
   Executives ``should not just sit there like gods, they should
experience the contact with the customer,'' he said.
   He is a ``practical man,'' Al-Fayed said, and enjoyed working at
the meat counter. He helped out for a time in fruit department too,
accompanied by a bodyguard.
   Harrods was founded by Charles Harrod in 1849. Al-Fayed began a
$320 million restoration in 1987 that will take 3{ years. He and
his brothers bought Harrods and the parent House of Fraser PLC for
$984 million in March 1985.
