<HEAD>Rebels Raid Farm Co-ops, Kill Managers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marxist rebels raided two farm
cooperatives operated by peasants, killing a manager at each
operation and destroying agriculture equipment, police said
Wednesday.
   About 30 guerrillas of the leftist Shining Path movement
attacked a sugar cane and fruit farm Tuesday in the Andes
foothills, about 70 miles north of Lima, police said. On Monday,
rebels raided a grain and cattle operation near Huancayo, about 130
miles east of Lima.
   The rebels accused the manager of each farm of supporting the
government and shot and killed them, police said. The rebels blew
up trucks and tractors before withdrawing, police said.
   The cooperatives are among dozens organized by the government
and operated by peasants. Rebels have repeatedly attacked such
farms in an effort to derail government efforts to improve Peru's
agricultural system.
   The Mao-inspired Shining Path, which seeks to install a Marxist
regime, launched its insurgency in the impoverished rural highlands
nearly eight years ago. The government says more than 10,000
people, mainly mountain peasants, have been killed in the violence.
