<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Amnesty     03-30 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Amnesty,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rights Group Probes IRA Slayings By British Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International said Wednesday that British
soldiers who killed three unarmed IRA members on Gibraltar may have
deliberately avoided capturing them, killing one guerrilla who lay
wounded on the ground.
   The London-based human rights group said it is investigating the
killings and has written Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher asking
for an explanation of what happened.
   The group said ``there are a number of circumstances which
suggest that the three were deliberately targeted by the security
forces and killed without challenge, and that no attempt had been
made to capture them.''
   The letter to Mrs. Thatcher said it ``was the government's
responsibility to provide a full and public account of the
circumstances surrounding this incident,'' an Amnesty statement
said.
   British security forces shot the three March 6 as they walked
toward the Spanish border on the British island colony. Britain
said the Irish Republican Army members planned to plant a bomb on
Gibraltar.
   The shooting aggravated British-Irish relations and was followed
by an upsurge of violence in the British province of Northern
Ireland.
   At the burial of the guerrillas March 16, a Protestant gunman
armed with grenades killed three people and injured 68. At the
funeral three days later for one of those victims, a mob attacked
and killed two British soldiers who drove into the area.
   Amnesty said the three guerrillas were watched for weeks while
they allegedly planned a bombing attack but no attempt was made to
arrest them during this period.
   The statement quoted witnesses as saying the three were shot
without warning and ``that at least one of the victims, having
fallen to the ground after an initial gunshot, was shot several
times while lying helpless and incapacitated.''
   It noted that the government rejected demands for an inquiry
into the shootings, despite such calls by lawmakers.
   Amnesty also said it intends to send observers to the inquest
into the deaths, expected to be held in Gibraltar in May.
   The mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republican Army is fighting to
end British rule in Northern Ireland. It wants to unite the
predominantly Protestant province with the mainly Catholic Republic
of Ireland.
   Since sectarian and political violence flared in Northern
Ireland in 1969, 391 British soldiers and 172 members of the Ulster
Defense Regiment, a locally recruited militia, have been killed
there.
</TEXT>
