<2ND_LINE>AM-Blind Man,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blind Man Will Become Neighbor At Condo That First Rejected Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man turned down for residency at a
apartment because of his blindness says he'll drop a discrimination
complaint now that he's been accepted as a tenant.
   Larry Tomecek, 35, says he'll move within a few weeks into a
$350-per-month apartment at a condominium building at Deerfield
Beach.
   ``These people said they are sorry, that they made a mistake,''
he said Tuesday at a news conference at his attorney's office here.
``I accept their apology.''
   Tomecek has lived with his parents near Delray Beach since the
condo directors rejected his application on Feb. 22, saying they
feared that he might cause a fire or trip on stairs and that they
might be sued.
   Tomecek's discrimination claim in Broward County also will be
dropped as soon as the Keswick B Condominium association picks up
moving costs for his personal belongings, which are in storage,
said Larry Corman, Tomecek's attorney.
   ``I'm glad it ends on a happy note,'' said Morris Barnett, one
of five Keswick B directors. ``We want to help him and everything.
It should have never happened, and I'm glad it's straightened out.
We want to get a truck and move the stuff in for him.''
</TEXT>
