<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Gulf     03-30 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Gulf Talks Hit Snag As Iran Delays Sending Envoy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. talks on a cease-fire in the Persian
Gulf war hit a snag Tuesday as Iran put off sending an envoy to New
York as promised.
   Talks between Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar and a
high-level Iranian official, scheduled for Wednesday and Thursday,
were delayed indefinitely at Iran's request, U.N. officials said.
No reason was given.
   Iraq was to send an envoy next Monday and Tuesday, but the
postponement and Iranian charges of chemical warfare by Baghdad
were expected to delay, if not scuttle, the discussions.
   Perez de Cuellar had invited both Iran and Iraq to send
representatives for the fourth round of talks since the Security
Council adopted a cease-fire resolution last July 20. He has
expressed frustration at the delay in putting a truce into effect.
   Iran's envoy was expected to be the deputy foreign minister,
Mohammad Larijani. Iraq had not named a representative.
   Diplomats were pessimistic about a breakthrough and halt to the
7{-year-old conflict. They cited a bitter Iraqi letter to Perez de
Cuellar on Monday and his own sharp retort, and an increase in gulf
warfare.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Azia on Monday sent a letter
attacking the secretary-general for allegedly siding with Iran. The
U.N. chief retorted Tuesday that Iraqi charges were out of place.
   The United States has been pushing for an arms embargo against
Iran to force the Tehran government to comply with the cease-fire.
   The diplomatic situation has been complicated by reports of
Iraqi use of chemical weapons. Iran charged that more than 5,000
people, mostly Iraqi Kurds, were killed and 7,000 injured in
chemical weapons attacks earlier this month. It said the worst-hit
area was territory in Iraq that had been captured by Iran.
</TEXT>
