<NOTE>$adv 30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday March 30</NOTE>
<HEAD>Big Business' Little Business That Prospered</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is nothing very new about recycling one of
nature's materials, since nature itself has been doing that with
air and water since the very beginning of time.
   But in the 1960s, when the aluminum can was introduced to the
markets and (unfortunately) the highways and recreational areas of
America, recycling was a relatively new idea to business, big
business especially.
   In retrospect, you might wonder why. To reuse aluminum was to
save money, protect the environment and generate the good will any
company needs to succeed in selling its products. It was good
business, but business wasn't sure it was.
   This month the aluminum industry observes the 20th anniversary
of the decision to recycle old cans, food trays, gutters,
downspouts, window blinds, house siding and beach chairs. In doing
so, it looks back on a lesson learned.
   The lesson is that it is foolish to waste, and the proof of it
is in the kind of statistics that industry pays attention to.
   In that time, according to Reynolds Aluminum, which claims to
have begun the first program in March 1968, the industry has
recycled 10.5 billion pounds of the metal, equal to 268 billion
cans.
   In that time it has paid $3.75 billion to collectors, saved 60
billion kilowatt hours of electricity, conserved 18.4 million tons
of bauxite (an import that would have added to the trade deficit),
and created 30,000 jobs.
   Recycling has financed charities, spurred entrepreneurship,
saved highway departments big dollars, provided a third of the
industry's raw materials, and undoubtedly protected companies from
environmental law suits.
   What had been viewed as a problem was really an opportunity _ in
fact, dozens of opportunities. Consider, for example, the enoromous
savings on freight costs through use of lighter-weight containers.
   Without recycling, it is unlikely the aluminum can would have
gained much acceptance, since its virtues, such as corrosion
resistance and durability, make it persist as trash, not only in
landfills but wherever discarded.
   The 1960s was a time for activists. The stirrings of a consumer
revolt were being felt, and environmentalists were making the
nation pollution conscious. It wasn't a fortuitous time to
introduce a can with such qualities.
   Looking back, the environmentalists might have destroyed the
industry in its infancy had recycling not been accepted and
developed.
   As it was, the beginnings weren't smooth. In 1968, when Reynolds
began recycling in Los Angeles, only eight beverages _ three soft
drinks and five beers _ were sold in aluminum cans.
   Few people, even those in the industry, believed recycling could
work on a large scale. ``Many within our own industry thought
large-scale consumer recycling was a pipe dream,'' says William O.
Bourke, Reynolds president.
   ``Much to their surprise,'' he comments in remarks prepared for
the 20th anniversary, ``we recycled one million pounds of aluminum
in that first year, and by 1983, just 15 years later, we were
exceeding that amount daily.''
   Today, according to Reynolds, more than 95 percent of all canned
beer and soft drinks are sold in aluminum.
   While there are lessons in this tale for industry and
government, there is one for individuals, too. If you rip the
siding off your house or decide on new lawn furniture or throw a
big summer party with lots to drink, save the waste.
   Then find yourself a recycling center _ there are 10,000 of them
around the country. You might earn as much as 32 cents a pound for
your troubles. But even if you don't, you'll be doing the
environment a favor.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed March 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv31   03-30 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-On the Money, Adv 31,0652</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday March 31</NOTE>
<HEAD>Getting Out of a Bad Investment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York retiree who depends on her savings
and investments for income recently asked a broker for some advice.
   She was worried about the volatility of both the bond and stock
markets, and had been especially upset by a dire forecast for the
economy she had heard on television.
   In her situation, she told the broker, she wanted to take the
safest possible approach, even if it meant sacrificing a few
percentage points in yield.
   ``Your money market funds are fine,'' the broker told her. ``And
don't sell that bond fund. If you get out of it now, you'll be
taking a loss.''
   Most financial advisers would give the broker good marks for his
comment on money market mutual funds. But they would flunk him for
his reasoning on the other fund.
   When people make choices about whether to hold or sell an
investment, these advisers say, they should give very little weight
to what has happened in the past. The future is what matters.
   That goes, they add, for any type of investment that fluctuates
in value, be it a stock, bond, mutual fund, real estate or a
baseball card, for that matter.
   ``Waiting until the value of your property is back up to your
purchase price before you sell is irrational,'' says John Reed in
his newsletter Real Estate Investor's Monthly. ``Your purchase
price is irrelevant to your decision to hold or sell.''
   ``Values go up and values go down, and in their going up and
down they may pass the same figure twice. But values DO NOT `come
back' like homing pigeons or rubber bands that have been stretched.
   ``To think that they do is incorrect analysis and can lead to
bad decisions.''
   After the wide swings in many investment markets over the past
year, including the crash in stock prices last October, there are
countless people sitting with paper losses on their investments.
   Even supposedly hard-nosed professionals acknowledge that it is
only human nature to resist selling something at a loss.
   ``In my work as a money manager, I see two powerful emotions
time and time again,'' says Paul Merriman, who publishes an
advisory letter called Fund Exchange:
   _``The desire to break even on an investment _ regardless of how
costly a bullheaded pursuit of this goal may prove;
   _``The desire to buy the past, which manifests itself in the
insistence on purchasing a particular stock, fund or other
investment because it has done well in the past, without taking
into account the amount of risk that may be involved.''
   The choice of selling rather than holding on does have some
consequences that must be considered. All other things being equal,
it is worthwhile to try to time your sales of losing investments
with tax consequences in mind.
   Also, sales of some types of investments involve significant
transaction costs that can't be ignored. And the market for an
out-of-favor investment may be relatively illiquid, so that you
might be faced with accepting a bigger price concession than you
feel comfortable with.
   These and other considerations militate against changing your
mind too often, jumping from one investment to another.
   Still, veterans of the investing wars say, no investment that
falls in value with changing market conditions ``owes'' you your
money back.
   Says Reed: ``All decisions, including a decision to own
property, are choices between alternatives. When confronted with a
choice between alternatives, you should always pick the best one.
   ``That sounds obvious. But many investors clearly lose sight of
it, especially when they get bad news like a value drop.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs March 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 2324EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv31   03-30 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 31 ,0621</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday March 31</NOTE>
<HEAD>An Old Story: The Amateur Buyer vs. the Professional Seller</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A regulation of the Federal Trade Commission
declares that ``no statement or illustration should be used in an
advertisement which creates a false impression of the usability of
the product offered.''
   The law is violated, according to the regulation, ``if the first
contact or interview is secured by deception.''
   Question: Is an automobile-company finance subsidiary guilty,
therefore, if it advertises a low-low rate on two-year loans,
knowing that most customers will need longer-term loans at higher
rates?
   Some other credit lenders think they are, and they have
petitioned the FTC to rule in their favor. The practice, they say,
``is a classic case of bait-and-switch, and is unlawful under the
FTC Act.''
   As viewed by the Credit Union National Association and the
Independent Bankers Association of America, whose members depend
heavily on income from car loans, the interest-rate promotions hurt
not just them but customers, too.
   Their claim adds another twist to one of the more puzzling
challenges of today's marketplace: What is the price of a car? It
isn't the first time the question was posed.
   In fact, detailed sticker pricing on car windows was among the
primary accomplishments of the consumer movement that began in the
1960s. Before then, not even a cryptographer could foretell with
certainty what you might pay.
   The stickers helped, but still left many questions, in part
because of the number of options available on a particular car. And
like it or not, some cars were available only with the options
included, and others came without them.
   The options themselves, so numerous, present customers with
decisions many feel unqualified to make. Their despair can be
compared to a novice traveler trying to develop, without help from
an agent, a lowest-cost air itenerary.
   When car companies decided to compete with rebates and
below-market interest rates still greater complexity was added to
the challenge. And, say the credit union and banking people, it
made buyers easy targets for sellers.
   In the petition, they state that the cut-rate financing by
Chrysler Financial Corp., Ford Motor Credit Co. and General Motors
Acceptance Corp. often applies only to two-year loans, whereas many
customers need much longer terms.
   Such offers, they say in the petition, are bait to lure
customers into showrooms where, in spite of the low interest rates,
customers first become aware of the unacceptable high monthly
payments on the two-year loans.
   But is it deception? Or is it merely an attempt by intensely
competitve marketers to sell their products in the most enticing
way they know how? The rates are honestly quoted; they're
available, if only for two-year periods.
   And if the automobile financing companies are quilty, what then
can be said about many savings and commercial banks that publicize
high returns on their certificates of deposit _ and quietly
restrict them to larger accounts?
   Basic to all this is the same question that prevailed in the
1960s, when it was widely asserted that consumers were at a
disadvantage in the marketplace because they were amateurs and
sellers were professionals.
   Since then, the consumer has become more aware of how the
marketplace works, the result of legislation, advocacy groups,
education, publicity and honest efforts by sellers to make products
and policies understandable.
   Still, many people suspect that perhaps the ingenuity of the
marketplace pros may have developed more rapidly in the past two
decades than the awareness of customers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs March 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 0905EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv01   03-30 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 01,0641</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, April l and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``biblical hope'' of Passover, marking
emancipation of the Jews from Egyptian slavery to establish an
independent country, is seen by a Jewish leader as realized anew in
modern Israel.
   With the week-long Passover observance beginning this Friday
evening, Theodore Ellenoff, president of the American Jewish
Committee, said the rebirth of Israel 40 years ago embodies the
ancient Passover goal of a homeland.
   American Jews should ``maintain solidarity with Israel, whatever
differences of opinion might arise over specific issues and
particular policies,'' he said.
   He said the ``centrality of freedom'' was the Passover theme of
deliverance from bondage to a promised land, and that wherever
countries ``restrict the freedom of their inhabitants, Jews must
protest.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Denton Lotz has been named acting
general secretary of the Baptist World Alliance, replacing the Rev.
Gerhard Claas, who was killed March 21 in an automobile accident
near San Francisco.
   Lotz previously was associate secretary. A memorial service for
Claas of Wetter, West Germany, has been set for April 19 at the
McClean Baptist Church, Maclean, Va.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1987 when the world's population hit 5
billion, the number of Scriptures which the American Bible Scoeit
has distributed since its founding in 1816 also passed the
5-billion mark.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executive bodies of two Protestant
denominations have agreed that their new ecumenical partnership
eventually will involve ``mutual recognition of members and
ordained ministers'' and ``full communion.''
   The statement was approved in a joint meeting of the executive
council of the 1.7-million-member United Church of Christ and
administrative committee of the 1.1-million-member Christian Church
(Disciples of Christ).
   Officials of the two denominations, which declared a working
ecumenical partnership in 1985, said it is not ``the full unity to
which God calls us'' but ``we are working toward a time'' when it
will be.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Southern Baptist executive committee has
declined to make a sweeping investigation of its Baptist Press news
service, but a subcommittee has advised it to exercise ``Christian
restraint.''
   The news service has come under increasing pressures as a
fundamentalist wing gained control of denominational operations.
   But the executive committee said the requested investigation of
stories issued over the last 10 years would be a ``prohibitive task
of studying more than 9,000 releases.'
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 50-member administrative board of U.S.
Catholic bishops voted that their June meeting include a discussion
of AIDS, about which policy had become controversial.
   Some bishops objected to a statement issued by the board last
December, saying pre-marital celibacy and martical fidelity were
the only safeguards against AIDS, but public schools might provide
information about condoms.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishops of the Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America say ``persons of homosexual orientation'' seeking
ordination or who already are ordained ``are expected to refrain
from homosexual pracrtice.''
   The statement came after three senior seminarians at Pacific
Lutheran Theological Seminary at Berkeley, Calif., announced they
are homosexual and have been assigned as pastoral candidates in
West Coast synods.
   Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom, head of the denomination, said the
church's ministry embraces all people, including homosexuals, but
the church must set standards for those called as pastors.
   He said the church draws a distinction between homosexual
orientation and homosexual practice, and many denominations have
clergy who may be homosexually oriented, but he added:
   ``The church will not ordain persons who engage in homosexual
behavior nor will it permit such persons to be on the clergy roster
if such pracrtice is discovered.''
</TEXT>
