<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Oscars-BestPicture Adv04   03-30 0978</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Oscars-Best Picture, Adv 04,1001</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: Best Picture</HEAD>
<HEAD>Box Office Success Doesn't Always Lead to Oscars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the Academy Awards were based on box-office
popularity, ``Fatal Attraction'' would eliminate its four opponents
and win as best picture with ease.
   If Oscars were based on media acclaim, ``Broadcast News'' no
doubt would be the winner. The funny, incisive look at how network
journalists do their jobs under constant pressure captivated most
critics, yet ``Broadcast News'' has been a disappointment at the
box office.
   Despite mediocre attendance and mixed notices, the home-stretch
favorite for best picture of 1987 is the ``The Last Emperor,'' a
mammoth epic centering on the life of Pu Yi, boy emperor of China
and later puppet ruler of Manchuria for the Japanese. Bernardo
Bertolucci was nominated for director and co-writer, but the actors
were overlooked.
   The thriller ``Fatal Attraction'' was by far the biggest
moneymaker of the year, its combination of adultery and terror
selling $150 million worth of tickets in the United States and
Canada.
   ``Fatal Attraction'' also picked up nominations for Michael
Douglas, Glenn Close and Anne Archer, as well as director Adrian
Lyne and writer James Dearden.
   Lyne, a graduate of British TV commercials, admits that he was
sold on ``Fatal Attraction'' from the time he read the script.
   ``It was a page-turner,'' he said. ``It was sent to me when I
was in France. I sat down on some steps, and two hours later I was
still on the steps, finishing it off. It was something I couldn't
put down. I thought if I could provide the visual equipment and not
screw it up, that it had a fighting chance of being as interesting
a movie.''
   Lyne signed on with producers Stanley Jaffe and Sherry Lansing
and worked with Dearden on the script. The director carries a tape
recorder while preparing a film, and he made notes of matters he
could use, such as his own son's attempt to demonstrate card tricks.
   The three leading actors of ``Broadcast News'' _ William Hurt,
Holly Hunter and Albert Brooks _ also were nominated for awards.
James L. Brooks was named as writer and producer but, astoundingly,
did not receive a nomination as director.
   ``I wanted to do a romantic comedy,'' Brooks said. ``Just
through a series of circumstances I wound up being around a number
of network news people.''
   Brooks, who once worked as a news writer for CBS News, spent
months hanging around in studios of Washington and New York for his
research. The result is a verisimilitude that has attracted the
praise of many network news people, including the curmudgeonly Andy
Rooney.
   Bertolucci amazed the film world by winning permission to film a
movie with political overtones within China. More amazingly, he was
able to shoot inside the fabled Forbidden City, the shrine of
Chinese history.
   ``The fact that this movie exists is another proof that China is
changing,'' the Italian director said. ``Only eight years ago it
was inconceivable for the Chinese to let a Western filmmaker do a
scene about the Red Guards, as at the end of the movie when you see
the Cultural Revolution.''
   Nominee ``Hope and Glory'' is John Boorman's valentine to his
boyhood during the Battle of Britain. The writer-director-producer
won triple nominations, but his actors received none. The movie's
box-office performance has been less than impressive.
   Despite the background of German bombings, the film is primarily
comedic.
   ``For me as a child, the experience of the war was largely one
of exhilaration, joy and fun,'' Boorman said. ``This is what the
film is; it's great entertainment, it's very funny. There were
moments of horror, when people were killed. As a child, you forget
this very quickly.''
   Also up for best film of the year is ``Moonstruck,'' a romantic
comedy about an excitable Italian family in Brooklyn. Cher, Vincent
Gardenia and Olympia Dukakis are acting nominees, as well as
director Norman Jewison and writer John Patrick Shanley.
   ``Moonstruck'' has been a major success at the box office, doing
more than $50 million in business so far.
   After a pair of heavy dramas, ``A Soldier's Story'' and ``Agnes
of God,'' Jewison ``was in the mood for a romantic comedy.'' His
first choice to play Loretta, the widow torn between two lovers,
was Cher.
   ``For me, there has always been something `streety' about Cher,
a lacking in pretension,'' the Canadian director said. ``She's a
very honest person _ in-person and on the screen. She looks
Italian, although she's part Armenian and part Cherokee.''
   Yet directors don't always get their first choice for lead
performers, as was the case with ``Fatal Attraction.'' As right as
Glenn Close might seem for the role of the jilted Alix, director
Lyne said Isabelle Adjani was actually his first choice, since she
had played a similar role in a French film.
   ``But after a few months of casting _ I like to see everyone I
can _ I thought it would be more effective to go with someone who
was not obviously sensual from the outset,'' he said.
   ``Glenn Close pursued the movie and was prepared to come in and
test, which was unusual for a star. When I saw her testing with
Michael (Douglas), it was already decided on.''
   Lyne had once worked with Douglas as producer on ``Starman,''
which he ended up not directing.
   ``I had seen Michael almost every day for a year, and I saw him
as a man who was infinitely charming to both men and women but was
also very vulnerable,'' Lyne said. ``I had never seen that in
movies he had done. I had always seen more of his father _ the
heroic, the macho qualities.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 4</NOTE>
