<2ND_LINE>AM-R Is for Ritalin I, Adv 04-1st Add,0730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LOS ANGELES: cause delinquency.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In a report to Congress last year, agencies including the
National Institutes of Health, the Food and Drug Administration,
the National Institute of Mental Health and the Centers for Disease
Control said ``the side effects are minimal'' for children treated
with Ritalin.
   Ritalin's manufacturer, Ciba-Geigy Corp., is straightforward
about the side effects, which include nervousness, insomnia,
rashes, anorexia, nausea, headaches and weight loss. Some evidence
suggests it can temporarily retard growth.
   Ciba-Geigy also cautions about its use by emotionally unstable
patients and the possibility of severe depression in unsupervised
withdrawal from the drug.
   Clarke complains these warnings don't reach parents and further
asserts that psychiatrists have used drugs to create a
self-perpetuating industry. Those who dispute him, he adds, are
trying to protect their business.
   ``These are the baby-druggers,'' Clarke said. ``I believe I'm
pretty conservative with my information. ... The whole thing does
not exist because of Scientology. The problem exists because
children are being harmed.''
   Clarke defends his allegations, saying they are based on medical
literature, and contends doctors who prescribe Ritalin aren't
acknowledging its dangers.
   Psychiatrists, however, say CCHR attacks them because of their
basic philosophical difference with the Church of Scientology,
which does not recognize mental illness as a physiological problem.
   Scientology, founded by science fiction writer Hubbard in 1954,
is based on a theory called ``Dianetics'' which says physical and
mental problems can be solved by using an ``E-meter,'' an electric
device set up much like a lie detector. Members are assigned
exercises and counseling to eliminate negative mental images and
achieve a ``clear state.''
   The church supports CCHR, Clarke said, because the group is
``part of the basic philosophy _ things having to do with the
spiritual nature of man. You don't deal with the spirit by
lobotomizing someone or using electric shock. It's not only bad
science, it's harmful for the being.''
   Clarke is a convincing speaker with a seemingly endless catalog
of Ritalin horror stories. He left a successful solar heating
business in Hawaii in 1985 to run CCHR, and travels constantly,
using local issues as a platform for his crusade.
   Just before 15-year-old Rod Matthews, an emotionally troubled
youth who used Ritalin, was tried for the murder of classmate Shaun
Ouillette, 14, in Canton, Mass., Clarke appeared on local talk
shows. After the trial, he held a news conference to announce more
lawsuits.
   Last year, the local CCHR chapter staged a demonstration in
Canton. The victim's mother, Jeanne Quinn, said a couple holding a
sign reading ``Ritalin Killed Shaun, Not Rod'' came to her door,
asked for her and offered pamphlets on the dangers of Ritalin.
   Matthews' defense included claims that Ritalin worsened his
severe mental problems. The jury found him sane and convicted him
of second-degree murder. He was sentenced to life in prison,
eligible for parole after 15 years.
   Ironically, the victim had taken Ritalin for four years,
successfully conquering his hyperactivity.
   ``They look for cases like this and grab onto it for their own
purposes,'' Mrs. Quinn said of CCHR. ``I have little respect for
any of their opinions. They take small quotations and excerpts from
medical books and give you their opinion. Everything is out of
context.''
   When the University of Minnesota held a conference on ADD last
summer, CCHR members staged rallies, hung signs on expressway
overpasses, announced a Ritalin lawsuit and staged a rock concert
for a ``Drug Free America.''
   ``The following week my practice received roughly 40 phone calls
from parents concerned about the medication,'' said Dr. Jeffrey
Alexander, a pediatrician at Minneapolis' Park Nicollet Medical
Center who has about 200 patients on Ritalin. Three or four
actually discontinued treatment, he said.
   Experts like the Satterfields say that while they are concerned
that Ritalin needs to be used properly, they worry that because
CCHR is trading on parents' fears, children not getting treatment
they need.
   ``It's unfortunate that these children become the victims of
special interest groups instead of being looked at for their
individual requirements,'' said Mrs. Satterfield. ``Fear doesn't
contribute to good treatment of children and good medical
practices.''
</TEXT>
