<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Drug Helps 80 Percent of ADD Children, But No One Knows Why</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-R Is for Ritalin I</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To calm hyperactive children, doctors give them a
stimulant.
   The seemingly contradictory effects of stimulants on hyperactive
youngsters have been known since the 1930s. When used carefully,
most experts agree, they are safe and effective.
   The most commonly prescribed of these medicines is a mild
central nervous system stimulant called Ritalin. The drug, known
generically as methylphenidate, was first sold in 1955 to improve
mental performance in the elderly and reduce fatigue.
   Now it is the mainstay of treatment for attention deficit
disorder in children, which parents usually recognize by its most
common and distressing symptom, hyperactivity.
   Experts say as many as 80 percent of ADD youngsters may be
helped by drug treatment, but the extent of their improvement
varies.
   ``Thirty percent of the kids who have attention deficit disorder
do so well on the drug that the parents want to kiss you on both
cheeks,'' said Dr. Jonathan Cole of McLean Hospital, a
Harvard-affiliated mental hospital in Belmont, Mass. ``Other kids
are sort of better or not really better at all.'' The underlying
cause of the disorder and the reason stimulants calm children and
help them concentrate are still mysteries.
   Genes play some role. Studies show one-third of all youngsters
with ADD have parents with the ailment. About half the youngsters
with ADD outgrow the problem by adolescence; the rest carry it into
adulthood.
   ``This drug has been around for 50 years and marketed for 30,''
said Dr. Ron Kartzinel of Ciba-Geigy, the company that makes
Ritalin. ``We really cannot fully explain, biochemically or
physiologically, how the drug works in attention deficit disorder.
There are many theories, but they are just that _ theories.''
   Other drugs used to treat the disorder are Cylert, or pemoline,
and Dexedrine, or dextroamphetamine. All of them stimulate the
brain to produce chemical messengers that brain cells use to alert
and stimulate their neighbors. Experts believe this increase in
brain chemicals has something to do with the drugs' beneficial
effects.
   The drugs do carry side effects, but most are mild and passing.
Some youngsters lose their appetites and have trouble falling
asleep for the first week or two they take Ritalin.
   Ritalin can also slow youngsters' growth. Dr. David Zametkin of
the National Institute of Mental Health said doctors should monitor
patients' height and weight. If growth slows, they should take them
off the drug temporarily, during summer vacation, for example. The
youngsters then have a growth spurt and catch up.
   Another, but extremely rare, side effect is tics and twitches.
Zametkin said that when the drugs are stopped, these problems
almost always go away.
   At Ciba-Geigy, Kartzinel said that over the last 16 years, the
company has received 17 reports of slowed growth and 10 reports of
tics associated with Ritalin.
   A few years ago, doctors feared that Ritalin caused Tourette's
syndrome, a disorder in which people make involuntary movements and
noises. However, Zametkin said it now appears Tourette's syndrome
itself is often preceded by symptoms that resemble those for ADD.
   Some youngsters who are treated with Ritalin for ADD
subsequently develop Tourette's syndrome, he said, but this would
have happened anyway, regardless of whether they got the drug.
   Zametkin said the stimulants do not, as some parents fear, make
children high or euphoric. Instead, if they take too much, they
tend to become moody and irritable.
   ``If you know anybody who ever took Dexedrine to stay up and
study, they got some of the same effects as these kids _ improved
concentration, decreased distractability and less fatigue,'' said
Cole. ``It's sort of like super-coffee, although it makes you feel
less jittery.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 4</NOTE>
