<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Robertson'sLegacy Adv03-1stAdd   03-30 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Robertson's Legacy, Adv 03-1st Add,0553</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday AMs, April 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: against Robertson.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Hawaii, where Robertson swept party caucuses Feb. 4, GOP
chairman Howard Chong was ousted by a Robertson supporter, losing
his chance to attend the party's state convention as a delegate.
   Chong first pledged to unite the warring factions, but later
called a news conference to denounce the ``lies and innuendoes'' of
Robertson people and announced: ``Frankly speaking, I have had
enough.''
   Under the rules, Bush won all 48 delegates in Georgia, but when
the state's delegates are selected as many as half are expected to
go Robertson people. They will be bound to Bush for two ballots at
the national convention, but free to vote with Robertson on
platform issues, credentials challenges and party rules.
   ``It is our aim to see that the party is broadened,'' said
attorney Don Johnson of Marietta, Ga., a Robertson supporter.
``...We're either going to broaden it with them or broaden it over
them.''
   Bob Bell, former state GOP chairman, said, however: ``Nothing in
their numbers would lead me to believe this group can take over the
party.''
   Robertson supporters dominated many precinct meetings and county
conventions in Oklahoma. One likely result, says Matt Seward,
Bush's state director: the Oklahomans will support a plank
denouncing the arms control treaty coming before the Senate for
ratification even though Bush vigorously supports it.
   Bush swept the 111 national delegates available from his adopted
state of Texas, but Robertson forces, based on their showings in
county conventions in March, think they have a chance to elect
their own candidate as state GOP chairman in Houston in June. Some
Texas counties will send delegations that are 100 percent Robertson
people.
   ``If the new Robertson-type people will filter out some of the
biblical language and keep their principles, they can realize more
of their goals,'' commented retiring Texas chairman George Strake,
a former Democrat who converted to Republicanism in 1961 ``because
I thought Republicans were firmer against communism.''
   Nevada, reflecting the outcome of February's caucuses, will send
a pro-Robertson delegation to the national convention. Robertson's
state director, Steve Wark, said the Nevadans will be in no mood to
jump aboard a Bush bandwagon. Such a conciliatory move, he said,
would be ``poisonous.''
   In Washington state, the only Super Tuesday state that went for
Robertson, GOP executive director John Meyers was asked if he saw
the Robertson crowd as heirs to the Reagan Revolution. He replied:
``I see it as an extension of the Goldwater Revolution.'' Anti-gay,
anti-United Nations, pro-school prayer conservatives have run the
state party for decades, even though Sen. Dan Evans, R-Wash., is
characterized as moderate-to-liberal.
   In Maine, when Robertson people threatened to take over in
February, forces supporting Bush and Bob Dole buried their
differences to vote them down and prevent the selection of a
pro-Robertson delegation to New Orleans.
   Robertson coordinator John Solberg cried foul. ``The Bush and
Dole campaigns are attempting to keep the majority silent in the
democratic process,'' he complained. Gov. John R. McKernan Jr., a
Bush man, brushed off the charge. ``This is not fun and games,'' he
said. ``We're talking about the next president of the United
States.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
