<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0536</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., a leveraged
buyout specialist, is seeking federal permission to buy up to 15
percent of Texaco Inc.'s stock.
   In announcing the move, the investment firm also said Tuesday it
had already acquired 11.95 million Texaco shares, or about 4.9
percent of Texaco's roughly 242 million outstanding shares.
   The move added fuel to growing market anticipation that a
takeover attempt of the nation's third largest oil company is only
a matter of time.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc., seeking to end
a 2-month-old takeover war, plans to weigh final offers by the two
companies that want to buy the retailer.
   One of its suitors, Campeau Corp., immediately objected Tuesday
to the guidelines for choosing a winner, but a federal judge
rebuffed its attempt to block Federated's plan. The deadline for
bids is Wednesday.
   In a letter to Campeau and R.H. Macy & Co. Inc., Federated said
its board would choose the ``best proposal'' from the final
purchase offers. Campeau and Macy have each offered to buy
Federated for more than $6 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Odyssey Partners has sweetened its tender offer
for J.P. Stevens & Co. to $1.14 billion, but analysts predicted
further bidding in the battle for the textile giant.
   West Point-Pepperell Inc., which has made a $1.1 billion bid for
Stevens, is expected to compete fiercely for the crown jewels _
three state-of-the-art factories and licenses for hot designer
labels that lure consumers around the world to Stevens' quality
sheets and towels.
   Odyssey, a New York investment firm, said Tuesday it would pay
$64 for each of Stevens' 17.8 million outstanding shares, up from
the $61.50-a-share tender offer Stevens' management accepted
earlier this month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roper Corp.'s board of directors have
changed sides in the takeover fight for the appliance manufacturer,
and are backing a bid from General Electric Co. instead of
Whirlpool Corp.
   Roper's board determined that GE's $508 million tender offer was
clearly superior to Whirlpool's $470 million one, the company said
Tuesday in withdrawing a recommendation of Whirlpool made March 18.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's chief economic forecasting
gauge posted a 0.9 percent increase in February in a performance
which analysts said should lay to rest fears of a 1988 recession.
   The 0.9 percent rise reported Tuesday in the Commerce
Department's Index of Leading Indicators was the biggest advance
since a 1 percent rise last June.
   The index had fallen in three of the past four months, including
declines of 0.1 percent in October, 1.2 percent in November and 1.1
percent in January.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New home sales broke a three-month slide by
jumping 20.3 percent in February, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that new single-family
homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 628,000
units. It was the first monthly increase since a 1.4 percent rise
in October, but it still left sales 14.9 percent below where they
were a year ago.
</TEXT>
