<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   03-30 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0510</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress unconstitutionally singled out
publisher Rupert Murdoch by prohibiting his continued ownership of
newspapers and television stations in the same city, an appeals
court says.
   A recently enacted provision barring the Federal Communications
Commission from extending temporary waivers from its
cross-ownership rule is unconstitutional because it ``strikes at
Murdoch with the precision of a laser beam'' without a legitimate
purpose, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington ruled
Tuesday in a 2-1 opinion.
   Murdoch recently sold the New York Post so he could keep a New
York television station in compliance with the law, and faces a
similar choice in Boston.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. has offered significantly increased
pension benefits to about 11 percent of its employees if they elect
to retire within the next four months.
   The option was offered Tuesday to about 800 of the company's
7,000 workers and was described as part of the company's continuing
effort to streamline operations to be competitive.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American builders will be allowed to bid on
Japanese construction projects under a new agreement aimed at
ending a trade dispute that has soured relations between the two
countries.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter told a joint news
conference Tuesday he was pleased that the prolonged, on-and-ff
talks had reached ``a fruitful conclusion,'' proving that the two
countries through negotiations are able ``to manage difficult
bilateral trade disputes.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate trade bill writers have
defied President Reagan's veto threat by approving a plan to
require companies to give employees advance notice of plant
closings and large-scale layoffs.
   The action Tuesday came amid new administration warnings that
putting the provision in the final package could doom the
1,000-page trade bill designed to sharpen the U.S. edge in global
markets.
   Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin said she hoped ``congressional
leaders will find a way to drop this provision in these last days
of the conference. If not, I have no recourse but to recommend a
veto.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines has been ordered to stop the
training of non-union pilots aboard its aircraft by a cargo carrier
that was hired to help the company prepare for a possible strike
this spring.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker granted a preliminary
injunction Tuesday sought by the Air Line Pilots Association to
prevent Eastern from leasing as many as five of its aircraft to
Orion Lift Services Inc. to train 350 to 400 non-union pilots in
case of a strike.
</TEXT>
