<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall After Four-Day Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Profit-taking by futures investors has snapped a
four-day rally in oil prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Tuesday, contracts for May
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
settled at $16.98 per 42-gallon barrel, down 12 cents from Monday's
close. All other contract months also lost 12 cents a barrel.
   Among refined oil products, the April contract for wholesale
heating oil edged down 0.02 cent a gallon to 48.15 cents. Unleaded
gasoline for April rose, on the other hand, by 0.24 cent a gallon
to 48.26 cents.
   Analysts noted that the decline was moderate and prices moved
within narrow trading ranges. The selling was led by oil companies,
they said.
   Prices are ``still showing a fair amount of resiliency,'' said
John Azarow, an oil futures trader for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The recent strength stems from hopes that the pricing committee
of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries will
achieve an agreement to prop up prices, analysts say. Prices have
risen in eight of the last 11 trading sessions on the Mercantile
Exchange.
   The OPEC pricing panel has announced it will hold a meeting in
Vienna, Austria, starting April 9. The five pricing committee
members are Saudi Arabia, Nigeria, Indonesia, Algeria and Venezuela.
   On the negative side, Middle East Economic Survey, an oil
industry newsletter, said some observers believe OPEC production
has risen to about 18 million barrels a day.
   The newsletter said demand for OPEC crude, even taking into
account some stockpiling, is unlikely to top 17 million barrels a
day.
</TEXT>
