<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CBS-Retirement Bjt   03-30 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS-Retirement, Bjt,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Offers Early Retirement Incentives to Older Employees</HEAD>
<HEAD>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. says its special offer of increased
pension benefits to about 11 percent of its employees who agree to
retire within four months would help it slim down and compete in
the tough broadcasting business.
   But one securities analyst said such offers have typically cost
companies some of their better workers and could hurt CBS in the
long run.
   ``These things have tended to give the best people a reason to
leave and the worst people a reason not to,'' said Alan Gottesman,
who follows media companies for the investment firm L.F. Rothschild
& Co.
   On Wall Street, CBS rose 62{ cents a share to $158.75 in trading
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   CBS disclosed Tuesday that it was offering the option to about
800 of the company's 7,000 workers and was described as part of the
company's continuing effort to streamline operations to be
competitive.
   A company spokeswoman, Alice Henderson, said the company had set
no goal for how many people it hoped would take advantage of the
program.
   ``The program is completely voluntary and eligible employees
have until July 1 to make their decision on this offer,'' CBS said
in a memo to the workers who are involved. Retirement must occur no
later than July 29.
   Since Laurence A. Tisch took over as chief executive in the fall
of 1986, CBS has sold its records, magazines and book publishing
units, leaving it with a core business of broadcasting and about $3
billion in cash.
   But analysts say the CBS Television network has been
unprofitable and is likely to end the current season in last place
in prime-time audience ratings, a development that could depress
its advertising revenue.
   The special retirement program is available to CBS employees 55
years of age and older who have at least 10 years of pension
vesting credit.
   Those who accept the offer would get pension benefits calculated
as if the employee were five years older and had completed an
additional five years of service.
   ``As we all understand, CBS is still in the process of examining
ways in which we can further streamline our operations to ensure
our ability to be competitive in an increasingly competitive
market,'' the memo said.
   ``We hope that the availability of this very attractive
voluntary retirement option will assist us in reaching this
objective,'' it said.
   The company offered a similar early retirement incentive plan in
1985, and a CBS source who asked not to be identified said about
500 people took advantage of it.
   The source said the latest plan is viewed by CBS management as a
less painful way to make staff reductions than by firings.
   J. Kendrick Noble, the media analyst for the investment firm
PaineWebber, said the offer was a cost-cutting move that reflected
the corporate restructuring and the television network's dismal
ratings performance.
   ``It's not that this company is fat or anything, but it is under
more pressure than others to reduce costs,'' he said.
   Rumors have circulated _ and have been denied repeatedly by CBS
_ that Tisch may be planning to sell the television network while
holding on to its radio and television stations. Rothschild's
Gottesman said the retirement incentive is ``consistent with the
liquidation theory.''
   But John Reidy, a media analyst for the investment firm Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc., said he found nothing unusual about the early
retirement offer.
   ``Tisch felt he could do things with less people ... He wants to
get an improved return on his investment. I don't see anything
cosmic in any of this,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
