<DOCNO> AP880330-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 0110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AgingWorkers     03-30 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aging Workers,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Shows Ways Companies Deal With Older Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Older white-collar workers face employer
attitudes ranging from accommodating to hostile, and a company's
financial health plays a part, a University of Michigan study shows.
   Corporations with money problems are most likely to be
antagonistic toward older workers, according to the study of 25
Fortune 500 companies by Barbara Hirshorn.
   She said her interviews at the 25 companies indicated factors
such as the state of the economy and the industry, corporate
personality, corporate leadership and organizational structure
shaped company attitudes.
   The study also indicated corporate attitudes can change, said
Hirshorn, a research fellow at the university's Population Studies
Center.
   Companies participating in the study were guaranteed
confidentiality.
   Hirshorn said attitudes toward older workers could be
categorized as:
   _Pro-active. These companies dealt most effectively with older
workers, offering more than one possible career ladder, maintaining
options for the company and for workers of all ages, encouraging
lateral career changes and reassigning workers to relieve stress
and boredom.
   _Performance-focused. Such companies tried to ignore age and
apply a reliable evaluation system to all employees. Hirshorn said
this tended to benefit older employees over younger ones who had to
be considered more in terms of their potential.
   _At cross-purposes. At these companies, managers might express
high regard and design some effective policies for older workers,
but retain other policies that work against them. Limited
opportunities for promotion or lateral moves and huge, sweetened
early retirement programs were examples.
   Hirshorn said some retailers have policies at cross-purposes,
voicing pride in being non-discriminatory but at the same time
assuming older employees will burn out because the business is
stressful and failing to offer them new opportunities.
   _Positive means-negative ends. These were companies where
coordinated planning efforts were subverted to get rid of older
workers. Hirshorn said such actions were often the result of new
stresses from inside or outside the organization.
   _Actively antagonistic. In a few companies, hostility showed up
in a variety of policies. ``I came across one insurance company
where age bias ran deeply throughout the ranks,'' Hirshorn said.
``Those who refused to relocate were fired, and since so few
employees over 55 were promoted, many older workers left.''
   Some companies refused to retrain older workers, citing poor
return on investment, though they did not raise the issue when
retraining workers in their 30s who are more likely to leave for
new jobs, she said.
   Hirshorn said she will study 10 of the 25 companies to determine
how they change or maintain their policies in reaction to external
and internal stresses over time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
