<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-30 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Generally Higher In Sluggish Trading, Gold Eases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies in
sluggish European trading this morning as volume tapered off before
the Easter break. Gold prices eased.
   Dealers predicted volume would remain thin through Good Friday
and the dollar would likely trade around its present levels until
after the Easter weekend.
   The Bank of Japan intervened for the second straight day to
support the dollar, but traders in Frankfurt said the market
reacted mildly because the amount of dollars purchased by Japan's
central bank was apparently small.
   Traders said, however, the intervention served its purpose by
reviving market fears of concerted central bank intervention.
   ``There are a lot of traders around who want to sell dollars but
are afraid to do so,'' said a dealer at a major West German bank in
Frankfurt.
   Traders said the dollar gained some support from recent
statistics that indicate the U.S. economy is robust.
   ``The underlying sentiment is still certainly bearish on the
dollar, but not aggressively so,'' said one trader with a major
European commercial bank in Milan.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.06 yen to a closing 125.43 Japanese yen.
Later, in London, it fell back to 125.28 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.6705 West German marks, up from 1.6610; 1.3790
Swiss francs, up from 1.3735; 5.6587 French francs, up from 5.6280;
1.8764 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8690; 1,236.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,232.50; 1.2362 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2363.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.8615 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8705 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $454.50 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $454.00. Both were down from Tuesday's late
bid of $454.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $454.00, down from $455.00 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.09 to close at a bid of
$455.79.
   Silver bullion eased in London to a bid price of $6.675 a troy
ounce, down from $6.69 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
