<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-30 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Market Soars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gains on overseas markets helped boost the dollar
in Tokyo today, while the stock market's key index closed at a
post-crash high.
   Trading on the foreign exchange market was quiet, with many
corporate customers staying on the sidelines until the end of
Japan's fiscal year on Thursday, dealers said.
   The dollar opened at 125.75 yen, up 1.38 yen from Tuesday's
close of 124.37 yen. It began edging down in the afternoon and
ended trading at 125.43 yen, up 1.06 yen. The U.S. currency ranged
between 125.40 and 125.78 yen, with spot volume totaling $5.3
billion.
   The gain came after the dollar had lost a total of 2.78 yen over
four trading days.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange enjoyed its third consecutive day of
healthy gains in heavy trading. The 225-stock Nikkei Average rose
366.89 points, or 1.41 percent, ending the day at 26,319.98.
   It was the first time the key index had closed above the
26,000-level since the October market crash. The closing was less
than 327 points from the index's all-time closing high of 26,646.43.
   Traders said stock prices were boosted by the stronger dollar,
gains on the New York and London markets on Tuesday, and typical
enthusiasm marking the start of the new Japanese fiscal year.
   ``Sentiment is very positive. We might see a new historical high
this week, as long as New York (Wall Street) and the yen behave,''
a trader said.
   On the foreign exchange market, traders said many participants
continued to cover dollar-short positions as they had on Tuesday,
when the dollar temporarily touched 123.87 yen, its lowest level
since the first week of January.
   They attributed the U.S. currency's higher opening today to
overnight gains on overseas markets and unconfirmed reports of
greater intervention in support of the dollar by the U.S. Federal
Reserve.
   Also adding to the U.S. currency's strength was a denial today
by Japanese insurance companies that they were planning to begin
dumping dollars after the start of the new fiscal year.
   Rumors had been circulating that the companies, a major
influence in currency markets, would discontinue their recent
support for the dollar, said to have been aimed at defending the
value of their holdings for accounting purposes.
   But many analysts said bullish sentiments toward the yen remain
in the market because of healthly Japanese economic fundamentals.
</TEXT>
