<1ST_LINE>u f PM-FCC-Murdoch 1stLd-Writethru   03-30 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FCC-Murdoch, 1st Ld-Writethru,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murdoch Still Faces Problem Holding onto Both Boston Properties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT title</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Rupert Murdoch could still have
trouble obtaining a government extension allowing him to keep both
his newspaper and television station in Boston, because both
properties are making money.
   The possibility of an extension was opened Tuesday by a federal
appeals court. The panel ruled that Congress unconstitutionally
singled out Murdoch when it barred the Federal Communications
Commission from extending temporary waivers of a rule forbidding
common ownership of newspapers and TV stations in the same city.
   Under existing FCC cross-owership rules, Murdoch would have to
show that either the Boston Herald or WFXT-TV is financially
distressed. However, both properties are making money.
   ``Unless the commission were to make some tremendous change in
the criteria for granting a waiver, he doesn't qualify and we will
oppose it,'' said Andrew Schwartzman, executive director of Media
Access Project, a Washington, D.C.-based public interest law firm.
   Diane Killory, FCC general counsel, said temporary waivers are
granted to give the owner of a newspaper-TV combination time to
sell one of the properties for a fair price and avoid forcing a
distress sale.
   ``If someone were willing to pay fair market value, it would be
tough to argue it would be a distress sale, and that's the criteria
we use when a temporary waiver is justified,'' she said.
   For a permanent waiver, an owner must show that common ownership
was necessary to keep both the newspaper and TV station afloat
financially, she said.
   Lawrence Kessler, general counsel for Murdoch's News America
Publishing Inc., acknowledged that the Herald could survive without
the TV station's revenues, but he said the company will argue that
the issue is fairness.
   ``The hardship would be if we were forced to dispose of another
asset and then the FCC modified the rule (to allow common
ownership), that would be a hardship in and of itself,'' he said.
   Kessler noted FCC precedents for granting further time for
Murdoch. The commission last year granted Capital Cities-ABC Inc.
and General Electric Co. waivers of orders to sell radio stations
while it decides whether to eliminate the cross-ownership rule
barring common ownership of radio and TV stations in the same city.
   Murdoch received temporary waivers from the FCC's
cross-ownership rule after he bought the Boston TV station and New
York station WNYW-TV in 1986. He was given until March 6 to sell
either WNYW or the New York Post, and June 30 to sell WFXT or the
Boston Herald.
   Murdoch had been widely expected to request extensions of his
waivers, but Sens. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., and Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., cut short that option. Late last year, they slipped
through Congress a measure prohibiting the FCC from extending any
outstanding waivers. The measure also forbids the agency from
considering any changes in the rule.
   In a 2-1 decision Tuesday, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Washington ruled that the law is unconstitutional because it
targeted a specific individual for no legitimate purpose.
   Though the ruling opens the possibility that Murdoch could keep
both Boston properties at least temporarily, it won't affect the
New York Post, since he sold the newspaper earlier this month for
$37 million to real estate developer Peter Kalikow.
   Murdoch and others had said the ban by Congress was an attempt
to silence his newspapers' criticism of Kennedy. Kennedy and
Hollings, however, said they were merely trying to preserve the
cross-ownership rules and force Murdoch to comply with them.
   The court did not address the section of the provision that
prevents the FCC from considering whether the cross-ownership rule
should be abolished. Therefore, that prohibition remains in effect
until Oct. 1, when the authority under the spending bill to which
the measure was attached expires.
   Kessler said Murdoch will ask the FCC to extend its waiver for
six months after the FCC makes a final decision on its
cross-ownership rule.
   Congress could forestall such a decision by continuing to
prohibit the FCC from considering the issue.
   Whether Congress would do that would depend on ``many factors,
including whether the commission grants Murdoch a waiver,'' said
Tom Cohen, a staff attorney for the Senate Commerce subcommittee on
communications.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1012EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LuckyStores     03-30 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lucky Stores,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Stores Warns Lucky Against Defensive Action</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of American Stores Co. warned
Lucky Stores Inc. against making a ``defensive acqusition'' that
would thwart American's $1.74 billion tender offer for the grocery
store company.
   In a letter to Lucky's board of directors Tuesday, American
Stores Chairman L.S. Skaggs said there have been ``various
reports'' that Lucky may be considering an acquisition that could
interfere with his company's bid.
   American launched a $45-a-share tender offer for the Dublin,
Calif.-based company on Monday and said it was prepared to increase
the offer to $50 a share, or about $1.93 billion, if a friendly
deal can be worked out.
   In a brief statement issued Tuesday, Lucky acknowledged that it
is reviewing both proposals. The company has urged shareholders not
to tender until its directors make a recommendation.
   Skaggs warned in his letter that any attempt by Lucky to
``frustrate the choice given to your shareholders through a
defensive acquisition'' would affect American's willingness to
increase its tender offer to $50 a share.
   He also reiterated that American would consider divesting stores
in order to mitigate any antitrust concerns that may exist.
   The combination of American, the nation's third-largest grocery
retailer with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $15 billion, and
Lucky, the sixth-largest with 480 stores and sales of $7 billion,
could produce the biggest grocery retailer in the nation, analysts
say.
   Documents filed Monday at the Security and Exchange Commission
hinted that American may be positioning itself for a hostile
takeover of Lucky, which resisted such an effort from takeover
specialist Asher Edelman 16 months ago. In return for Edelman
dropping the effort, Lucky agreed to pay his $2.8 million in legal
bills.
   American's SEC documents include a copy of the lawsuit the
company filed Friday in Delaware, which alleges Lucky and its
executive officers have breached their fiduciary duties by
``following a course of conduct directed towards entrenching
themselves in control of Lucky Stores.''
   As part of the defensive measures dating back to the Edelman
bid, Lucky voted senior management lucrative ``golden parachute''
contracts and announced a restructuring plan that included changing
the company's state of incorporation from California to Delaware
and a buy-back of 27 percent of its outstanding shares, the suit
contends.
   The company has noted that its bylaws also contain a ``poison
pill'' anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any
shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of Lucky's stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
