<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LILCOTakeover     03-30 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LILCO Takeover,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LIPA Moves To Take Over LILCO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An offer by the Long Island Power Authority
to purchase Long Island Lighting Co. for $971 million was termed
``ridiculous'' by some industry analysts.
   The state agency's decision to attempt a takeover was made after
a study showed electric rates on Long Island would be 12 percent
lower under a publicly-operated utility.
   LILCO had not yet received the offer, made Tuesday in a letter
to LILCO Chairman William Catacosinos and the utility's board of
directors, said James Lois, a LILCO spokesman.
   ``Should an offer come in we would seriously evaluate it, and
inform our shareholders of the offer,'' Lois said.
   The proposal contemplates that LIPA would acquire through a
friendly merger transaction all 111 million outstanding shares of
LILCO common stock at $8.75 per share.
   LILCO stock was trading at $9 a share, down 12{ cents, in early
New York Stock Exchange trading today.
   The proposal also contemplates that LIPA would acquire all
outstanding shares of LILCO preferred stock.
   Financing is expected to be provided through the sale of
approximately $7.45 billion of long-term, tax-exempt bonds,
officials said.
   It was not known if LIPA's offer, which is open until April 15,
would be considered at a previously scheduled LILCO board meeting
today.
   Gary F. Hovis, a utility analyst at Argus Research Corp., called
the offer ``somewhat funny or ridiculous.''
   ``Obviously, the board of directors of LILCO won't even think
about accepting this offer,'' he said.
   He said it was so far below the true value of the company that
even the less sophisticated investors would quickly reject it if it
were ever approved by the LILCO board and sent to the 118,000
shareholders for a vote.
   ``That is a number that is well below what was generally
expected,'' said analyst Paul Parshley at Donaldson, Lufkin &
Jenrette Securities Inc. ``I would certainly expect the company
would reject the bid and that would begin a bargaining process.''
   He and other analysts said an offer was not likely to be
seriously considered until it reaches at least $12 per share.
   LIPA's nine-member board of trustees met for several hours in
closed session Tuesday before voting to attempt the takeover at
what Mack called the average trading price of LILCO stock over the
past 30 days.
   LIPA is an independent state agency formed in January 1987 by
Gov. Mario Cuomo and the Legislature to decide if a takeover of
LILCO would lower rates. LIPA also is trying to prevent LILCO's
Shoreham nuclear plant from operating.
   The $5.2 billion plant, one of the most expensive ever built, is
currently licensed by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to operate
at up to 5 percent of full power.
   LILCO officials have continued to press for a full operating
license for the plant, contending it is needed to meet the growing
electric demands on Long Island.
   Cuomo and local officials have argued against granting a full
operating license to Shoreham, saying Long Island could not be
safely evacuated in the event of an accident at the plant, located
on the island's north shore about 50 miles from Manhattan.
   Federal law requires that an approved evacuation plan be in
place before a nuclear power plant can be granted a license.
</TEXT>
