<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Kodak-Colorcraft     03-30 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak-Colorcraft,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Completes Deal With Fuqua On Photofinishing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. and Fuqua Industries
Inc., wasting no time after a favorable court decision, announced
today they had merged their photofinishing operations.
   The new company, Qualex Inc., was formed on Tuesday immediately
after the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans reversed a
federal court injunction that had blocked the merger since Feb. 22.
   Qualex combines Fuqua's photofinishing subsidiary, Colorcraft
Corp., with Kodak-owned laboratories, forming the country's largest
wholesale photofinishing operation. It has 94 processing labs
around the country.
   ``We've been delayed in doing this by the lawsuit so we wanted
to get it done as soon as we could. Our target date for having this
merger completed had been Feb. 1,'' said Paul Allen, a Kodak
spokesman.
   The company will be based in Durham, N.C., the home of
Colorcraft. Colorcraft's former chairman, D. Carl Hamill, will
serve as chief executive officer.
   Allen said the Court of Appeals granted permission for the
merger to go ahead immediately, even though a lawsuit trying to
prevent it is still being argued.
   ``The court noted that a merger can always be undone at a later
date,'' Allen said.
   A small wholesale photofinisher, Phototron Corp. of San
Bernardino, Calif., filed the lawsuit to block the merger because
Phototron officials claimed it would create unfair competition in
the market.
   A federal judge in Fort Worth, Texas, where the lawsuit was
filed, issued an injunction Feb. 22 preventing the merger, but that
decision was reversed Tuesday in New Orleans.
   That lawsuit is expected to continue, Allen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
