<HEAD>Wheat Futures Open Higher; Corn, Soybeans Retreat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures opened slightly higher but other
grain and soybean futures opened a little lower today on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat got a boost from news this morning that the Soviet Union
will bid Thursday for 500,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat, analysts
said.
   Acceptance of the bid by the Agriculture Department would
complete a Soviet purchase of 1 million metric tons of wheat
recently offered under the USDA's Export Enhancement Program.
   But the U.S. is likely to offer the Soviets another million
metic tons of subsidized wheat in the near future, said Richard
Loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   Corn and soybean prices retreated on profit-taking ahead of
Thursday's eagerly awaited government reports on spring planting
intentions and grain stocks, Loewy said.
   Soybeans also drifted lower on ideas that arid conditions in an
important Brazilian soybean-growing region probably had not caused
as much crop damage as some had feared, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 1} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.02{ a bushel; corn was { cent to
1 cent lower with May at $2.11 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1}
cents lower with May at $1.62 a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to
1} cents lower with May at $6.48} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .20 cent higher with April at
75.30 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent lower
with March at 82.75 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .20
cent higher with April at 45.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .30 cent lower to .15 cent higher with May at 55.90 cents a
pound.
   Most livestock and meat futures settled lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
