<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MexicoEconomy     03-30 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico Economy,0186</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced that the nation's
economy grew a tiny 1.4 percent last year, recovering from a steep
recession that had hobbled the economy in 1986.
   The office of President Miguel de la Madrid delivered late
Tuesday to the federal legislature its report on the state of the
economy in 1987.
   ``The advances reached with the (government's economic) plan and
its programs were substantial,'' it said.
   The report said non-oil exports soared 24 percent, giving the
nation a surplus of $4.2 billion in the 1987 current account, which
is the broadest measure of a country's trading position. Mexico
recorded a deficit of $1.3 billion in its current account in 1986.
   It said unemployment declined by 3.2 percent last year,
according to its surveys of the nation's 16 major cities.
   Private analysts estimate about 18 percent of the labor force of
25 million is out of work.
   The economy contracted at an inflation-adjusted 4.0 percent in
1986.
   The government previously had reported that inflation soared a
record 159.2 percent last year.
</TEXT>
