<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PlywoodCanada     03-30 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plywood Canada,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Official Calls For Joint Construction Standard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's top trade official
says that the U.S. tariffs on Canadian plywood won't be lowered
until the two countries have developed ``common standards'' that
would allow American-manufactured plywood to be used north of the
border.
   In a letter to Oregon Republican Sen. Bob Packwood, U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter said the administration will propose
that U.S. and Canadian experts from two forest research
laboratories develop and draft construction standards for the use
of plywood in both countries.
   ``Under this scheme, reductions in the U.S. tariff on plywood
and other panel products would not be phased in until we get a
satisfactory solution to the technical trade problems,'' said
Yeutter.
   Packwood told reporters he was optimistic that a joint-standard
could be negotiated.
   ``This ought to solve our plywood problems with Canada,''
Packwood said.
   The proposed U.S.-Canada free trade agreement calls for
elimination of the 20 percent U.S. tariff on Canadian plywood and
the 15 percent tariff on American plywood over a 10-year period.
   But the treaty linked elimination of the tariffs to changes in
the Canadian construction codes.
   Canadians have insisted that American plywood was not sturdy
enough to withstand the harsher climate of Canada, a claim the
American plywood industry has said is unfounded.
   Earlier this month, the Canadian Mortgage and Housing Commission
(CMHC) refused to revise its building code that has essentially
blocked imports of U.S. plywood.
   The government-controlled mortgage authority rejected the
changes without even making a technical review of U.S.-manufactured
plywood.
   Northwest lawmakers, including Packwood, were outraged.
   Oregon is the leading plywood producing state and Washington
ranks No. 4. Together, the two states produce about 40 percent of
the plywood manufactured domestically.
   Yeutter said that he was ``disappointed'' with the CMHC
rejection.
   ``I believe that CMHC's action does not conform with provisions
of the free trade agreement,'' Yeutter wrote. ``My expectations of
CMHC have not been met.''
   Yeutter said that after common standards were developed and
implemented, ``then tariff reductions envisioned in the free trade
agreement could take effect.''
   Packwood said that adoption of joint construction standards
should ensure that U.S.-manufactured plywood will have access to
Canadian markets.
   ``Plywood made in Eugene, Salem or Vancouver, British Columbia,
will all be made to the same standard,'' said Packwood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-MergerWave Adv03   03-30 1123</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Merger Wave, Adv 03,1157</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Merger Wave Continues, But Is It Healthy?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Merger Wave-Boutique</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cash-rich companies have replaced corporate
raiders of the bust-'em-up style on the merger trail, lassoing
businesses that will increase their market share and make long-term
economic sense.
   Takeover activity, often of the hostile variety, has resumed
with a new frenzy as initial jitters about the economy have
subsided in the wake of October's stock market calamity.
   Despite nagging fears that the new wave will further restrict
competition in some industries and leave many businesses awash in
debt, the urge to merge seems ever stronger among companies bent on
raising their standing in the global marketplace.
   Lured by battered stock prices, corporations are shedding their
inhibitions about making overtures that are ``unsolicited,'' a
euphemism for hostile bids.
   Fears that taking the role of aggressor could tarnish the old
corporate image are subsiding along with concerns about the
disruptive effect an unwanted takeover might have on the target
firm's work force _ from top management defections to a sense of
alienation among the rank-and-file.
   Lately, ``it's become respectable for quality corporate buyers
to make unsolicited offers,'' said Michael B. Hoffman, co-director
of mergers and acquisitions at Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``That general respectability is allowing people to come in and
do something they haven't done in the past,'' he said.
   Among the unsolicited offers is American Store Co.'s nearly $2
billion bid for Lucky Stores Inc., a combination that would create
the nation's biggest supermarket chain. Elsewhere in the retail
arena, Campeau Corp. and R.H. Macy & Co. have both bid more than $6
billion for Federated Department Stores Inc.
   Some companies are so intent to jump on the acquisition
bandwagon, they're launching tender offers after a target company
has signed an agreement with another suitor.
   General Electric Corp., which analysts are quick to note has
never pursued an unfriendly deal, launched a $507 million tender
offer for Roper Corp. after the appliance and lawn equipment maker
agreed to be acquired by Whirlpool Corp.
   SmithKline Beckman Corp. went after International Clinical
Laboratories Inc. to beef up its lab network even though the
company already had agreed to be acquired by Corning Glass Works.
   Acquiring another company is a quicker and often cheaper way of
broadening product lines and gaining market share. Instead of
building a factory from the foundation up over the course of
several years, corporations can expand their distribution channels
instantly by snapping up a competitor.
   Even Eastman Kodak Co.'s megapurchase of Sterling Drug Inc. for
$5.1 billion _ the largest completed deal so far this year _ is not
a wild diversification move for the camera maker, some argue.
   Large companies also are aiming to outgun their foreign
counterparts.
   ``Market share is being divided up _ and U.S. companies are
consolidating to meet foreign competition coming in,'' said Robert
Willard, managing director and head of mergers and acqusitions at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   To the extent that companies are leading the effort as opposed
to raiders, the latest wave ``is clearly healthier,'' said Willard,
who noted that the recent combinations not only ``make economic
sense ... but probably at the end of the day there is less
dislocation in terms of employees forming stronger economic units
to be competitive on worldwide basis.''
   But Hoffman said it is ``definitely not clear that these are
somehow better than the mergers of the past.'' It's difficult to
argue whether Campeau or Macy would be an inherently better partner
for Federated, he said.
   Still, an increasing percentage of transactions ``are not
bust-up or junk-bond driven; they appear to be driven by
synergistic ideals,'' said Stephen Fraidin, a partner of Fried,
Frank, Harris, Shriver & Jacobson, a leading
mergers-and-acquisition law firm.
   Changes in tax laws have made the breaking up of companies not
as attractive for raiders who must sell off parts of targets just
to finance the actual acquisition.
   Corporations have an opportunity to display their natural
advantage in winning deals _ namely, they have deep pockets and can
borrow cheaper than raiders relegated to the high-yield but risky
junk-bond markets.
   And there's no question that corporations are in a strong cash
position right now. Buoyed by a weaker dollar that has made
American exports more attractive, corporations' after-tax profits
shot up 8.4 percent in last year to $137.4 billion for the first
increase since 1984, according to Commerce Department figures.
   While the number of takeover deals announced seems to have
slowed, the dollar value has increased steadily. In December, 484
deals were announced for a total dollar value of $16.1 billion. But
the 364 deals announced in February carried a combined price tag of
$32.7 billion.
   Experts say the pace will wear on. ``All the forces in place
that have contributed to the first three months (of 1988 activity)
we see as continuing into the forseeable future,'' said J. Tomilson
Hill, co-head of mergers and acquisitons at Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
   ``Banks are fully prepared to provide a substantial amount of
credit, there's bridge financing from the investment banks,'' and
while there are fewer bargains in terms of stock prices now than a
few months ago, ``prices nevertheless are still on average below
their highs'' he said.
   Ironically, mergers are now providing some support for stocks as
takeover issues dominate the play on an otherwise dull Wall Street.
   On the downside looms the specter of an economy constrained by
too much debt and too little competition.
   In the concrete and construction materials business alone, three
major takeover attempts are under way, two of which are being
spearheaded by foreign firms. Beazer PLC of Britain has made a bid
for Koppers Co.; Brierly Investments Ltd. of New Zealand is seeking
to acquire Calmat Co.; while Moore McCormack Resources Inc. has
rebuffed an offer from Southdown Inc.
   Ultimately, the bill for such combinations will have to be paid.
   ``There's the danger of getting into a situation where companies
are so highly leveraged that it becomes a question whether they can
survive an economic downturn,'' said Jay Lorsch, a professor at
Harvard Business School.
   Some experts criticize restructuring in the face of a takeover
as too short sighted. To fend off a hostile bidder, companies often
take on debt to make themselves less attractive. Or as an
alternative defensive move, companies sell off assets that may be
weak at the moment without considering their long-term potential.
   ``It's like the Hong Kong race track _ everybody's betting on
the short term and not that the earnings of a company will rise''
over the long haul, Lorsch said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 3</NOTE>
