<1ST_LINE>s f BC-MergerWave-Boutique Adv03   03-30 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Merger Wave-Boutique, Adv 03,0466</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Takeover Industry Goes ``Boutique''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Merger Wave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While legions of Wall Streeters have headed for
the unemployment lines since October's market crash, some
high-rolling investment bankers, takeover lawyers and acquisition
hand-holders have shifted into fifth gear.
   ``We've been intensely busy for a long time; now we are,
perhaps, intensely busier,'' said Stephen Fraidin, a partner of
Fried, Frank, Harris, Shriver & Jacobson, a New York law firm that
handles takeovers.
   Some of the more entrepreneurial members of this inner sanctum
have shifted out of old-line establishments altogether to set up
their own shops, otherwise known as ``boutiques.''
   Indeed, some of the hottest talk on Wall Street of late
surrounded the string of defections from First Boston Corp.'s
mergers and acquisitions department. Superstars Bruce Wasserstein
and Joseph R. Perella, who ran the highly successful operation,
announced in February they were leaving to form their own firm,
taking a score of staffers with them.
   ``First Boston was wiped out in that department,'' one Wall
Street insider said. Wasserstein and Perella took the 20 best
people, ``and they are the business,'' he added.
   These boutiques are not merely high-class consulting firms. With
huge pools of international money available from pension funds,
insurance companies and the like, they have access to enough
capital to spin their own deals.
   And boutiques are counting big players as clients. The
Blackstone Group advised Japan's Bridgestone Corp. on its proposed
venture with Firestone Tire & Rubber Co., while Wasserstein,
Perella & Co. is counseling Campeau Corp. in its battle against
R.H. Macy & Co. for Federated Department Stores Inc.
   One senior mergers and acquisitions banker said boutiques have
created ``a second force'' in an industry that has evolved into a
veritable ``oligopoly.''
   ``There are three firms among us that are capturing probably 80
percent of the takeover market,'' he said in reference to Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc., Goldman, Sachs & Co. and Morgan Stanley & Co.
   Boutiques are vying hard for that remaining 20 percent.
   This banker predicted that the recent wave of takeover activity
could push first-quarter profits to record heights at the three
major houses.
   ``Merger activity is carrying over to the results of the overall
firm,'' he said.
   But that may be the very reason boutiques are popping up.
   ``Since the M and A people are on top at the moment, they want
it all for themselves and do not want to carry everybody else. So
they start their own boutiques,'' said Robert Pirie, president of
Rothschild Inc., which has advised Sir James Goldsmith, the
Anglo-French financier.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
