<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Reagan-Superconductor     03-30 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Superconductor,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Seeks Funds for Supercollider</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today urged congressional
approval of his request for $365 million to begin construction of
the superconducting super collider, saying the technology it
represents is ``changing the way we live.''
   ``I know that some people may question the practical
applications of the superconducting super collider,'' the president
said. ``The strange world of subatomic particles, they may think,
will never be more than an arcane interest to a few highly
specialized scientists.''
   ``But the truth is the practical applications of this new
technology are already changing the way we live,'' the president
told a gathering of science students and others in the Rose Garden.
   ``Every time someone turns on his desk computer, makes a phone
call or plays a video game, he is plugging into that mysterious
world of quantum physics,'' Reagan said. ``The superconducting
super collider is the doorway to that new world of quantum change.''
   The superconducting super collider will investigate the origin
and nature of matter by whirling beams of protons into each other
at an energy 20 times greater than is now possible in a
53-mile-around underground tunnel.
   The students in the audience were part of a program established
in 1985 that gives top students from each state an opportunituy to
work for two weeks in the summer at national laboratories in the
Washington area.
   Reagan approved construction of the collider, the world's
largest energy particle accelerator, in January 1987. The
Department of Energy asked for site proposals in April 1987, and 36
of the 43 proposals received were judged qualified.
   The National Academy of Sciences and the National Academy of
Engineering selected eight as the best qualified. The sites were in
Arizona, Colorado, Illinois, Michigan, New York, North Carolina,
Tennessee and Texas.
   Secretary of Energy John S. Herrington is sheduled to recommend
a preferred site in July and the final site is to be chosen in
January after an environmental imnpact study.
   Some scientists oppose the project, saying it would be too
expensive and drain money from more desirable scientific projects.
   However, six Nobel laureates, four of whom were present for the
ceremony, wrote Reagan that the project ``represents America's
commitment to the pursuit of excellence in basic scientific
research.''
   Although Reagan spoke seriously of his dedication to the
project, he opened his remarks with a joke about it.
   ``When I first heard about this place where things go round and
round at great speeds and then crash into each other, I thought
tney were talking about a presidential campaign,'' the president
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
