<1ST_LINE>u r AM-DeadlineFliers Bjt   03-30 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deadline Fliers, Bjt,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fliers Racing To Beat Triple-Mileage Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thursday is the last day to qualify for the big
airlines' triple-mileage programs and travelers have been flocking
to the skies to beat the deadline.
   ``This is their time to strike,'' said Suzanne Jensen, a
spokeswoman for Uniglobe Travel (International) Inc., a large
travel agency franchiser based in Richmond, British Columbia.
   To drum up business in the slow winter months, the major
airlines offered to triple all mileage credits accumulated by
participants in frequent-flier programs this year _ if the member
took at least one round-trip or two one-way flights on that carrier
between by the end of the day Thursday.
   The deadline, coupled with the approach of Easter and school
vacations, seems to have touched off a flying spree _ with many
travelers taking short, relatively cheap flights in order to
qualify for the bonus mileage.
   The rush has mainly caught up ordinary consumers rather than
frequent business travelers, who qualified earlier in the year for
triple credits.
   ``There may be some short hops out there being taken for
qualifying trips,'' said Alan Loflin, a spokesman for Pan Am Corp.
``We were extremely heavy this weekend all over the (Pan Am)
system.''
   He said traffic was especially thick on Pan Am's Northeast
corridor shuttle service and on Pan Am Express _ both short-haul
operations for the international carrier. Pan Am Express serves
about a dozen cities in the Northeast and feeds into the airline's
main hub in New York, while the shuttle links New York, Washington
and Boston.
   Uniglobe's Jensen reported an especially big flurry of business
in the West and Midwest _ with a lot of Western customers booking
short trips from Los Angeles, for example, to Las Vegas, San
Francisco or San Diego.
   Launched at the start of the year by Delta Air Lines, the
triple-mileage marketing weapon was quickly embraced by other major
carriers hoping to bolster business during the first quarter, which
is traditionally the slowest for leisure travel.
   Triple mileage is an extension of the popular frequent-flier
programs, which reward passengers with free tickets or upgrades to
first class after they have flown a set number of miles.
   ``We've had some very heavy passenger loads the past few days,''
said Dan Sheehy, a spokesman for United Airlines. ``It looks like
people are rushing to qualify for triple mileage.''
   United, the nation's largest airline, saw passengers board its
planes in record numbers last weekend on its 400 or so daily
flights out of its hub at Chicago's O'Hare International Airport,
Sheehy reported. Boardings on Friday, Saturday and Sunday ranged
from around 45,000 to more than 49,000 a day _ compared with
United's average rate of 30,000 to 35,000.
   Second-ranked American Airlines had a similar increase in
passenger traffic last weekend, spokeswoman Mary O'Neill said.
   Eastern Airlines also has experienced a ``travel frenzy''
recently, spokeswoman Paula Musto said, citing the twin factors of
Easter and the triple-mileage deadline.
   Observers said most major airlines are reaping the same
last-minute windfall _ with one notable exception. Delta, which
started the triple-mileage competition, did not impose a deadline
for eligibility, spokesman Neil Monroe said.
   Delta's frequent-flier program, including the triple mileage
feature, is also unique in that all tickets must be charged on an
American Express card.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Construction Bjt   03-30 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Construction, Bjt,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Hails Construction Accord; Business Wary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese government hailed the U.S.-Japan
accord on access to Japan's construction market, but Japanese
construction executives expressed wariness about the agreement
Wednesday.
   ``Since this agreement came about when Japanese firms are still
barred from the U.S. public works market, I am dissatisfied,''
Hajime Sako, president of the Japan Federation of Construction
Contractors, said in a statement.
   Washington banned Japanese companies from U.S. public works
projects last year because of Japan's restrictive policies.
   ``It is good that the two countries were able to reach an
agreement,'' Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita told reporters.
   Construction Minister Ihei Ochi said he was satisfied that Japan
had done enough to help American companies take part in Japanese
construction projects, long seen as representing continued closure
of Japan's markets.
   Japan will honor the agreement and with the cooperation of
Japan's construction industry, ``I hope things will go smoothly in
the future,'' Ochi said.
   Japanese and U.S. negotiators agreed Japan will encourage
foreign participation in major public works projects financed by
the Japanese government and other projects carried out by Japanese
companies with funding from both the central and local governments.
   The United States had threatened to invoke a law calling for
retaliation unless negotiations this week produced an accord
allowing U.S. companies to bid on an equal footing with Japanese
firms for hundreds of millions of dollars of work in large public
works projects in Japan.
   Such projects include airports and airport terminals _
particularly the planned Kansai International Airport in western
Japan _ plus conference halls, expressways and bridges.
   Keizo Obuchi, chief cabinet secretary and Takeshita's top aide,
told a press conference the successful conclusion of the Washington
talks was a victory over protectionism, and said he hoped the
agreement will have a ``favorable influence'' over deliberations in
the U.S. Congress on various trade bills.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, construction company stocks were
boosted by the progress of the talks and announcement of the
accord, possibly because investors believed it would lead the
United States to drop restrictions on them.
   Since Monday, Shimizu Construction surged 33 yen to 934 yen
$7.42) per share, while Taisei Corp. rose 22 yen to 969 yen ($7.75)
and Kajima Corp. jumped 40 yen to 1,550 yen ($12.40).
   Japanese construction executives, however, expressed caution.
   Sako said he was happy Japan has been able to prevent U.S.
retaliation, but said it was unavoidable that Japan had to
compromise to bring about a resolution to the deadlock.
   Teruzo Yoshino, president of Shimizu Construction, thanked the
government Wednesday for reaching a conclusion without U.S.
retaliation, but stopped short of endorsing the accord.
   ``From now, I hope the Japanese industry discusses the issue
fully ... to develop a policy,'' Yoshino said in a statement.
   The European Economic Community charged the Japan-U.S. agreement
ignores other countries.
   ``The EC has repeatedly warned against bilateral deals on trade
and public procurement and particularly against this tendency
between Japan and the U.S.,'' said Michael Lake, a counsellor at
the EC delegation in Tokyo.
   ``European firms have shown more practical interest than
American firms in the Kansai airport,'' he said. ``We do not regard
any U.S.-Japan deal as infringing on our rights to pursue our own
interests in this market.''
   A French firm's design was chosen for the Kansai airport's
terminal, and European firms are hoping to follow with actual
construction contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ConstructionContracts     03-30 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Contracts,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Contracts Up 10 Percent in February</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Release at 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for future construction projects
jumped 10 percent in February, recouping January's 8 percent
decline, according to a report published Thursday.
   The survey, by the F.W. Dodge Division of McGraw-Hill
Information Systems Co., estimated the annualized value of all
newly started construction projects in February at $249.7 billion,
the highest level since last October.
   While the February increase was paced by a 14 percent surge in
nonresidential building, the construction information service said
housing and public works also contributed to the advance.
   The gain in nonresidential construction was concentrated in
commercial and industrial buildings, up 32 percent, while
institutional construction projects declined 11 percent.
   F.W. Dodge said its seasonally adjusted index of construction
contracting rose to 159 in February from 145 in January, which was
its lowest level in two years. The index is based on a level of 100
for 1982.
   ``Because construction activity can be notoriously erratic
during the winter months, February's welcome gain in contracting
needs to be paired with January's sharp decline,'' said George A.
Christie, vice president and chief economist for F.W. Dodge.
   Taken together, he said, January and February showed the rate of
new construction contracting to be 5 percent below the fourth
quarter of last year, extending a gentle decline from the peak rate
reached in the third quarter of 1987.
   Contracting for residential buildings rose 9 percent in February
to an annualized value of $120.2 billion, according to the report.
It noted, however, that the improvement was limited to multi-family
housing and hotels and motels, while the single-family sector
showed little change.
   Public works and utility construction in February was valued at
$43.4 billion, up 3 percent from January but 5 percent below the
average level in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
