<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Maxwell     03-30 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Maxwell,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maxwell Communication's Profit Doubles in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC, a group
controlled by British publisher Robert Maxwell, said Wednesday that
its pre-tax profit more than doubled in 1987, boosted by strong
gains in publishing, printing and from property sales.
   The company said its pre-tax profit for the year came to 166
million pounds, or $309 million, compared with 80.3 million pounds,
or $149 million, in 1986.
   At the same time, Maxwell said the company was close to
acquiring an Australian newspaper, the Melbourne Age, from
Australian media group John Fairfax Ltd.
   Maxwell added that he expected to reach and agreement with
Fairfax on the acquisition in two weeks. The Age is part of a
package of properties, which include the British weekly The
Spectator, which Fairfax is offering for sale.
   Maxwell Communication said its profit after taxes also more than
doubled to 134.3 million pounds, or $250 million, from 64.4 million
pounds, or $120 million.
   Sales spurted 91 percent to 884.1 million pounds, or $1.64
billion, from 461.7 million pounds, or $859 million.
   The company didn't break out quarterly or half-year results. It
isn't required to under British law.
</TEXT>
