<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 03,0766</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 3 and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Last Year's Farm Export Rise Could Be a Hopeful Sign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Agriculture Department analysis of last
year's trade situation helps point the direction for U.S. farm
exports in 1988 and beyond, if a year or two can be called the
beginning of a trend.
   Basically, the report showed that the value of agricltural
exports in the 1988 calendar year rose, while imports of
agricultural commodities declined. That resulted in a larger trade
balance in favor of American farmers.
   The periodic report is called FATUS, which stands for Foreign
Agricultural Trade of the United States. It was issued last week by
the department's Economic Research Service.
   A bit of background may be useful.
   One of the quirks of USDA agencies that sometimes confuses as
well as informs is the practice of compiling statistics for
different time periods. There is the fiscal year, which begins each
Oct. 1, and the calender year, which commences on Jan. 1.
   Then there are crop years, which vary according to the
commodity, and the marketing year, which is just as confusing and
can include livestock as well as crops. International trade figures
often are reported for years beginning on July 1.
   Under most circumstances, the most popular USDA farm trade
figures are those for the fiscal year running fr     4.5  0  
