<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     03-30 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0346</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices turned downward today after an
early advance faded.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points
in early trading, was down 9.12 at 1,989.22 by 2 p.m. today on Wall
Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 610 up, 766 down and
508 unchanged.
   Analysts noted that the dollar had shown signs of steadying in
foreign exchange. That sparked a rebound in bond prices in
Tuesday's activity.
   Wall Streeters were generally pleased with the government's
report Tuesday that the index of leading economic indicators rose
0.9 percent in February.
   That was taken as a signal that the economy was neither weak nor
dangerously strong.
   The market's advance tailed off as the session passed, however.
Brokers said traders seemed reluctant to expand their holdings with
a long holiday weekend approaching.
   The market will be closed in observance of Good Friday, when the
government is scheduled to report on the employment situation for
March.
   Technology stocks were notably weak. Digital Equipment fell 3\
to 102[; International Business Machines 1 to 104~, and Apple
Computer 2 to 39 in the over-the-countyer market.
   Texaco rose ] to 48] on top of a 3\-point jump Tuesday, when
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. said it would seek regulatory
clearance to buy as much as 15 percent of the company's stock.
   J.C. Penney added 1 to 48\. The company raised its quarterly
dividend from 37 cents a share to 50 cents a share.
   Fur Vault, traded on the American Stock Exchange, fell ] to 2\.
The company reported sharply lower quarterly earnings and suspended
its dividend.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.48 to 146.74. At the Amex, the market value index was off .16 at
294.17.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 111.28 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
