<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1425EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ThePound Bjt   03-30 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-The Pound, Bjt,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The `Renaissance' Pound Surges To Two-year Peak</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British pound has jumped to its highest level
in two years, boosted by a strong economy, Britain's relatively
high interest rates and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
unrelenting grip on inflation.
   Sterling held relatively steady for 12 months and was uncapped
when the Conservative government decided earlier this month to ease
central bank intervention and allow the pound to rise above a
previous target against the West German mark.
   ``It is a currency renaissance,'' said Keith Skeoch, chief
economist at the London investment firm James Capel and Co. ``What
we're beginning to see is the transition of sterling from being one
of the weaker brethren among the international currencies to one of
the stronger.''
   Jonathan Lopatin, vice president for foreign exchange dealing at
Goldman Sachs & Co. in London, said, ``The authorities decided to
allow sterling exchange rates to rise.''
   The Bank of England's index measuring the pound's trade-weighted
value against 17 currencies finished at 77.7 on Wednesday,
unchanged from Tuesday, when it rose 0.6 point to reach its highest
level since closing at 78 on Jan. 16, 1986.
   On Wednesday, the pound rose to $1.8790 from $1.8705, and to
3.1225 West German marks from 3.1069 marks.
   In the past seven years, the pound has hit a low of $1.0470, in
February 1985, and a high of $2.4525 in November 1980.
   Until taking the rein off the pound this month, the government,
through the Bank of England's sale of pounds and purchase of West
German marks, had closely guarded a rate of 3 marks. It also has
controlled sterling by signaling changes in interest rates.
   ``But that ceiling was lifted because there was a great deal of
market pressure pushing sterling up. At that rate, more people
wanted to buy it than sell it,'' Lopatin said.
   ``It certainly has been made clear in the eye of the foreign
exchange market and investors that the government is more concerned
about the threat of inflation than they are at holding the exchange
rate at any particular level.''
   Mrs. Thatcher's priority has been to control inflation, now
running at an annual rate of 3.3 percent compared with a 18 percent
in 1980.
   That means the government is less likely to cut interest rates
further for fear of reigniting inflation.
   Britain's high interest rates, compared with the rates of other
major industrialized nations, make pound-denominated investments
more attractive and create demand for sterling.
   The British commercial banks' base lending rate _ a benchmark
interest rate _ stands at 8.5 percent.
   The strong economy, however, is the underlying factor pushing up
the pound.
   Britain's gross domestic product _ its total output of goods and
services _ is expected to grow 3 percent in 1988, faster than any
of its major trading partners except Japan. That will be the
economy's seventh consecutive year of expansion.
   Other pro-pound factors are a fiscal budget surplus, the first
in nearly 20 years, announced March 15, political stability and a
Conservative government.
   ``They all are the hallmarks of a basically hard currency,''
Skeoch said.
   The trade deficit is forecast to widen sharply with the strong
currency, which can hurt exports and encourage imports.
   On Tuesday, the pound also was boosted by rumors that Chancellor
of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson had resigned, even though the
Treasury issued a denial, and by a later statement from Mrs.
Thatcher that she and her finance minister weren't split on policy.
   The pound would be allowed to find its own level under a new
chancellor, dealers first speculated. Then they decided the
authorities won't step in to restrain the pound, even if he stayed.
   ``Both Mr. Lawson and I put downward pressure on inflation as
top-most priority. Both of us think interest rate stability can be
very useful to industry,'' Mrs. Thatcher said in response to a
question in the House of Commons.
   Mrs. Thatcher and Lawson have expressed differing views in
recent weeks _ he for restraining the pound and she being more
concerned about inflation.
   Meanwhile, the analysts expect the pound to continue to move
upward. Skeoch said he expected the pound to reach 3.20 marks
within a few months and $2.04 later in the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
