<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Rover     03-30 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Rover ,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Legislators Attack Plan for Government Aid to Rover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political opponents attacked Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's plan to inject 800 million pounds into
automaker Rover Group PLC when the government sells it off, calling
it an amazing giveaway.
   The Rover plan, criticized Tuesday in Parliament, would come to
the aid of the automaker with the equivalent of $1.49 billion in
government funds.
   The plan, part of Mrs. Thatcher's huge and ongoing privatization
program, also is likely to create controversy in the European
Economic Community's executive Commission, without whose approval
the plan cannot proceed.
   British Aerospace PLC announced Tuesday that it had reached an
agreement to acquire Rover from the government for 150 million
pounds, or about $279 million, a cheaper price than had been
expected. The government would make the cash injection to reduce
Rover's debt, British Aerospace said.
   Labor Party legislator Bryan Gould, who serves as a spokesman on
industrial issues for the opposition party, said the British
Aerospace announcement was astonishing and attacked the plan as an
``Easter giveaway.''
   Lord Williams, also a member of the opposition, said British
Aerospace shareholders ``will no doubt think Christmas has come
rather early this year.''
   Gould claimed that the government was paying British Aerospace
650 million pounds, enough to raise the government's child benefit
by 1 pound a week, ``to persuade them to walk away with net assets
worth 770 million'' pounds.
   Gould demanded a full House of Commons debate on the issue after
the Easter recess.
   Trade Secretary Lord Young countered: ``This is not a knock-down
price,'' and described the package as ``the deal of the decade.''
   Rover Chairman Graham Day said the sale was good for the company
and its employees.
   British Aerospace Chairman Roland Smith promised to develop the
combined company and ``not to destroy it.''
   One condition the government has attached to the Rover sale is
that British Aerospace must not dispose of any of the business
within five years.
   The Conservative Party's large majority in the House of Commons
guarantees passage of Mrs. Thatcher's policies.
   Rover Group, which is made up of automaker Austin Rover and Land
Rover, which produces utility vehicles, recently announced a 1987
profit before taxes of 27.9 million pounds, or about $52 million.
That compared with a loss of 355.6 million pounds, or around $661
million, in 1986.
   Mrs. Thatcher has sold 16.5 billion pounds worth of state-owned
companies since she came to power in 1979 as part of her
``capitalist revolution.'' Her goals have been to make those
companies more competitive as well as to get more shares into the
hands of the British public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1539EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LaborLaws     03-30 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Labor Laws,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Committee Hears Charge of Union-Busting Tactics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies are increasingly demanding
concessionary contracts as a tactic for provoking strikes in an
effort to drive unions out of their plants, a House subcommittee
was told Wednesday.
   Labor leaders for now are combatting the effort by instructing
their members to keep working after a contract expires and wages
and benefits are unilaterally cut by an employer.
   But through an orchestrated series of congressional hearings,
they also are trying to build a case for lauching another attempt
to change the nation's labor laws if a Democrat is elected
president next fall so that it would be more difficult from
companies to hire strikebreakers.
   Local union officials at paper, chemical and meatpacking plants
complained Wednesday to a sympathetic subcommittee of the House
Education and Labor Committee that the National Labor Relations Act
has been turned againt them.
   Rep. William Clay, D-Mo., chairman of the committee's
labor-management relations subcommittee, said the growing
anti-union tactics adopted by employers and approved by the
National Labor Relations Board threatens the future of collective
bargaining.
   ``What was once the workers' weapon of last resort _ the strike
_ is now being used as a tool by employers to terminate bargaining
relationships,'' Clay said. ``Employers are purposely adopting
bargaining positions intended to drive their workers out on the
picket line.''
   Ken Tritz, president of a Paperworkers Union local in Missoula,
Mont., said its members have been working at a Stone Container
Corp. paper mill the past seven months without a contract after the
company tried to provoke a strike.
   As a result, he said, his members have been losing premium,
vacation and holiday pay incentives as well as some of the fringe
benefits they formerly had. He estimated the lost wages and
benefits for each worker at about $7,000 a year.
   ``The company was so convinced that it would succeed in
provoking a strike and breaking a strike ... that it prepared a
manual for strikebreakers,'' Tritz said. ``We chose to work without
a contract at this time because the alternatives were even more
obnoxious. Would you rather be shot or hung? Some choice.''
   No Stone Container officials testified at Tuesday's hearing. But
a vice president of another paper company locked in a lengthy
strike at three plants with the Paperworkers Union testifed that
union officials and their members were repeatedly warned that
replacements for them would be hired.
   ``Competition _ both domestic and foreign _ is real, serious and
does not allow a labor strike `time out,''' said John Nevin, a vice
president of International Paper Co. ``If we are not producing, one
of our competitors will gladly take our place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1543EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AluminumRecycling     03-30 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aluminum Recycling,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reynolds Metals Expanding Recycling Network</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reynolds Metals Co., celebrating the 20th
anniversary of the first aluminum can recycling, said Wednesday it
is expanding its network of company-operated recylcing
installations.
   More than 650 units will be operating by the middle of the year,
compared with about 500 last year and about 600 now, company
officials said at a news conference.
   Since Reynolds began buying used cans in Los Angeles in 1968,
the first in the industry to do so, it has bought 88 billion cans
to melt into aluminum ingots in its furnaces.
   The industry has bought 270 billion cans, the company estimates,
and is recycling about half of current production. Reynolds itself
is recycling more than 100 percent of can production _ it buys more
cans than it sells.
   Scrap aluminum is the cheapest source of raw material, in part
because aluminum manufacture is energy-intensive. It takes 6.5
kilowatt-hours of electricity to make a can from ore and only about
5 percent of that energy to make a can from scrap.
   Reynolds started out paying 8 cents per pound. The price
fluctuates according to the world market, and currently Reynolds
pays 42 cents to 46 cents for a pound of cans, about 26 cans, or
1.6 cents to 1.8 cents per can.
   A brewer or other bottler pays about 7.5 cents for a can with a
label printed on it.
   Reynolds estimates the handling costs double that before the
metal is in a form equivalent to what would result from smelting
the ore. At that price, scrap-derived aluminum is still cheaper
than ore-derived, but the company declines to release exact figures.
   Prices have been rising recently, and aluminum trades on the
London Metal Exchange at about $1.31 a pound in the form of 19\-ton
ingots.
   Can production is rising at better than a 6 percent annual rate,
by about 5 billion cans a year. William O. Bourke, Reynolds'
president and chief executive officer, said the company believes 80
percent can be recycled by the year 2000 as more and more cities
turn to recycling programs to ease thir waste-handling problems and
the shortage of landfill space.
   But he opposed as ``not cost-effective'' the so-called ``bottle
bills'' that some states have enacted to require refundable
deposits on beverage containers.
   Manufacturers of competing containers ``should make it possible
for people to return the bottles for cash,'' he said. But he
conceded that those companies would find it difficult since their
materials are not as valuable as scrap aluminum.
   Reynolds spokesman Bob Shaffer said later the company opposed
bottle bills also to retain the good will of its bottler customers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880330-0307 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1510EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-30 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Close Higher; Corn, Soybeans Retreat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures closed slightly higher Wednesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade while corn and soybean prices retreated
in light trading.
   Wheat was supported by expectations that the Soviet Union would
bid Thursday for 500,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat, analysts said.
Acceptance of the bid by the Agriculture Department would complete
a Soviet purchase of 1 million metric tons of wheat recently
offered under the USDA's Export Enhancement Program.
   The slight downward movement of soybeans and the other grains
reflected position-evening by traders ahead of the USDA's Thursday
afternoon reports on spring planting intentions and U.S. grain
stocks, said Joel Karlin, research analyst for Research Department
Inc. in Chicago.
   ``There wasn't a whole lot of activity,'' he said. ``Everybody's
sitting on their hands before the reports.''
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.02 a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 2\ cents lower with May at $2.09\ a bushel; oats were 3 cents to
4 cents lower with May at $1.59} a bushel; soybeans were 3} cents
lower to } cent higher with May at $6.50 a bushel.
</TEXT>
