<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 1541EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Dumping 1stLd-Writethru   03-30 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Dumping, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0144,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Automaker Group's Study Shows Japanese Dumping Small Trucks,
Causing Injury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after graf 15 pvs: If the; picks up graf
16 pvs: The MVMA</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Japanese automakers have been dumping small
trucks on the U.S. market, costing U.S. workers jobs and the U.S.
auto industry $500 million in lost wages, sales and profits, a
study released Wednesday claimed.
   The 42-page study was commissioned by the U.S. Motor Vehicle
Manufacturers Association on behalf of General Motors Corp., Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
   ``The study analysts concluded that the effect of this dumping
margin was something on the order of 140,000 lost units of
production to U.S. manufacturers,'' said MVMA President Thomas
Hanna.
   The investigation, by the Washington, D.C. law firm Wilmer,
Cutler & Pickering, found that the five Japanese companies are
selling compact pickup trucks for 10 percent to 48 percent less in
the United States than they charge in their Japanese home market.
   Dumping is illegal under trade agreements between the United
States and its foreign partners. The companies charged with dumping
by the MVMA are Toyota Motor Corp., Nissan Motor Co., Mazda Motor
Corp., Isuzu Motor Co. and Mitsubishi Motors Corp.
   Toyota immediately denied the charges in statement by Robert
McCurry, senior vice president of Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A.
   ``Any assertions that Japanese compact trucks are injuring or
threatening to injure the U.S. industry ring hollow,'' McCurry
said. ``First, U.S. producers are enjoying their greatest success
in history, collectively continuing to set records for sales and
profits.
   ``Second, Japanese truck sales continue to decline and presently
represent the smallest share of the U.S. market since compact
trucks were introduced by the Japanese,'' he said.
   McCurry has been the most outspoken Japanese auto company
executive in denying charges leveled this year, particularly by
Chrysler Corp. executives.
   In previous defenses, McCurry and executives for other Japanese
auto companies have said that the strength of the Japanese yen
against other currencies has made it cheaper for them to buy raw
materials.
   In addition, Japanese automakers have worked aggressively to cut
production costs, they said.
   In a letter accompanying the study, which was hand-delivered to
Commerce Secretary William Verity's office Tuesday afternoon, the
MVMA asked that the U.S. government begin negotiating with the
Japanese government to end the dumping.
   However, Claire Buchan, a Commerce Department spokeswoman, said
the U.S. government has only initiated a dumping investigation
once, in a semi-conductor case.
   In the vast majority of dumping cases, she said, it is up to the
U.S. industry involved to file petitions with the Commerce
Department and the International Trade Commission.
   If the two agencies find dumping has occurred and has injured a
U.S. industry, then the government assesses a duty on the imported
product that is equal to the difference between the prices charged
here and in the product's home market.
   John Greenwald, an attorney with the firm that conducted the
study, said negotiations between the two countries would eliminate
the need for lengthy and costly litigation involved in filing the
petitions.
   ``The white paper was prepared ... in hopes they would go to
Japanese government and say dumping is causing us problems, not
only in compact pickups but in other products, and preventing the
exchange-rate realignment from curing the trade deficit,''
Greenwald said.
   Automotive products account for about half of the nearly $60
billion U.S. trade deficit with Japan. Greenwald said continued
dumping and denials of dumping would push the value of the dollar
down further against the yen.
   The MVMA study found the truck dumping prevented U.S. makers
from fully using factory space, from moving car workers to truck
production jobs instead of laying them off or from earning healthy
returns on production and sales of small pickups.
   It estimated the cost to the U.S. auto industry and its workers
at $500 million in lost wages, profits and sales.
   For example, according to the study, Toyota charges $3,988 at
the factory for a small pickup destined for the U.S. market and
$5,313 for the same truck destined for sale in its home market.
   The study's authors wrote that when the Japanese yen began to
appreciate against the dollar two years ago, the Japanese producers
lost the price advantage that had enabled them to undersell
American makers.
   ``Faced with the choice between surrendering the gains in import
levels or dumping, they decided to dump,'' the study said.
   The authors also called Japanese makers' response that the
dumping has caused no harm ``absurd.''
</TEXT>
