<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Kodak-Colorcraft     03-30 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak-Colorcraft,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Goes Through With Photofinishing Merger Despite Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Bussiness Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. and Fuqua Industries
Inc. said Wednesday they had combined their photofinishing
operations, although a lawsuit challenging the merger is still
being argued.
   Kodak and the Atlanta-based Fuqua wasted no time in completing
the deal Tuesday after the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New
Orleans reversed a lower court's injunction that had blocked the
merger since Feb. 22.
   Qualex Inc. combines Fuqua's photofinishing subsidiary,
Colorcraft Corp., with Kodak-owned laboratories, to form the
country's largest wholesale photofinishing operation. It has 94
processing labs around the country.
   Paul Allen, a Kodak spokesman, said the target date for the
merger had been Feb. 1.
   The Court of Appeals decided that Phototron Corp., a small San
Bernardino, Calif.-based photofinisher, had no right to try to
block the merger, although it may continue pursuing its lawsuit,
Allen said.
   Phototron sued Kodak over the photo giant's Colorwatch
photofinishing system, claiming it violates antitrust laws because
it is forcing non-Colorwatch processing labs out of business, said
Joseph Alioto, a Photron lawyer.
   Alioto said Phototron is seeking between $100 million and $150
million in damages because of Colorwatch. The merger, he said, will
just increase that range.
   Nonetheless, Alioto said Wednesday that he plans to ask the
Supreme Court to issue a temporary injunction preventing the merger
until he can file a request for the court to consider the matter.
   ``As far as we're concerned, the Supreme Court should get a look
at this thing prior to the scrambling of the eggs,'' Alioto said.
   As far as Kodak and Fuqua are concerned, the eggs have already
been scrambled.
   The company will be based in Durham, N.C., the home of
Colorcraft, and Colorcraft's former chairman, D. Carl Hamill, will
serve as chief executive officer.
   The lawsuit filed by Phototron is being heard in U.S. District
Court in Fort Worth, Texas, and is expected to continue regardless
of the status of the injunction blocking the merger.
</TEXT>
