<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0513</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An afternoon round of selling sent stock prices
lower Wednesday after an early advance faltered.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points
in the early going, finished with a 20.22-point loss at 1,978.12.
That marked its lowest close since it stood at 1,962.04 on Feb. 11.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 in the
daily tally on the New York Stock Exchange, with 571 up, 917 down
and 477 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 151.81 million shares, against 152.69
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index fell
1.00 to 146.22.
   Analysts noted that the dollar had shown signs of steadying in
foreign exchange, which sparked a rebound in bond prices in
Tuesday's activity.
   Wall Streeters were generally pleased with the government's
report Tuesday that the index of leading economic indicators rose
0.9 percent in February. That was taken as a signal that the
economy was neither slumping nor dangerously strong.
   The market weakened as the session passed, however. Brokers said
traders seemed reluctant to hold onto big positions with a long
holiday weekend approaching.
   The market will be closed in observance of Good Friday. The
Labor Department is scheduled to report on the employment situation
for March that day, but stock and bond traders will have to wait
until Monday to respond to it should it contain any surprises.
   Technology stocks were notably weak. Digital Equipment fell 2|
to 102}; International Business Machines } to 105[, and Apple
Computer 1{ to 39{ in the over-the-counter market.
   Losers elsewhere among the blue chip and glamor stocks included
Merck, down 2{ at 157{; General Electric, down ~ at 40\; American
Telephone & Telegraph, down ] at 26{, and DuPont, down 1] at 79~.
   Texaco led the active list, off \ at 47} on turnover of nearly 3
million shares. The stock jumped 3\ points Tuesday, when Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. said it would seek regulatory clearance to buy
as much as 15 percent of the the shares.
   J.C. Penney added 1 to 48\. The company raised its quarterly
dividend from 37 cents a share to 50 cents a share.
   Fur Vault, traded on the American Stock Exchange, fell ] to 2\.
The company reported sharply lower quarterly earnings and suspended
its dividend.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $16.34 billion, or 0.63
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 181.72 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 2.33 to 299.37,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 2.00 at 258.07.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped 1.18 to 371.38. At the Amex, the market value index closed
at 293.67, off .66.
</TEXT>
