<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Roper     03-30 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roper,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Won't Block GE Bid For Roper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission has decided
not to intervene in General Electric Co.'s bid to acquire Roper
Corp., GE said in a brief statement Wednesday.
   GE is battling with Whirlpool Corp. for control of Roper, an
Augusta, Ga.-based appliance maker.
   GE's sweetened $54-a-share tender offer is valued at $507
million; Whirlpool is offering $470 million, or $50 a share.
   Roper's directors initially supported the Whirlpool offer, but
Tuesday urged stockholders to accept the GE offer.
   GE said in its statement that the FTC had decided not to block a
GE-Roper combination because of antitrust concerns.
   Roper employs about 4,750 people, 3,000 of them in four Georgia
plants. In addition to electric and gas appliances, the company
manufactures tillers, lawn mowers and lawn and garden tractors. Its
customers include Sears Roebuck & Co., the nation's largest
retailer.
   It also manufactures some gas ranges for GE, and the
Fairfield-based company has said its interest in Roper stems from
that association.
</TEXT>
