<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-30 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0832</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Futures Soar For Second Day On Strong Demand Prospects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices soared Wednesday for the second
consecutive session on the New York Mercantile Exchange on rumors
of increased Japanese buying and an improving economic outlook.
   On other markets, copper and precious metals futures advanced;
energy futures were higher; livestock and meat prices retreated;
grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index futures fell back.
   Platinum settled $12.10 a troy ounce to $13.80 an ounce higher
on the Nymex with the contract for delivery in April at $532.50 an
ounce.
   Platinum prices have gained about $75 a troy ounce in the past
two months as economic data have increasingly dispelled fears of a
recession and pointed toward higher inflation.
   Gold prices have also advanced on inflation concerns but
platinum has an edge because of its strong industrial-use
component, analysts said.
   Although there was no fresh positive economic news on Wednesday,
rumors that Japanese firms planned to increase their purchases of
platinum gave the market a boost, said Stephen W. Platt, an analyst
in Chicago with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Heightened racial tensions in South Africa, the source of most
of the refined platinum on the market, also underpinned the rise in
prices, Platt said.
   Copper futures also posted strong gains Wednesday on New York's
Commodity Exchange, with the April contract settling 3.95 cents
higher at $1.0795 a pound.
   A sustained rally in industrial-metals prices likely would be
perceived as inflationary, which could push gold and silver prices
higher as well, said analyst Craig Sloane of Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co.
   On the Comex, gold settled $1.50 to $2.20 higher with April at
$457.80 a troy ounce; silver was 4.7 cents to 5.5 cents higher with
April at $6.757 a troy ounce.
   Unleaded gasoline led energy futures prices higher on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   The buying stemmed from a strong increase in demand reflected by
Tuesday's weekly American Petroleum Institute report showing a
4.22-million-barrel drawdown in gasoline stocks to 230 million
barrels.
   ``That's 15.6 million barrels behind last year,'' said Andrew
Lebow, an analyst in New York with E.D.& F. Man International
Futures Inc. ``We're seeing very strong demand for gasoline and
that seems to be dragging the other markets up.''
   Lebow said higher speed limits have resulted in greater
consumption of gasoline. A sharp increase in wholesale demand in
the past two weeks may have reflected dealer stockpiling ahead of
the Easter-Passover weekend, he said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 11 cents
higher with May at $17.08 a barrel; heating oil was .32 cent to .45
cent higher with April at 48.60 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .11 cent to .53 cent higher with April at 48.65 cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange on
fears that consumer demand for beef will drop when recent price
increases in the cash cattle market reach grocery stores in the
form of higher beef prices, said Chuck Levitt, an analyst in
Chicago with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Pork futures prices fell as traders squared their positions
ahead of Thursday afternoon's 10-state hogs and pigs report from
the Agriculture Department, he said.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .62 cent lower with April at 75
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .78 cent lower with
March at 82.75 cents a pound; hogs were .58 cent lower to .07 cent
higher with April at 45.35 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
unchanged to .28 cent lower with May at 55.90 cents a pound.
   Wheat settled slightly higher on the Chicago Board of Trade
while corn and soybean prices retreated in light trading.
   Wheat was supported by expectations that the Soviet Union would
bid Thursday for 500,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat, analysts said.
Acceptance of the bid by the USDA would complete a Soviet purchase
of 1 million metric tons of wheat it was recently offered under the
USDA's Export Enhancement Program.
   The slight downward movement of soybeans and the other grains
reflected position-evening ahead of the USDA's Thursday afternoon
reports on spring planting intentions and U.S. grain stocks, said
Joel Karlin, research analyst for Research Department Inc. in
Chicago.
   Wheat settled { cent to 1\ cents higher with May at $3.02\ a
bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 2 cents lower with May at $2.09{ a
bushel; oats were 3 cents to 3} cents lower with May at $1.60 a
bushel; soybeans were 3 cents lower to { cent higher with May at
$6.49 a bushel.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 1.7 points lower at 258.25. The underlying
spot index closed at 258.07, off 2 points.
</TEXT>
