<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LeaseSale     03-30 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lease Sale,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds To Open Bids On 3 Million Acres Of Offshore Oil Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spurred by greatly reduced minimum prices, 84
oil companies bid almost $593 million dollars Wednesday for leases
of federal waters in the Gulf of Mexico.
   Successful high bids totalled $404.6 million, according to
Eileen Angelico, spokeswoman for the Minerals Management Service of
the Interior Department.
   Atlantic Richfield Co. submitted the highest bid of any of the
companies _ $18.2 million for a single 5,000-acre block, identified
as West Cameron Block 248.
   Shell Offshore submitted the largest number of bids, 250, said
Angelico.
   Angelico said 931 bids on 684 different tracts had been
submitted for Wednesday's bid opening. A breakdown of how many
tracts were leased to each successful bidder was unavailable
Wednesday afternoon, she said.
   At a similar lease sale a year ago, about 300 bids were
received. Angelico the increase in bids was probably due in large
part to the Interior Department's drastic drop in the minimum price
per acre _ from $150 to $25.
   ``We think that helped the number of bids,'' said Angelico.
``One thing it did was provide an opportunity for more small
companies to compete in the sale.''
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel said last month that the minimum
bid was dropped to stimulate interest in the lease sale during a
period of low oil prices.
   The lease sale was announced in February, when 6,265 unleased
blocks _ each about 5,000 acres _ went up for sale. The blocks are
anywhere from three miles to 220 miles offshore, Angelico said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
