<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Southland     03-30 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Southland,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southland, Old And New, Reports Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southland Corp., the parent company of 7-Eleven
convenience stores, on Wednesday reported a net loss of around $59
million for 1987 because of interest expenses and other costs
related to its leveraged buyout.
   However, the company said that in the seven months prior to
going private it earned $90.1 million on revenues of $4.9 billion.
Southland said it lost $149.7 million in the first five months of
its new operating structure.
   In 1986, Southland earned $200.4 million on revenues of $7.8
billion.
   ``Southland's operating performance for the year was quite
strong, especially considering that the company undertook the most
extensive reorganization and cost-reduction program in its history
during the fourth quarter,'' said Jere W. Thompson, Southland
president and chief executive officer.
   In December, Southland completed its $4.9 billion leveraged
buyout by merging with JT Acquisition Corp., an affiliate of the
Thompson Co., the investment firm of the founding family.
   In a leveraged buyout, a company is bought primarily with
borrowed funds that are repaid with funds generated by the acquired
company's operations or through asset sales.
   Southland owns about 7,000 7-Eleven stores and is the nation's
largest independent gasoline retailer with 50 percent interest in
Citgo Petroleum Corp.
   In reporting 1987 earnings, Southland divided the seven months
preceding the company's buyout and merger activities from the five
months at the end of the year.
   The company warned a clear comparison between the two earnings
periods is impossible because of the changed structure and
different accounting bases.
   Southland said it does not expect to report a net profit ``for
some time'' because of interest costs to service the LBO-related
debt and other factors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
