<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FirstRepublicBank-Investor     03-30 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First RepublicBank-Investor,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investor Files Class Action Suit Against First RepublicBank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York man is suing First RepublicBank Corp.,
accusing the financially troubled bank holding company of financial
misrepresentation, an attorney said Wednesday.
   Attorneys for Martin Theodores, a New York investor, filed the
suit in federal district court in Dallas on Tuesday.
   In the class action suit, Theodores seeks compensatory and
punitive damages, said James Malone, attorney in the Haverford, Pa.
firm of Greenfield and Chimicles, which is representing Theodores.
   Malone said the suit claims First RepublicBank inflated and
misstated the collectability and security of its assets.
   ``That has an overall effect of making the bank's balance sheets
and statements look better than they are,'' Malone said.
   Theodores' investment in First RepublicBank, which involved
about $5,000 to $10,000 in bonds, shrank as the company posted a
$656.8 million loss last year. But Malone says it is too early to
tell how much in damages will be sought.
   First RepublicBank had no comment on the suit and would not
discuss pending litigation, said spokesman Joe Bowles.
   First RepublicBank received a $1 billion loan from the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. earlier this month after asking the federal
insuror for advice on restructuring.
</TEXT>
