<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 2259EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlliedSignal     03-30 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allied Signal,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allied Signal Sells Three Units To Concentrate On Aircraft
Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied Signal Aerospace Company
announced Wednesday it has completed the consolidation of its
Bendix and Garrett units and will sell three of its divisions to
focus on commercial and military aircraft contracts.
   The company, a unit of Allied-Signal Inc., also announced that
its streamlining efforts in the past year have cut about 2,000
jobs, including 200 administrative posts.
   The company, based in Morris Township, N.J., is going to sell
its Environmental Systems Division of Towson, Md; Fluid Power
Division of Utica, N.Y.; and Oceanics Division of Sylmar, Calif.
   The combined annual sales of the businesses are about $200
million, about four percent of the company's total sales.
   Allied-Signal Inc. runs businesses in aerospace, automotive
products and engineered materials.
   ``These actions will consolidate the company's efforts in those
markets where we are established leaders,'' said Robert L. Kirk,
chairman and chief executive officer of Allied Aerospace.
   ``One half of our sales will continue to come from the military
market, with the other 50 percent from commercial customers,'' Kirk
said.
</TEXT>
