<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 2308EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ContinentalTrial     03-30 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Trial,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Witnesses Say Penn Square Banker Broke Lending Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Penn Square Bank moved toward its 1982
collapse, top officials seemed bent on expanding its energy-loan
portfolio in a bid for growth that had ``no rhyme or reason,'' a
former vice president testified Wednesday.
   ``It appeared to be unrestrained growth for growth's sake,''
John Baldwin of Oklahoma City told a U.S. District Court jury.
   Baldwin's testimony focused on William Patterson, 37, who was in
charge of Penn Square energy loans when the Oklahoma City bank went
under.
   Patterson is one of three men being tried on charges of improper
loan activity that may have played a part in the near-collapse of
Chicago-based Continental Illinois National Bank & Trust Co. in
1984.
   All have pleaded innocent.
   Federal officials have said Continental participated with Penn
Square in more than $1 billion in uncollectible loans _ most of
them energy loans. The Chicago bank was saved from collapse in 1984
by a $4.5 billion federal bailout.
   Baldwin testified Wednesday at Patterson should have been aware
of the bank's agreement not to sell off parts of loans that had
been questioned by federal bank examiners.
   Patterson violated the pact in 1982 by taking part in the sale
of at least $5 million in problem loans to Continental, he said.
   Baldwin also said Patterson didn't seem to care about
Continental's buying loans that carried inordinate risk, and was
concerned only with dumping the Penn Square energy loans on the
Chicago bank.
   The sales shifted virtually the entire burden of risk for those
loans to Continental.
   Defendant John R. Lytle, 52, of suburban Northfield, who once
headed Continental's Oklahoma oil and gas lending operation, is
accused of buying millions of dollars in poor-quality loans from
Penn Square in exchange for nearly $600,000 in personal, unsecured
loans.
   Patterson is accused of arranging the personal loans, which
prosecutors characterize as kickbacks.
   The third defendant, Tulsa drilling contractor Jere Sturgis, is
accused of making payments to Lytle in an attempt to obtain loans
from Continental.
   Prosecutors hope to show that Lytle knew or should have known he
was buying up problem loans for his bank, and that Patterson knew
he was dumping off a bad product on Lytle.
   Baldwin told the court that while he was at Penn Square, from
July 1981 through its closing, top bank officials seemed intent on
expanding their loans to independent oil and gas concerns.
   ``In my opinion, the bank's ... growth had no rhyme or reason to
it,'' he said, calling Penn Square ``severely understaffed.''
   Lawyers said they expected the trial, which began March 9 before
U.S. District Judge Milton Shadur, will last about three more weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
