<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 2313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HiltonEstate     03-30 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hilton Estate,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barron Hilton Wins Key Ruling in Battle Over Father's Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilton Hotels Corp. chairman and chief
executive Barron Hilton won a major court ruling Wednesday in a
nine-year legal battle over his father's estate.
   The court fight has, in effect, pitted Hilton against several
orders of Catholic nuns devoted to helping the poor who were
singled out as beneficiaries of the estate of the late Conrad
Hilton.
   The California Court of Appeal reversed Los Angeles County
probate judge's decision and concluded that a stock-purchase option
granted by the father to the son covers all 6.78 million of the
estate's shares. That is 27 percent of Hilton Hotel's shares.
   The stock was given to the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation after the
hotel magnate died in 1979 at age 91. The foundation's directors
were instructed by the elder Hilton's will to promote world peace
and ``shelter little children with the umbrella of your charity.''
   Nuns as far away as Italy were beneficiaries of the estate's
largesse.
   The father's will also gave Barron Hilton an option to buy stock
that couldn't be properly held by the foundation.
   The dispute centered on a 1969 Internal Revenue Service rule
prohibiting private foundations from owning more than 20 percent of
any public company.
   Barron Hilton claimed that since the rule was violated, he could
exercise his option to buy all the stock at $24 per share, or $163
million, its value at the time of his father's death.
   The stock today is worth about $598 million.
   To avoid the stock-ownership rule, the charitable foundation
reclassified itself as a public-support organization. Last April, a
probate judge ruled that action was proper and that the foundation
didn't need to divest itself of the stock.
   Barron Hilton appealed, resulting in Wednesday's ruling that
remanded the case to probate court to determine terms of selling
the stock to Barron Hilton, who now owns only about 4 percent of
the company.
   He said he was ``very pleased'' with the action, adding, ``It
validates the positon I have taken since my father's death, and I
regard this as a significant victory.''
   The head of hte foundation, Donald Hubbs, said he would meet
soon with the organization's directors ``to determine what action
to take, but I presume we will appeal to the California Supreme
Court.''
</TEXT>
