<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-88 2229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Farmers-Batus     03-30 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Favors Batus in Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc.'s challenge of a 19-year-old Nevada
law in its hostile $4.5 billion bid for Farmers Insurance Group was
upheld Wednesday by a judge who labeled the law unconstitutional.
   Batus has offered $63 for each of Farmers' outstanding shares.
In over-the-counter trading Wednesday, Farmers closed at $58.12{,
down $1.37{.
   U.S. District Court Judge Howard McKibben said that the law,
which allows stockholders only 60 days to decide whether to sell
their shares in a tender offer, violates the Constitution.
   Batus argued the Nevada law conflicts with the federal Williams
Act, which gives shareholders the right to participate in tender
offers at will. ``The investors ultimately suffer because they they
are required to deposit shares within the 60-day period without
complete information on regulatory approvals,'' McKibben wrote in
his ruling.
   Los Angeles-based Farmers has been resisting takeover overtures
by Batus since January. Batus is the American subsidiary of
London-based BAT Industries Inc. PLC.
   BAT is a tobacco, retailing and paper-goods conglomerate that
for some time has been seeking a foothold in the U.S. financial
services market.
   Farmers, with about $11 billion in assets, is the nation's third
largest home and auto insurer, and the seventh largest property and
casualty insurer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
